\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Single.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname date}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Year}{\xmlattrvalue 1891}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Day}
{\xmlattrvalue 18}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Month}{\xmlattrvalue 11}}}18 - November 1891{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The place where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 {\*\xmlclose}. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What part of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, it's no longer there now - it was - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Milk Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} it was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Milk Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and - I don't know what the district would be called - near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Pilkington Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now if {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Pilkingston Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s still in existence - off 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Derby Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, off {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Derby Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Can you remember how long you lived in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I was born there but we removed when I was four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you know where you moved to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, 11 - number {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}11 Rankin Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Rankin - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Rankin Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh, how many years - probably - nine
 or ten I should say - no - yes, probably going up to nine or ten but then we moved to various - various other streets near round about there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you know why it was that the family made these moves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, really - the family where I was
 born it was a back to back dwelling. There was only one room downstairs and one up and there were seven of a family and eight with myself as a baby and presumably the house was so crowded that something had to be done about it you see and my eldest siste
r - there were three boys and two girls older than, of course, I was the last to be born in the family - and presumably my eldest sister then started work in the mill. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 
At that time they could go at twelve - twelve years of age - and she - she was twelve, sh
e was twelve years my senior, and presumably her wage coming into the house, small as it was, did enable them to move to this Rankin Street which was of course a two roomed - four roomed house, two rooms up and two down which gave them more breathing spac
e you see and I presume that was the reason they - they went because for the first time they had a bit of money.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What about the other houses that you moved to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, they were all similar - two up, two down - until the war - about the war period.
 And then I had started to work by the, the other - the boys were working and consequently you could pay a better rental you see, but during - when the war came in '14 of course well then the boys were called up and the family was reduced so the girls - t
h
e three girls - the two older ones and myself decided it was high time we went into a more decent house with more sanitary conveniences - a bath - we'd never had a bath before - a bathroom and - so then we moved to Fern Street which was off Jean Road but 
it was a much better house because it had a little parlour, living room, kitchen, bathroom and two bedrooms you see. That would be about 1914 - '14/15 - in between - just when - after the war had started.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were these other houses you moved to in between better than the previous ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well they weren't better in the sense that there was still only two up, two down., no hot water - no baths or anything but of course we were a difficult family - my father was an Irishman. His people - father and moth
er - had originally come over from Ireland during the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 potato}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 famine and they had - they should - they came over in a ship that went to Liverpool with a lot of the other migrants and Liverpool had had it's quota so they were sent to Bolton and settled near 
St. Patrick's church in Great Moore Street - that was the Irish quarter then in Bolton. Dawe Street, that's gone now, that's been - removed you see - but there was an Irish colony there - Irish Catholics - and his father - my father - my grandfather and g
r
andmother went there, you see, so that I'm not sure whether he was born there or whether he came with them as a baby from Ireland you see. That's all I know about that part of it, you see. Well, now, why we had to keep moving around like this was - this i
s
 - this is rather intimate. Father of course was a heavy drinker and a heavy gambler and he scarcely ever worked. The result was that my mother had to bring us all up as we say, out of the wash-tub. She did washing for people. She also worked in the mill 
b
efore I was born but after I was born she just went washing for people or taking people washing in, and there was constant rows going on with the older boys because of father - inability to do anything, only drink and gamble, that they were constantly lea
ving him and - having to get in other houses because of the position in those days where the wife had very little protection from the law. You know, you couldn't get a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 divorce}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  unless you could prove such and such things about your husband and - consequently
 there was these constant shiftings I couldn't understand it of course, I was too young part of the time to understand why - but later on I could put two and two together and realize that this was an attempt on the part of the family to get away from fath
e
r. But the legal position, at least so I was told after mother had consulted some solicitor, and he said they could only leave the house, go elsewhere, but they'd to leave the biggest share of the furniture in the house with father's name being in the ren
t book, that was the legal position. So, of course, the thing was that they did - did this kind of thing - moved about from house to house - but they merely had to leave the bulk of the furniture in the house which was in father's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 home}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 . And the result was t
hat usually he sold most of the valuable possessions to live on and then when he was destitute they took him back, you see, which was a peculiar situation, but probably common at that time because the - the - you see, the husband's name was in the rent bo
ok and the wife really had no property in her own name. The legal position was so - so much against the - the woman so that that accounted more or less, I could }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 tell after}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  - wards, why }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  moved }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  these other houses, you see. And the last house we went into
 was probably the worst of the lot because it had no - we - we had to share an outside toilet with other people - other neighbours. In the other houses we had at least had our own toilet in the backyard but in that particular house that we stayed the long
e
st and where father died was really the - the worst house of the lot. It was up steps that had - a big cellar where the old hand loom weavers used - used to weave their - their cloths and - it had an attic but apart from that it was no better than the oth
e
r houses because there was no hot water and no bath you see. But it was, I suppose it was because they'd had to get somewhere quickly and they'd taken it and that was the house that we decided the girls - after the boys were called up for military service
 - decided that we'd had enough of it and it was about time we looked round for a - a better - better }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 accommodation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 you see and of course the three girls were working you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 This was when you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Fern Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, we moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Fern Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 then where we had the better accommodation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You said there were three brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And two sisters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What order did the boys and girls come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The elder - the eldest - no, the - the b
oy - there was one - the boy - there was a boy, John, who preceded my sister probably would be, I should say three years between the birth of the boy and the birth of this - the first sister you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was John the eldest of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 John was t
he eldest, yes. The - the sister came - Katherine - she was - twelve years older than myself, you see, so she would be - she would be born twelve years earlier than 1891. Now, the next boy was Thomas. He came after Katherine and I should say probably two 
a
nd a half to three years between them - probably two and a half I should say. And then there was - another boy called James. And there was a gap there because I believe there had been a - a child born but had died between Thomas and James there was a gap 
o
f some years. Probably six or seven I should say but there had been a - a baby that had born - been born between them and died, you see. Then there was Emily - the next girl. And I should say there would be three or four years between James and Emily. And
 then there was myself and there was two years between Emily and myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Your father came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} or he may have been born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, I never saw his birth certificate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Have you any idea how old he would be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I was sixteen when he died, I remember that very clearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How old was he when he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 He was fifty - fifty-six I think or fifty-four - fifty-six I think he was - yes, fifty-six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 His occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, it's difficult to say - I
 don't think he had one really. What I remember him doing more than anything was - they called it engine tenting in those days - looking after the engine in the cotton mill, you see, and I think he was rather good at that if he could have stuck it, you se
e
, but usually he either got drunk or - lost his temper - he was rather wild Irishman - and was nearly always out of work and then he would go labouring - caretaking at foundries at night - all night caretaking, you know, jobs like that with very little mo
n
ey attached to them. But more or less in and out of work and I don't remember him working for about the last - well I - I - he was - I was sixteen when he died and I don't remember him having a job for six years previous. I don't ever remember him - we - 
he just simply lived as part of the family but not - not working you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you know how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 I should - no, I don't really know - but I should say about forty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 She was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} - yes, her parents did live in - had lived in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} - they were dead of course when - but they had lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
. Now, her's was a peculiar and rather sad life because you see I only picked up a lot of these things when I was very, very much olde
r and I found out that - she had formerly been a child in a large family and her father had been a cotton weaver with a loom in his cellar, you see, which they had in - had had in those days and she used to tell me as a little girl about her jobs that she
 
did - around the loom you see, all the family had to work and contribute to the waving of the cloth. Now, then came the civil war - the American civil war - there's a lot of history you see in this - the American Civil War came along and - the Lancashire 
o
f course was almost dead because they couldn't get any cotton - raw cotton. You see, the war was on and there were no ships and they couldn't get any cotton. So they went through a very, very hard time and I remember her telling me about she as a little g
i
rl used to go out for jug - with a jug and got the soup you see. And - then the father died - her father died - of typhoid fever - she always said it was almost through semi-starvation and she was sent onto a servant - she was seven years of age, she neve
r
 went to school - she had no schooling at all - and she was sent onto a little farm somewhere at Lostock, just outside Bolton, for a shilling a week and her keep and she stayed there until she was old enough to go to - to work in the mill. I think she wen
t
 in at about ten or eleven. And she never learned to read or write, so that all through her life she depended on the family reading aloud to her. Father was a good reader - he had a good intelligence and he had paid for his schooling I understand at tuppe
n
ce a week at a dame school. He earned this money by the Bolton theatre at that time was in Dawe Street, near where they lived, you see, the Irish people, and he used to go as a scne shifter as a boy, scene shifting at this theater with the result that he 
earned this money - not very much - but it paid for his schooling and he was an excellent reader and of course with watching these plays he heard all the great - great actors of the time with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Shakespeare\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  plays - he had learned off by heart most of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Shakespeare\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 plays. And so as a young child we all had to sit round on little stools while father read aloud which was probably a good thing in my life you see, because I became initiated into Shakespeare before ever I went to school you see, and he was very fond of 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Dickens\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 novels and - and George Elliott and quite a lot of very, very good English literature. So that was one good part of his nature that he read aloud and then after his death I had to take the job on. Strange that the older people - older member
s of the family never tried to teach mother to read or write, you see, they were - 'course mind you she was busy - always busy working - and so consequently I was the - after father died I took on the job of reading aloud to her. I read aloud to her until
 
of course she died at the age of eighty-two and she had a very good brain and could of course - I am quite sure - she told me - I asked her once why she never - went to Sunday school because in those days they taught them in the Sunday school you see, to 
read the Bible at least. And she said she was - she used to go to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Wesleyan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 chapel in Fletcher Street, Bolton, and she was so ashamed at letting the other girls know that she couldn't read that she used to memorize the verse - they had to read a verse in
 turn - and so she used to go round the class and memorize this verse in the Bible so that when it came her turn she could recite it without them knowing that she couldn't read you see. It was a pity that she did that because probably they might have put 
h
er in the way of having some reading lessons, you see. But she didn't like to let on to the other girls who could read that she couldn't you see, and then she left when they found out. One time some other girls missed turning up or something and she was g
i
ven this girls verse and of course she had to admit she didn't know it and she couldn't read. So she was so ashamed that she left this Sunday school, you see, and never went again. But that was mother's background, but she was an ideal mother from many, m
a
ny points of view. She - she had a sound instinct for what was right and wrong and though she - her leadership in the family was gentle compared to father's - 'cos father kept a great big trap hanging up by the fireplace and if any of us were unruly of co
u
rse we got a good belt with the strap you see. But mother's was a rather quieter way and - what I respected her for was in later years she gave you the benefit of feeling that you knew what was the right thing to do and she trusted you she didn't - she wa
sn't always questioning you - where'd you'd been - how long had you stayed out - she seemed as though she had a - a kind of instinct that she knew that - she wouldn't interfere - she knew that you had some degree of reasoning }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 power}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you see and could - could
 go along without too much mothering as it were. Yes, she was a very, very fine - fine person and - I was only sorry that - after father died of course it was a great relief to us because you see, mother wasn't a catholic. He was. And he insisted on us go
i
ng to the catholic church you see - religiously - he never went himself - but we had to go you see. So we were then - I was probably about fourteen and my sister - the eldest sister - was a very intelligent person - she had already broken away from the ca
t
holic church so had the older boys and they refused - of course I wasn't old enough - the two sisters - Emily and I - the one who was two years older than myself - we were very close together you see and we had to go and - father of course was a radical -
 
utterly opposed to the Boer War - he made us all pro-Boers I can remember, because he - he didn't approve at all of the British being in Pretoria and Africa - and the result was that he made us pro-Boers and I can remember to this day the fierce battles w
e
 had in the street because we were always the Boers and of course the group were always English - the English and we used to get some terrible pastings. But father was right and we accepted it you see. And of course I was grateful for that because it's al
w
ays made me able to stand on the unpopular side - take the unpopular side, you see, it was good - it was good training really. And - then, you see, of course, we were drifting away from the catholic faith - Emily and I. My sister coming - she had then joi
n
ed the Labour party - and the - well, it was called the Independent Labour party at that time - and they had a Labour church in Bolton - they were rather strong Labour church at that time in Bolton and she used to come home telling us about the things the
y
 were doing at this Labour church which rather shocked me as a little good catholic and - I remember her telling us once that they were reading - William Morris - his News from Nowhere and John - The Dream of John Ball - and I was shocked to think that th
e
y were reading these things on a Sunday of all times - I remember putting her name - had a little prayer book and I remember putting her name in this prayer book, you see, as needing - in need of my prayers for her salvation but I'm sorry to say - or am I
 
sorry, I don't know - I - two years after - after father died we left the catholic both Emily and I and I - we joined and we've more or less been in the Socialist movement ever since. You see. So that - we're a queer family - very queer, you see, a mix up
. But - that's really the early background. Is there anything else that you - arising out of that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Your mother worked as a weaver?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, she was in the card room but that was - in the cotton mill you know. In the she wasn't a weaver - her father w
as a weaver. She used to go in - she went in the mill at - I think she was ten - about ten or eleven - so that - she - she was brought up in the card room - they went in as little card - what they called them card tenters in those days and - the - they wo
r
ked up to what they called a Jack Frame Tenter and she went into the mill and of course would progress to probably being a jack frame tenter but she never went in the mill after I was born, you see, probably because she - she'd worked in between, oh yes, 
a
nd preferred it she told me to being at home. She preferred being in the mill of course to being mithered to death by father hanging around the house, you see, not working and - she used to go out to work and then come back home and do the meals and that 
k
ind of thing. Yes, the house was always kept beautifully clean. But she did go out but it was before I was born you see, I never - I never remember going in the mill after I was born. 'Cos I used to go round with her - you see, she had these places to go 
w
ashing and as a child - a tiny little one I can remember trailing round with her to these houses and sitting on the floor amongst a pile of old dirty washing playing with things while she did the washing. So - she never - she never went back into the mill
 after I was born you see. Which I can - I can remember the hardships of it because there were no day nurseries you know, nothing of that kind then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did the children manage while she was working at the mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I think they all depended mo
re or less on Katherine - the eldest girl. She was the - she was a pivot - the pivot of the household when mother was away. Everybody turned to her you see. And I can remember almost as a little mother you see even - even when father was alive because - s
h
e had the job of bathing us, I can remember that, you see we'd no bath but used to bring a great mug on the hearthstone you see, fill it with hot water and the lads used to go out on a Friday night and she used to bath Emily and I and - do our hair - alwa
ys washed our hair and - looked after us you see, so that I should imagine that when mother was working the household turned on Katherine - you see, she was the pivot of the household - she was the elder girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did she go out to work herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh, 
yes, she worked in the mill - yes. You see, that was why they were able to leave that up and down - just the back to back dwelling because she went out to work and probably would earn - well she would probably be earning at that time about twelve shilling
s
 a week which was a fairly good sum. So presumably when they got this income - this added income of her wages they would feel they could then afford a rent - a - a better rental than they were paying for this back to back dwelling, you see. Yes, she worke
d
 in the mill until the - well, probably before the - first world ward - and she hated the mill. Mother like it - she hated it. With the result that when she became more capable of sorting things out she decided to go into be trained for a nurse - she alwa
y
s wanted to be a nurse. And so - she went to a hospital - this would be about 1914 because they were then calling on girls to go to be trained for nursing - and she went to a children's hospital at Pendleton and took some training there as a nurse. And th
en I remember from that she got a post under the insurance act with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southport{\*\xmlclose}. I know she left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}, she left home and went to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southport{\*\xmlclose} for a few years during the early years of the war and then she went in for training midwifery and she passed her examinations and she became the first nurse at the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}
 - the they called it in those days the child welfare. The child welfare - it was a voluntary organisation started by Miss Reddish and a few enlightened ladies in the town - I think they were mainly Liber
als, enlightened ladies, and they started this babies welcome in a house in St George's Road, because of course the - the - the - the country was being decimated by the lads that were being killed you see and there was that urge coming forward that they s
hould look after their babies. So she then got the post and she remained in that post - she was very, very happy in it because it was the first time she'd ever really done what she wanted - until she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13978893 Married
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The house you lived in longest would be the one in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Rankin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 That was the longest period, yes, yes, that was the longest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters and yourself live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh no, there was no room. You see there were only two bedrooms and 
the division was mother and the girls slept in the front room and father slept in the back room with the boys and that was the arrangement and we never could have anyone staying with us because of course there was no room. We suffered - we suffered I thin
k by - we were never really hospitable because we never could afford it you see through this poverty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Obviously your mother wouldn't be able to pay anybody to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would she have to make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 S
he mended and darned - I don't think she was very good at making things but she did mend and darn tremendously because you see she'd always the bed linen to be repairing - we never could afford new bed linen so they were always patched. And I can remember
 
when father was - these evening when father read aloud she was always sewing - sewing and patching. I remember the stocking darning that she did for the boys - it was tremendous - she never seemed to have anything in her hand but darning - darning socks y
o
u see, mending clothes. She didn't make many new ones but what - well, we never did have - I don't remember having a new frock until I was about fifteen years old. I always had to wear the other two girl's cut down. And - several times I've been accused o
f spending money on clothes but it was because I was denied so much in childhood that it made me - I thought well if ever I get enough any loose money it'll go on some nice clothes because you see I - I must have gone to school looking like }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Josephs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  coat of 
many colours because everything was patched, you see. I'd have the bottom part of a frock would be part of somebody else's - the sleeves would be a different colour, be out of something else, and altogether I - I must have looked a little queer - queer ch
ild you see. But that was the set-up - we'd no money - mother would never go in debt and consequently she - what she could patch up - and then Kathy - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Katherine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  - when she got older she did help to make pinafores and things like that you see that covered up
 this coat of many colours as it was you see, but certainly we never had any new things and if anything did come in at all it was for the boys - the boys were always kept - if there were any new clothes the boys had to have them. And I can always remember
 
the elder boy, John, you see, the eldest one - he used to have one good suit and the neighbourhood used to borrow it because they used to come knocking on the door - they were all as poor as each other you see - and he used to - to come - John came knocki
n
g on the door - can I borrow your John's suit. And if it was for a wedding or a funeral it was cheerfully handed round you see and this suit then came back you see. But that was the - that was the community life if you see. And things that did come in as 
I say - they were bought cheaply from the pawnshop - there was a pawnshop not very far away and mother went to the pawn shop every Monday morning - can remember as a small child going to the pawnshop and - if the pawnbroker had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 anything}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you see that had nev
er been redeemed he would sell then cheap to - to her, you see. So that new things - no, I never remember any new things coming in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would this apply to shoes as well as other kinds of clothing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, we wore clogs of course, it was the age of
 clogs and - only the boys wore shoes you see and my eldest sister when, of course, she was going out anywhere. But we, Emily and I, the two younger, always wore clogs and we had a - a very cheap pair of shoes for Sunday. Either secondhand that were broug
h
t from - the secondhand dealer or perhaps a very cheap new pair that might cost about two and eleven in those days you see so that - and father - I will say that for him - he did mend shoes - if the boys shoes wanted mending he would mend them. And he had
 
a habit - a trick - we used to take the clogs to the cloggers to be ironed - you know, they had irons on the bottom, and there was a cloggers shop just near and of course it was a social event to us as children taking these clogs to the well, they were on
 
our feet. But we used to sit on a very long form in a very dark shop and watch the man - well, there'd be two men - putting the irons on the clogs. You see, they used to put the - all the nails in their mouth and - hammer them in from the mouth - it was -
 
it was a - it was a feat - I used to be fascinated with it and - but father when we'd got these new irons on he'd an irritating habit of putting leather - pieces of leather inside the - inside the frame of the iron so that they would last longer, you see 
again poverty. And I hated it because you see we used to kick our clogs against the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 sidestep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 and sparks used to fly out and this was a real game and - but when you'd got this leather in between you couldn't - there was no spark. And I always felt a morsel o
f resentment against father for putting these leather linings in you see. Yes, it applied to shoes - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did he do anything else at all in the house to help your mother?
