cleaned the windows. I can remember mother cleaning the windows and Kathy - the - the eldest girl cleaning windows - sit out on the window ledges you know, that kind of thing. No, he was a big reader and - but he spent a lot of time backing horses. And he
 
had - to this day I can remember piles and piles of sporting handicaps - that was a book you see, little book that the sporting world published with all the horses and all the races and he used to spend hours picking out what he thought were winners - he 
h
ardly ever won but - that was part of his occupation you see, until the pubs opened. But he was a solitary drinker. The worst type of drinker. I don't remember him going sitting in pubs - drinking. He used to have it all brought into the house you see, an
d I as a little girl was the constant person until the act was passed and then children }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 were not}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 allowed to go. But up 'til the act being passed I used to be the beer carrier - can always remember going with jugs for the beer you see and he would sit there 
hours with this jug of beer ruminating about horses and one thing and another. It was a tragic - a tragic man because he had the intelligence you see to have become something really. But that was it. No, I don't remember him helping in the house. No.

