ld fashioned fireplaces. And they used to rake the bottom - get the bottom red - and then they would pile coal on and then cinders right on so that it kept in, because you see, you must remember that they had to get up at five o'clock. And, I can always r
e
member this - this business - raking - they called it raking the fire - I can always remember it. So the result was that the fire kept in and mother merely raked all the dead ashes and cinders out the following morning but it was never re-set, you know ho
w
 I mean, like they do now with chips don't they - in fact I don't remember firewood at all - I don't know really how they lit - how they lit it when the fire went out, suppose they would have firewood but out fire always seemed to be in you see. And she w
o
uld rake it out in the morning and then clean all the ashes and then clean the hearthstone - polish the fire irons and then towards the weekend they were always lifted up and put onto the couch so that they had to be kept nice and clean for Saturday after
noon, you see, when they were put down again. No, and he had no hobbies which was - again - lacking no gardening you see, there was no gardens of course. Most of the - quite a number of the fellow - the parents round about had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
