He was - he was anti-English all the time and of course, an Irishman and he got - he got somehow or other embroiled in the - round about - you know - home rule for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and Fenian movement and he used to spend a lot of his time with other Irishmen meeting in different houses. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Now what they were plotting or doing I - I 
was too young to know but I do remember this that we had a big - a - a huge box that was kept under the bed - under one of the beds and mother said it was full of firearms. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 
Now, that must have been about the time of the Fijian rising because he would go aw
ay for months at a time, we were always rather glad when he went, and we never knew where he was but he must have been propa - prop - doing propaganda work for the Irish because he would come back with no voice at all - lost his voice completely and - wit
h
 shouting I suppose and - so mother was so incensed about this that - because he - he used to come back in a terrible dilapidated condition and I can remember him lying on the rug so exhausted that we left him downstairs lay - lay on the rug and mother sa
id she'd got so tired of it all that - so she threatened him that if he didn't leave this Irish body whatever it was - home rulers - she would tell the police about these firearms because it was of course prohibited. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And it frightened him, so with that - I 
don't know what happened to them, where they went to or whether - what - but it was so that the box was emptied and - but it - it prayed on his mind because I think the men who'd been associating with then thought he was a traitor to the cause because he 
became more and more silent - more and more shut in within himself - probably the one outlet that he had had gone, you see, and that - that - that arrangement whatever it was ceased and he was never quite the same man after. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Everything seemed - his world ha
d collapsed you see, what little world he had it had collapsed to that what happened to that part of it I really don't know but he was a great believer in Ireland he always - his toast was we'll curse - we'll curse the English for the Irish Archers, I can
 always remember that before he drank his beer - that was his toast you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 So he was - it was a strange - a strange man and a strange father and - I've }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 tried}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  to - tried to be very just to him because I realise that probably he'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13978893 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  the wrong woman and she - my mother had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13978893 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 the wrong man. Because she couldn't sympathise with the things that he sympathised with and he couldn't enter at all into her world you see. So that it had its effects I suppose on all the members of the family because we're a
