th his drinking - I was his favourite be - being the last you see, the youngest and not knowing anything - of course I - I loved him passionately as a child. Largely because of his reading and his stories - he could tell - oh, his fairy tales were wonderf
u
l you know, the Irish fairy tales and I was thrilled to bits you see about it all, and Sunday mornings he would take - he would go out for a walk and he would take me with him but it was only later on that I realized why because he had to go the three mil
e limit to get to a pub to drink you see. So that was the only time I ever got to see the country and we would walk from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} to Horwich you see so he could get a - a pub you see, or 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} to Turton you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 And I would sit outside in a little bowling gr
een watching the men bowl while he went inside you see and had his - had his beer. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
But that - those are the only things that I can remember him taking us to. Concerts - no, we never got any concerts. The fairground - yes. I can remember him on new year's m
orning always taking us - Emily and I - to the fairground and he would - try his luck on the stalls, you know, the three balls a penny thing and if he won - we liked coconut - there were coconuts for the prize you see - knocking the coconuts. And of cours
e
 if he won we would have these coconuts under our arm. No, I don't remember him - only those things stand out - going on the fairground you see, and if he didn't win - he was a bad loser - and he would start having an argument with the stallholder and we 
t
wo children were terrified you see because we - we felt they were creating a row you see and the police might come and I can remember struggling to pull him away from the stall you see, to take him away. Then when we got to the - shows, where the tightrop
e
