m
. He never went to concerts, never went to church and seemed to take very little interest in our schooling apart from one thing which I was grateful for - he did not believe in the half time system and although we were wretchedly poor he would not allow m
e - allow Emily or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 to go half time. I was grateful for that because most of the girls who lived in the same street always went half time you see in those days and - when I was at school I can remember the girls who were - who were on the half time system
 you see they would start work at six o'clock in the morning then they had to go to school in the afternoon. Well they were so tired they'd just fall asleep and the teacher being sympathetic wouldn't waken them you see so they got very little schooling. W
e
ll I will say that for father he - he definitely refused that - that either Emily or I should go half time you see so at least I left school at thirteen but it was better than going half time at twelve see. That was one of the things - his principles were
 
right - his principles were - were often very right - he was a Socialist and - but it was his inability to - to kind of put his principles into practice - he - he didn't seem to have the - either the character - they staying power to put his principles - 
i
nto practice. Now I'm not saying that was all his fault because the other members of the family were terribly opposed to him. There was always this friction, you see there was always rows going on - always. As a child I used to be terrified. In fact mothe
r
 once said that she wondered that I'd grown up without heart disease because there was these constant - see, as the boys got older they would not submit, you see, and he would be drunk and there would be terrible fights and I used to go out in the street 
s
creaming you see, I was terrified and I'd - other neighbours would take me in you see and keep me in their house until they thought this - you know the squabble had died down. And - it really - in many respects it was - it was pretty awful and yet I think
 
if there'd been somebody that could have perhaps talked to him and reasoned with him instead of the - they were - antagonistic all the time. My sister never - the elder one - never had a good word for him because one of the things he did was when he was o
n
ce hard up he stole our holiday money and she never forgave him. It was terrible thing to do because she was working very, very hard - she never had a holiday in her life - she would probably be twenty-two - twenty-two or three then and she'd made arrange
m
ents to go up to the Lake District with a - a - another friend from the mill and she'd been saving in this money box and he broke it open and stole it. She never - she never forgave him. There was a terrible bitterness about it. And this was the atmospher
e
 you see. It was - it was really a - it was a tragic - and yet mother kept calm through it all. Now when I would come back from the - wherever I'd been - finding shelter, I'd find her - he would up - father would have gone upstairs to bed and she would be
 bandaging them - the cut heads and black eyes and she would be sweeping up the debris - he'd smash everything - we had a great big poker and I know he used to go round with this poker smashing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
