e train only went to Manchester, and when they got off it was midnight - past midnight and they walked to Bolton, this was the story. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Mother and Emily carrying - no, Emily was only two - it was Kathy and Emily and mother. And Kathy and Mother carried Emily 
between them to Bolton - walking twelve miles and they got to Bolton at about something early in the morning - six or seven in the morning and mother collapsed on the couch and I was born premature you see. And - mother never forgot that and so she was al
ways kind to anybody that came to the door. She would never - she knew what destitution was you see. And so she always - she never told me - I never heard anything of this until - oh my sister was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13978893 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and then she said one time, well I'll tell you about
 how you were born. So I wasn't expected to live being a premature baby. So I was - my sister - now that was - my father never came in - she carried me as a tiny baby down to St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Patrick's}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  church to be baptized. He insisted on baptism but didn't go. And I'd
 neither godfather, godmother nor anybody else and the priest was just finishing benedictions she said and he came down the steps and asked why this child - she was only a child herself, twelve you see - was carrying this tiny baby. And she said, well, we
l
