e she would buy a little bit of meat for herself - it would be probably in a mince - the mince meat you see and she would make something out of this mincemeat and she'd put a bit on my plate and I can remember to this day looking at it and saying but mumm
y
 it - it's a fast day. And she used to say - get it down thee neck, you see she talked - she spoke broad Lancashire. Get it down the neck and give oe'r - give oe'r mathering. And so I used to eat this meat. The result was I always had to confess it. And t
h
at terrified me going into the confessional box - having to confess, you see, that I'd eaten meat on a Friday. And - tea was peculiar because I can remember coming home from school and we had to stand round the table we never had any chairs to sit on roun
d
 the table, we had to stand, and there was no talking if father was there. Mum - you'd to be mum. And whatever she cooked they shared. Now this I think must have been the Irish in him you see, because other people didn't. But they just had one plate - fat
h
er and mother - and shared it and I can remember sometimes it would be one sausage and sometimes it would be a tiny bit of meat and onions - something like that. But he got the biggest share of it because she used to cook what bits she had up and give it 
to us as a treat. Just a little bit on the end of a fork, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 So that she would go without?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
She would go without - oh yes, she did, definitely - yes. Because - there was so there was so little and - father would take the biggest share of it
 you see - he would have a knife and he would cut his share and then she would be cutting what was - what was - the remains and just handing it to us you see, a little bit at a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have plates?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Just occasionally - not often 3/8 no. The
y would just give it us on the end of a fork and we'd put it in our mouth and that was that you see. We had bread - bread and margarine of course - mother baked - she baked her own bread and I can always remember baking days - they were lovely. And she us
e
d to bake a lot of what we called plain flour cakes - you know the plain flour cake - and put them against the door to cool - against the door jamb you know. And they were lovely and all fresh cakes - not often butter - just occasionally butter - but most
l
y margarine - it used to be lovely. And we had black treacle I remember and - never syrup because I often wonder - but syrup of course was dearer you see. And I used to go with a cup to the end shop for a pennyworth of black treacle and I was always fasci
n
ated because they weighted the cup, you know, they weighed the cup first - and I used to wonder why - why they put the cup - the empty cup on the scale you see. So we got this pennyworth of black treacle and then we could put that on our bread you see. Br
e
akfast time I remember nothing only porridge and just - just bread. Father was very fond of porridge and so there was always a big pan of porridge made and - we had milk - milk wasn't dear in those days. And so we had a - a - a - a - we didn't have plates
 
- we had a bowl of porridge. Basins we called them in those days, and we each had a basin and you got this porridge put in and then you got a sprinkling of sugar and then the milk on and you ate it that way and then just a - a thick slice of bread - we us
ed to call them butties. And - but no luxuries at all - can't remember any luxuries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You never had bacon for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh no. I never remember - no, no, I never remember. Bacon must have been a real luxury because I don't even remember them havi
ng it - my father and mother - although it's possible that occasionally they did because when I was about six I used to go to a lady's house who was a little bit higher up than us and she had she had one or two babies. She was a Welsh girl and - she used 
t
o send me to this end shop - her husband was a cotton worker but only getting fourteen shillings a week - he was a little side piecer - so she had hard work with these children you see, and she used to send me for two pennyworth of bacon and cheese. And t
h
ey used to give you a little bit of bacon and a bit of cheese for the tuppence. Or twopennyworth of sausage - never had - never was more than tuppence I remember that. Twopennyworth of sausage and cheese. Perhaps one egg - something like that. And - I use
d
 to watch her cooking it and - you see, it was an open fire and they had a kind of a thing that hung on the bars and they put this - skewered the bacon on - a piece of bacon and they had a dish underneath and it caught the - we called it dip, you know, th
e
 fat dripping and it always used to smell so good and I used to think ooh I wish we could have that. We never had it you see, it must have been a bit of a luxury - but she got it for tuppence you see. And I don't remember - I don't remember much - much va
riety in our diet - jam occasionally jam - or this black treacle.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 That would be for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Tea - yes. And marmalade at - at - I never tasted marmalade until I was about seven or eight and then I remember one of the neighbours sending me for a pot 
of marmalade and when I came back she said - would you like a bit on a buttie? And I said yes. And then I didn't like it because it was a bit bitter and I'd never had it before. I came of course to love marmalade later on. But those were things - bananas 
we never had - bananas were just beginning to come into the country. Bananas were strange to us - tomatoes I never had. I remember the lady next door giving me the first foreign tomato and thinking how horrible it was because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 we were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  never accustomed to any
thing like that. We used to have a bit of lettuce because it was very cheap - we used to go for a pennyworth to the gardens and they would give us, ooh, tons of lettuce and - stick of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 rhubarb
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and mint and quite a lot of things for a penny, you see. We used
 to have it tied up in a - in a handkerchief. That kind of thing we had. The only time I can remember any luxury at all would be on Christmas Eve. And mother went out of her way to make a special kind of function because it was Christmas Eve. And there sh
e
 would cook some meat in the oven which was always very nice and tender and - she used to bake - in addition to just bread and cakes - she would bake currant bread and a few scones and things like that. And I always used to look forward to it because it w
as such a treat to have these extras, you see, compared to the bare diet that we had during the week you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You didn't make a practice of having anything special on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, apart from mother baking - she used to bake what was called curran
t flat cake-flat cake now - well, she used to bake that at weekend and we had that for tea. But it was a long time before ever we got any tinned fruit or anything of that kind - that was sort of out - outside }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 our}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  means, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 And - oh fruit pies - occas
ionally she would make an apple pie - special for Sunday or a Whinberry pie something like that you see which I can always remember that going out with all my lips blue to show the kids that we'd had whinberry pie you see.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would that be for dinner or for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh no, tea, that was tea - yes. Sunday dinner was always the same - always. I never remember anything only this broth. We always had this, you know, scotch broth. It 3/8 mind you it was very good because she used to put little dumplings in a
nd it made it very, very tasty - tasty meal. But I don't remember - ever having, you know, a joint or anything like chops - no, I never remember chops. And - it was very - very meager. And we didn't have cups and saucers until Kathy - that was the eldest 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 sister}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 - decided we were going to go a bit polite. We had basins and we used to drink the tea out of these basins, you see. Well, then she decided that it was about time we had some refine - refinement - so she bought a set of cups and saucers and I know - 
I can remember how delighted it was with these cups and saucers - thought how fine we were you see. And it was the same with curtains - we never had any long curtains - we had short curtains - you know - short lace curtains. They are fashionable now but t
h
ey were for the poor in those days. And I can always remember making a promise to mother - the first wage I fetch home, mummy, I'm going to buy a pair of long curtains. And she said - are you? And I said yes. And I remember the first wage I ever got was f
o
ur and eleven and I called at a drapers shop on the way home and I bought these four and eleven - they were four and eleven - the exact wage you see - and they were long curtains. Oh, I was thrilled to bits. The idea that for first time in our lives we'd 
got a pair of long lace curtains you see. Yes. Yes. I - I remember a lot of those things - they stand out you see. But food was very, very frugal - very frugal in those days - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Apart from your special Christmas Eve food did you have a special Christmas dinner?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
I never remember any turkey or anything of that kind - no. Just occasionally mother would buy a piece of pork for new years day or Christmas Day and she would cook this pork which was, of course, we appreciated it very much because it w
as something new you see, and she would make stuffing and that kind of thing. But I never remember Christmas pudding - never remember any Christmas pudding until I got much older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you used to have puddings at dinner time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well mother used to
 make some kind of a pudding - that - I know had currants and raisins in. I don't know what sort of - it was a whitish kind of a pudding that she made in a big dish. There was a lot of flour, you know, probably a lot of flour and then some fruit put in - 
c
urrants and raisins and we used to have a kind of a slice of that for a sweet sometimes you see. But that - that was - she never - I wouldn't say that she was an imaginative cook because she'd never any time you see and she'd never learned anything becaus
e
 my sister - the eldest sister - she got very finicky about food and she used to say - mother never could cook - mother never could cook. But then she'd so little to cook with. But I - I didn't really blame her, but my sister was very finicky. And I can r
e
member when I got old enough I had to take her dinner to the mill and - mother used to be at her wits end what to put up for her because she had - a bad digestion and she hated the mill and she was rather a melancholy type of person and so you - sometimes
 mother would make - she was very good on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 potatoes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 pies, you know, the Lancashire diet - she was good on that, And so she would make a potato pie and so she would scoop some out and put it in a basin, cover it over and tie it up to keep it warm, you see, pu
t it in a basket and I had to carry this to the mill. Well, when I got there of course the meal break was on - the hour meal break - and all the machinery would be stopped and I would have to weave my way through - through all this machinery to find her. 
A
nd by that time she would have washed herself - she was very, very particular about her appearance - she would have washed herself. And you see, there were no canteens or anything and they used to have to sit having their meals behind the machinery and so
 
she would be on a little roller sit reading a newspaper about three of them shared a newspaper - the intelligent ones - you see, shared a newspaper. And she would be reading this newspaper and she would open this potato pie and on her - the look of disdai
n
 on her face, you see, I remember it yet, and I suppose in a hot stuffy mill it would be awful, you know, eating potato - hot potato pie and I used to be anxiously watching that she would leave some in the dish because she was a poor eater and I was hungr
y
. You see, with having been at school, had nothing to eat, gone right on, and so usually she used to leave about half of it, so I could then scoff it up you see. And - she would just have a jar - oh, a can of tea I used to take - a can of tea with me and 
s
he would have a drink of this tea you see. And we would remain silent most of the time - she didn't talk much. She never told me much about the mill although I knew how intensely she hated it and then she would just say it's about time you started going b
a
ck if you're going back to school. And so then I had to pick the empty things up and then to back to school you see, for half past one. But later on when she got that she'd more control - especially after father died - of course, she did start introducing
 
things into the house you see. And - mother would never have an alarm clock you see, we had a knocker up who used to come knocking on the windows as you know at five o'clock in the morning, and he was an elderly man and Kath - Kathy wanted to buy an alarm
 
clock but mother wouldn't have it. No, she said, he - he'd been coming all those years - thirty odd years or something and he would - she would keep on with him and it was only about threepence a week, you know, that we paid him - until he died you see. W
e
ll, the alarm clocks came in and they did - did away with the old knocker ups you see. But mother was very loyal to him and never would have the alarm clock. And she was the same with an egg boiler - she wouldn't have an egg boiler. She used to boil eggs 
y
ou know, silently counting sixty - sixty seconds to the minute and we all used to laugh at her and the boys especially used to try to joke her out of it and - but she would sit there solidly you know, rocking in the rocking chair with this egg boiling you
 
know on the fire and she'd count - they would try to break her off it you know - telling her all sorts of funny things - but she used to have a face like one of the - you know pharaohs monuments and she'd count her - the egg was done to a turn. Anyway Kat
hy bought - brought home an egg boiler from one of her holidays but mother never - never had anything of it. She didn't think they were boiled as well as they were with counting sixties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The people who went to work would get up about five o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would they have their breakfast on their own and then the rest of you get up later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Yes. I used to - you see, with being in the same room as Kathy, she had to get up you see and I used to hear her of course, I used to hear the man knocki
ng on the - tapping on the windows you see, with these wires and in winter feeling how lovely it was not to have to get out of a warm bed you see. And Kathy would go down - dress herself and go downstairs you see. Well, this was a horrible custom but it w
a
s the custom. They used to put a great big - ooh, tremendous tea pot full of tea in the oven before they went to bed and that tea was warm then, you see, in the morning - it was always black. And they used to cut their own bread and - get this tea out - t
h
is teapot out of the oven you see, and have this warm tea and then off to work, you see. Well, when I had to get up, of course, I began to realise how awful it was. Getting - getting out of bed you see at five o'clock in the morning - I hated it too. And 
-
 but Kathy was - think she was singular in that she - the - they must have been having a hygiene class at the Labour church and she came home full of cold baths. Well we had no bath so it fell to my lot, being the youngest, to fill this bath tin every nig
h
t and carry - well, I used to carry the water upstairs - the bath tin was upstairs - and I would carry buckets of water and mother used to say - oh, you're too full - oh she used to say some funny things to us. Oh, she used to call me a silly bitch. She s
a
id - you're two silly bitches because she was watching all this water drip up the stairs you see, out of the bucket. And I'd fill - fill this bath tin with cold water and then I would wait and Kathy would get up and I'd hear her gasping and splashing you 
k
now, and - then rubbing herself and the bed used to shake you know, and I used to think, oh, I wonder if I - if ever I'll be able to do that, you know. And it carried on for years, this business of carting this cold water - that was well, determined us th
a
t when the boys were called up we would get to a place where there was a bath you see because it was such a lot of trouble because I had to fetch it down, empty the dirty - the water out and I'd started following her you see. After she'd gone she'd leave 
t
he water in so when I got up I used to do this cold - absolution, and it was funny. But there were - there's some queer things about it - I never liked getting up at five o'clock in the morning. I never liked this horrible black tea that came out of the o
ven, you know. And all that it was - pretty awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When you were a child you got up later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Later - yes. And we had our breakfast - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And who would there be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, there would only be Emily and I and mother and father, you
 see. And often father wouldn't get up if - especially if he'd had a bit of a spree, you know, the night before. So usually there were just the three of us - mother and Emily and I and we had this, as I say, this porridge and this bread and marge and then
 of course, we went off to school when we'd started going to school, and if before I went to school of course I used to go with mother to all these places where she did her - did the washing you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 About what time did you get up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I should
 say probably about half past seven to eight. Never later than eight - eight o'clock - no. We never were late - we were always taught to be punctual - punctuality was one of the things that father did insist on and we never went late to school and we - I 
don't think we were ever late anywhere we were going we erred on the early side, you see, we were packed off pretty early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 At dinner times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, we came home to dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would everybody apart from Emily come home for dinner?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. Kathy 
stayed in the mill, you see, Kathy stayed in the mill. And - but the boys came home because they - they were working at different places apart perhaps from the elder boy, John, might not have always come home. But most of them did - the other two did. And
 - we more or less had our dinner together, you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you always have the same places round the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, no, I wouldn't say we all - it was rather a scramble as to who got there first you see, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 This would be standing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Yes, to standing up - yes. Until the boys got older and they then wouldn't stand up so they used to drag a chair up to the table, you see, but I as a child I don't ever remember sitting at the table. Until I - I got much older of course. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When you were very little would your mother take you on her knee do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
I don't remember a great deal of love - no. She wasn't - she wasn't demonstrative at all and I don't remember kissing her a great deal or her kissing me. I don't think she wanted
 children you see - I don't really think she wanted children and father now he was sentimental and I would kiss him and hug him and put me arms round his neck because he was - he was the emotional one but not mother. No, I don't - I don't remember a great
 deal of - patting and petting and that kind of thing you know. No, I don't - I don't really remember. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you feel that you were close enough to be able to confide in her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, I was an in - I was a - I was - we were all inhibited. I don't re
member ever - ever really confiding - just occasionally I would say things but she - she - rather queer. I remember once when I'd started to go to school we all got punished for something we hadn't done. Somebody had done something in the class. I don't k
now what it was, and the teacher came round and caned us all. And I was so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 incensed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 about this that I couldn't give over sobbing and I came home from school almost broken hearted - not at the actual caning but at the indignity you see, it was the indignity.
 And I remember trying to tell mother about this feeling, you see, but she just simply shrugged it off and she just said - oh, well you must have deserved it. You see, must have deserved it. And I don't remember that I ever did confide a great deal in her
.
 For one thing I think she left us to make our own judgements. Occasionally, you see, I would say - well, what would you do? And she would say - now please yourself, you've had you've had - you've had the education I didn't have, you ought to know what to
 
do. That was her attitude. Rather than saying well, let's sit down and talk about it - she never seemed to have time to talk, you know, she wasn't a talker really although people liked her - they always used to say she's a good sort is your mother. And bu
t in the home no, she didn't - she didn't talk much. I only remember once, we were all reading and - I used to have to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 person who read to library - went down this scale see - the older ones did it then it dropped to me. And every Monday night I had t
o go take a bag of books to Bolton Library and change them, because everybody had a book out. Father would have a book, the lads would have books, Kathy, Emily and myself. And I used to go and change these books and it wasn't an easy system because you di
d
n't - you didn't have open libraries then you know you had to go to the counter and look whether it was in or out. Yes. And I used to spend a lot of time and - you were not allowed in the reading room - children weren't you know. And occasionally I would 
sneak up into the room but me clogs always gave me away on the stairs you see, and I'd just picked a nice picture book - a magazine - when the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 caretaker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  would come in and shoo me out, you know, like a blinking animal. And I always think about it now, how lu
cky the children are to be able to go in the libraries. And anyway, I came home with all these books, well everybody started looking whether this was the book they wanted because often I'd to get other books if they weren't in and my choice would probably
 not be theirs and so everybody was - you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 
And they'd all started reading and mother was sitting there and then all at once - I shall never forget it - she jumped up and she says quite angrily - it was very rare she was angry - she said, I might as well
 go out - it's nought but a deaf and dumb school. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
And - I though to myself - deaf and dumb school - so I just said - you know, well would you like me read you a bit of this - my book. And she said - what is it? I says - it's Alice in Wonderland, I says let
s follow Alice in Wonderland. And do you know, she was wrapped in that - wrapped up in that book and it was the one book that she asked me to read before she died. Strange wasn't it? Yes. I said mother would you .....
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was that the first time you had read to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh no. I read to her many times but that happened to be the book you see. And says I we'll have that. No, she used to like love tales. And I used to get, ooh, quite a lot of very - you know, would we call them very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 romantic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  now. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Oh she l
iked Hall Caine - I used to read Hall Caine's Eternal City and things like that to her and - but she got quite interested in this Alice in Wonderland, you know, about her going down this hole, you know, and I had to read it all through to her and - of cou
rse that was - she liked that type of imaginative - I suppose it - it did something inside her you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
But she would like - she would like novels and when I used to get to hard words that I couldn't say she used to get quite impatient and I used to be stru
ggling over this big long word - she used to say - call it Manchester. And so it would be Manchester, And then - you know it was rather funny, but it made me a good reader. Made me a good reader. I was best reader in the class at school - I - I was always
 
being called on to do the reading especially if the inspector was there. But - she - yes - she was strange that way. But confide in her - no, I wouldn't say - and I was a child that was very I don't remember confiding in people - even the teacher - I was 
a
lways shy, terribly shy. And we had - we had several pictures - I can remember to this day these old pictures that we had on the wall and never would ask what they meant and I used to climb - when the - when the house was quiet and empty I would climb on 
a
 - on a chair and I would be looking at these pictures trying to make out what they were - who they were, and it was years before I really tumbled to what one of the pictures was. And I used to look at this figure - these figures, you know, and I could ha
v
e asked you see but I was never encouraged to ask somehow or other and then quite suddenly at school we were given the story of the prodigal son and it flashed on me like that that this was the prodigal son. I could see these figures draped in these cloth
e
s you see and the old man coming forward and the penitent kneeling down and then - somebody that looked like an angel but it wasn't an angel it was a - bringing a cloak out to put - and it took me I don't know how long to fathom this picture - and then al
l
 at once - yes, the story of the prodigal son and I raced home that day and - oh, I thought it was wonderful - I thought I'd achieved something marvellous to have realised it on my own what it was. And I can remember a lot of that - I never did - never co
n
fided in the teachers - never told them anything and - I missed a lot through it - I missed an awful lot through it but - I suppose that was part of our inheritance. We all were the same. We never confided in each other. Emily used to say to me later on i
n life, she used to say, wasn't it funny that we never could talk to each other? And I said, yes, it was queer - no, we never could talk to each other. So there wasn't much communication - no, there wasn't much communication.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were you allowed to talk when the grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh no. No. No, you see very early was embued the idea that you were a listener - you had to be a listener and we were all good listeners - I am today, I can listen easily. But never a very good talker especially if oth
er people were talking. And - no, we never were - never really encouraged. We were just encouraged to be listeners you see. Like the old saying you know, you have to be seen and not heard. It was very prevalent in our family. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 That's why I marvel at the chi
ldren today you know, how the parents allow them to - the - they - they interrupt on all sorts of occasions don't they and they never - hardly ever are chastised but oh, we were - very severely. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 If we spoke out of turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Which room did the family have their meals in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Yes, well, of course there was only one room in which you could have it - that was the living room. Because it was just a living room with a kitchen behind you see which was a very dull place compared to the living room you see, so th
at all the cooking was done on the fire - it wasn't really a - couldn't call it a kitchen range but it was just a fire with an oven - fireplace with an oven - and - and the - all the cooking was done on the open fire you see, boiling or braising or cookin
g in the oven.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 This was in the living room as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 In the living room - oh yes, it all had to be done in the living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You said your mother was not an imaginative cook but she did bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did she do anything like making jam or preserving fruit or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No. No, that seemed to be out of her range. What jam we had it was bought in very small quantities you see and the same with pickles and - they were just bought - pickles you see, and of cour
se she'd no knowledge whatever of wines or medicines - she had no knowledge. She didn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 She didn't concoct anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, she didn't - oh, well now, perhaps I ought to qualify that because father did brew herbs and of course mother helped him. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Sarsaparilla}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 herbs and dandelion wine - that was one his perhaps hobbies. At a certain part of the year he used to go out and collect dandelion roots and - make dandelion wine and also herb beer. We called it herb beer - it was really kind of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 sarsaparilla}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  
you know. And he used to make that in the kitchen - in the back kitchen, I mean, not the living room - the kitchen. And bottles - they used to bottle it you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 This would be a lengthy process?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh it was because you see it had to have balm
 in, you know, yeast and then it had to be allowed to ripen - ripen, you see, so that it was a - a rather long process yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You said your mother allowed you to eat meat on Fridays because you didn't like fish - apart from that could you choose what yo
u wanted to eat from what was available or did you have to eat a bit of everything that was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, there wasn't much choice - no. It was a question of it was put before you and you either ate it or left it. There wasn't much coddling, you know
, as there is today, asking a child does it like this does it like that - it wasn't - it wasn't a problem at all. The problem only arose for me - I was the only member of the family that intensely disliked fish and mother was not bound by her religion not
 to eat meat on Friday so I shared with her whatever she managed to cook unless of course, as I told you, before she gave me a penny then I went out for a bun. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 If you did leave food uneaten on the plate - you didn't always have plates did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, we didn't. At dinner of course we did have because you had to eat off a plate. Dinner we did have plates. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 If you did leave something uneaten what was the attitude?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Well, of course, you - you got scolded, you see, as to why you were w
asting good food, and usually we managed to dodge a little bit by - we always had a cat - by surreptitiously letting the cat eat at least some of it up for us you see, to avoid getting into too much hot water.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You said meal times were something of a s
cramble but if there was something on the table that you wanted that was out of reach, like the salt, could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I'm afraid our manners were not very cultivated and I'm 
afraid it was a case of stretching over and grabbing it rather than any more polite motives.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were there such things as second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, there were - you could have second helpings if there was anything left in the main dish, you see. Moth
er would cook whatever there was and bring the dish onto the table - give everybody a helping from the dish, you see, and there did happen to be any - anything left over, well usually the boys got it because they were the hungry section of the family you 
see, and usually the boys got it rather than the girls you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was there any formality attached to your leaving the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, I'm afraid there wasn't. I'm afraid there was no such things as may I leave the table, you see, it was just kind of - 
people were coming in from the mill, coming in from the - their work and the boys were coming in you see different times - people just went - members just went to the table - got what was available and then just as hurriedly disappeared either to go and w
ash them - selves or read or something of that kind. There was no formality about - really about either coming to the table or leaving it. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Ye
s, I think mother did. I think mother was a quiet but very effective person in giving us at quiet an early age a sense of responsibility because I can remember when I was quite small having to do certain jobs in the house you see - we all had to do someth
i
ng. For instance, the boys had to chop wood and bring coal in. And my sister - the elder sister, Kathy - helped with the sewing and always with the ironing after washing. She did all the ironing you see. And I remember my first job was looking after the -
 
the W.C. - well, it wasn't a WC really - at the bottom of the yard. You see, you had to do something. And I remember how - how I put quite a lot into that - cleaning it you see, scrubbing it - and - I - I - I remember - you know, you used to have newspape
r
s in those days for toilet paper - and I remember thinking oh, how untidy that is and - I must only have been five or six - and I remember getting a lot of fathers old handicaps - you know, I told you about him having little books - and taking the pins ou
t
 and then stringing them all together, you see, as kind of toilet paper so that the place would look tidier than these bits and scraps of newspaper all over the floor, you see, and we were all more or less in our turn expected to do that kind of thing. Wh
e
n I got older we had to help with the housework you see. There was - if a floor had to be scrubbed or sanded well, we had to do it in our turns you see. The boys, of course, didn't have to do as much as the girls because in those days there were the old f
a
shioned idea that boys didn't have to do chores in the home, you see, they were rather regarded as cissies if they did. So I suppose mother con - allowed herself that because - I know we used to grumble and say why aren't the lads doing something? And she
 
used to say, oh well, you know, they're lads - they're lads, you see. And - but we girls certainly had to take our share of responsibility in running the home. And another job that was mine that I remember I did with great diligence was looking after the 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 aspidistra}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 . We had a huge }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 aspidistra}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and it had a quite a - a formality and I had to stick it overhead in water in the sink every week you see and I had to polish all the leaves, nip off the faded ones and then put a final }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 polish}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  on it you - then bring it b
ack in it's place of honour on the sewing machine - on the top of the sewing machine. And it - I can tell in looking back that mother had an idea you see of making us feel we were part of the home but we had responsibilities and we were not allowed to go 
running out into the street playing unless we had done our particular jobs, you see. So there was a discipline - yes, I think there was a - it was a kindly discipline - I don't think that she ever forced us but - she sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 maneuvered}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you into a kind of habit as it were that these things occurred and it was your place to help you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would be when you grew up
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How old would they be? Well, if they had any ambitions about us they never - they 
never expressed it. One of the strange things. I never remember my mother sort of quietly expressing sort of any hopes about us because she had been reared in that hard school where children were not given any choice, you see, of occupations and it was cu
s
tomary very definitely that if the mother worked in the mill, the girls followed her, you see. And consequently she assumed that there was nothing wrong about girls leaving school - my sister at twelve and I - Emily at thirteen and I at thirteen - and the
n
 going into the mill. Perhaps - I don't know whether I ought to say this now - perhaps that might come later about leaving school - does it come up later? Would you rather me talk ...? Well, I - I don't remember father ever - suggesting that we ought to s
trike out, you see, we ought to be ambitious. We were never taught to be ambitious and we were never taught to be pushing and - it was only when I came very near school }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 leaving age}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  that my sister - the elder one, Kathy - was so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 anxious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 that I should try to 
get a scholarship in order to do better than she had done by being pushed into the mill and the school I was attending of course was a Roman Catholic school and at that time they were very laggard at - they were behind the ordinary - they were board schoo
ls in those days you see - and they were very much behind the ordinary school in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 offering}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 scholarships and my sister was so anxious that she tried to persuade me to leave the Catholic school when I was about ten and go to the nearby board school. But of cou
rse I was such an ardent little Catholic that I couldn't dream of it - I just thought it would be - you know - absolutely disloyal to everything that I'd been taught and - although in years - years afterwards of course I realised that her - her advice was
 
sound because they had no scholarships and they allowed me to leave, you see, at thirteen and sort of without offering anything in the way of further education which made me always a little bitter and then - then when she said - when Kathy said to mother 
- I - I don't want Alice to go in the mill and my mother seemed a bit taken a back that - anybody should suggest that I didn't you see.
\par And - so I got the first job I got after leaving school was in a shop in town and - but - I - I - I'd no training for a s
hop - for a shop assistant and - I did my best during - oh, I went on a month's trail - I did my best on this trial but it was a fancy goods shop and - rather a - I don't know whether I really ought to - to say this, but there was a lady in charge of it -
 
no, she was the owner. And her husband was a little demure man who only came in the shop now and again and who had an office upstairs where he did sight testing you see. And the little man I got on very well with - but the lady - I think she took a dislik
e
 to me because I was very timid and very shy and - although - so - she never told me that I wasn't satisfactory she - but she sent a little not to my mother and she said I was a good clean girl but I would never make a shop assistant. Probably she was rig
ht because I don't think I would ever have made a shop assistant. So that ended that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 
And of course there was a terrible lot of unemployment at the time and I spent weeks and weeks going round - nobody ever went with you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11536143  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 
see, and - I got very weary - of thi
s business of going to offices and shops in town and tobacco works and all sorts of things and - it was always the same reply - they would look you up and down and then say they would let you know but at the present they had no vacancies. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And so mother got
 a bit fed up with this business of me traipsing round and getting nowhere and so at the last she said to me, I can always remember it, I think thee'd better get thee clogs on and go in't mill. You see, that was what she knew. And so I did it - I was so w
e
ary of the rebuffs. You see, often you - you walked miles and then you'd get to an office and it would have on no hands wanted, you see, and things like that and so in sheer desperation I went into the mill. Although I felt it was a mistake because I was 
n
ever happy - never happy there. But that was how - but you see there was no guidance - there was no guidance from mother because - perhaps I ought not to blame her because she'd never known anything else, you see. Father was the one who might have taken t
h
e initiative you see, but didn't. And - so there was really - there was very little guidance in those days because there was no - no bridge whatever between leaving school and being dumped into a factory None whatever. No bridge at all and consequently no
 
training schemes - you'd no training. You were just thrown into the place amongst the deafening terrible machinery and you were put with an elder person to learn the particular process, whatever it was, you see. And I was always scared stiff - the early d
a
ys in the weaving shed because of these terrible flying shuttles and the dreadful noise you see, but - being in it was a question of staying where you were. So I couldn't say there was any - any - any real encouragement or guidance to do anything else, on
ly follow that pattern, you see, of going into the mill, you see.
