\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I should say - he was - he was exceptionally clean and he - he certainly put that standard before us. We always had to be - we hadn't to come in dirty and running to the table with dirty h
ands and things like that. He was in that sense very - he was very clean himself and punc - he liked punctuality of course. Now he did introduce the outside world which I think was - benefit to me in after years although I couldn't follow very much of wha
t
 went on in the discussions that took place between him and the older boys. But - he was, as I mentioned before, a radical at heart. He was rebellious because he felt that Ireland had suffered terrible what with - you know, the potato famine and all the p
o
verty and that kind of thing, so that he was in rebellion and he - he was a good reader and he brought the news into the home. We always had to have newspapers - however poor we were there had to be newspapers. And - he - he was a big reader of Robert Bla
t
chford who at that time was the editor of the Clarion. Clarion came out about the year that I was born and this Clarion had to be bought every week and of course it was Socialism you see and the - I forget their names now - but they might come to me - the
 
books that he wrote you see - Merrie England was one and - they - they were - all these books that were recommended and published in the Clarion father tried to get you see. And consequently there were - constant discussions going on about the injustices 
that existed you see, and what}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143  to do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
about them you see. And although he called himself a Liberal and never joined the Labour party he really was at heart - if he'd lived longer he probably would have been a member of the Labour party because the other - th
e younger people - the older people in the family all became members of the Labour party you see. The Independent Labour Party as it was then you see, and Emily and I and Kathy - the girls all joined the Labour church, you see, and became more or less str
o
ng Socialists you see, and I put that down to the fact that he did bring these problems into the house - oh, he was very keen on home rule for Ireland and he used to read aloud to mother the discussions in Parliament - it would be Gladstone wouldn't it - 
about Gladstone period - and - home rule was very much in the air - home rule for Ireland I mean, and consequently these were the discussions that I began to absorb as it were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What did your parents think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh, well father was a terrib
le swearer. He couldn't hardly speak a sentence without an oath in it. And mother, I think, took it all for granted - she disliked it but - it was no use - probably she did at times say to father you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 ought}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  to be more careful about your language in front of
 the children but it was impossible for him - it was - almost every sentence you see. And consequently I grew up with a terrible vocabulary of swear words. I didn't used them, only probably - when I grew a little older perhaps in desperation I would say o
ne or two naughty words but the vocabulary was there all the time you see and I never heard the boys swear. The boys didn't - didn't imitate him in that. He was the one heavy swearer and mother probably had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 protested}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  time and time again but it had been no u
se so she'd simply accepted it as part of the - part of the economy. So I've never been shocked, really, by all this - as quite a lot of other people have been, you see, that came in good stead on the bench when I became a magistrate - I could see the oth
er side of so many things, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
You said your mother had a gentle means of disciplining you and your father was rather hasher. Can you remember any particular occasion when you were punished for something in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I can remember one
 outstanding occasion - mother never - mother never hit us - mother never was vicious at all and I don't think that she ever - if we did anything wrong she didn't punish us. I can remember on one occasion when I was only quite a tiny child and I'd gone ou
t
 with her - I told you about the homes that she went to - she went to shop - shopkeepers mainly - and I would sit amongst a whole pile of dirty clothes and she was busy washing and I came across a very lovely little pink doll's frock - a knitted doll's fr
o
ck - I'd never seen anything like it before, it was so beautiful - that I purloined it - I had a little pinny on and I put this thing - this little - and took it home. It was the first time that I ever remember stealing and - when I got home I remember dr
e
ssing this shabby little doll that I had in this lovely little pink woolen frock and standing the doll up and thinking how beautiful she looked, she was like a little princess and - eventually it was discovered, you see, mother saw the doll in this. Now I
 
can't remember her saying a word to me about it - all that she did was to take the frock off the doll, put the old one back again and return it to the - place it had been taken from. And it had a remarkable effect on me, even as a child. You see, she didn
'
t scold me, she didn't slap me but she - she did the right thing in taking it back you see, and she had a trick of saying when I wasn't naughty, and I must have been a naughty child quite often, she would say now if you don't be good I shall run away with
 a black man - that was enough. You see, there weren't many black people in Bolton at that time but we had a family of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 Ice Cream}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  people called Doriswami and immediately I thought it's one of the Doriswami's that she's going to go away with, you see, and I w
as terrified and every day I went to school I would run home as fast as my legs could carry me to see whether mother was there. If she was there I'd drop my load of grief and anxiety but if she wasn't I used to say to myself she must have gone away with t
h
at black man. And it taught me one thing - never to say things like that to young children because I can remember the terror that I was in. But that was her method. She probably didn't know how much anxiety she was causing to her little girl by her remark
 but she never - she preferred, I think, that kind of thing to hitting you or punishing you or sending you to bed without supper.
\par Occasionally we were sent upstairs after we'd been extremely naughty just with a drink of water you see, but - the only real pu
nishment was father with this strap and he would land out, you know, whoever was nearest caught it you see. And I remember on one occasion when he was recovering from a bad bout of drinking he got up very late and he was very - funny about his food and - 
I
 often remember seeing him pick a plate up off the table with the food on and throw it behind the fire, you see, and swear heavily about it and then of course stalk out. Mother would never say anything, she would never retaliate and this Saturday morning 
m
other had gone out shopping - I was at home from school - and he - he told me to go to the butchers for a pennyworth of liver and I raced off to the shop because we lived quite a distance away from the place where I was born - you know, the Milk Street su
r
roundings and Shore Street - and this butchers shop that I was sent to was in Derby Street and I went for this pennyworth of liver and I came back with it and I put it on the table. Father had got the frying pan out to fry this liver for his breakfast - l
o
oked at it and was furious because he said it was full of kernel. Now I suppose kernel was the white streaks of white that's sometimes in liver and in his anger he - he came like that with me and sent me spinning round the kitchen and I fell - from the se
v
erity of the blow. I was astounded because he - he had never hit - never hit me personally like that before - he was rather fond of me and I was staggered you see, to think this brutality should fall on me when I'd done the deed of running to the butchers
 
and fetching the - and he told me to take it back and bring the penny back. That was more humiliating than ever. So I had to race back to the butchers shop and I waited outside until everybody had come out - there's quite a lot of women in - and I waited 
u
ntil they'd all come out and then I went in timidly and I put the little parcel of liver on the counter and I said - please, daddy says that it's all kernel - can I have me penny back. And without a word the man opened the drawer pulled a penny out, took 
t
he offending liver off me and raced back home with this penny and listened whether father was about, then I crept in, put the penny on the table, then I raced out for life. And that stands always out you see. But that was the only time that I remember him
 
sort of striking me but he did strike - he did strike the lads an awful lot until he got big enough really to retaliate on him. Yes. Everything that he was angry about he lashed out, you see, at something or - or somebody. But - that was the only time I c
an remember him ever - ever being sort of cruel to me. But it stayed with me for a long time.
