Well, Christmas Eve stays in my mind longer than Christmas Day. Christmas Eve stood out because as I said mother made a special effort and we always had a very, very nice tablecloth on, we weren't often - we hadn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5603085\charrsid11536143 often}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 had tablecloths on - it was just a clean scrubbed table you see. But on Christmas Eve mother always found a very, very nice tablecloth and of course to pacify father there was always a bottle of whisky stood in the centre of the table you see. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
The only time that I do remember any expense - expenditure on spirits you see, but on Christmas Ever there was always a bottle of whisky and then the best pots were fetched out, whatever nice pottery we had, it was brought out on that evening you see and 
- the food was always very nice you see because she would always - cook some kind of a piece of meat - very, very slowly in the oven 'til it was very, very tender and then we all had a very nice slice of this and probably something else - pickles or some 
savory or something with it, you see, and then her own made currant cakes and that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well after the table was cleared away we all had to gather round the fire while we talked - they told ghost stories. Father had a - oh, a good - a good repertoire of stories
 and he would start off with some old Irish ghost stories 'til our hair was nearly standing on end and - and this would go on for quite a while then he always - it was part of Christmas Eve to read Dickens's Christmas Carol aloud - and he used to read it 
a
nd then he would ask us which part of the carol we liked best. Well always Emily - Emily and I always plumped for little Tim and the dinner - the goose you see, the goose that they had and mother, for some reason or other, her favourite was the churchyard
 
with the old tombstone of old Scrooge where he sees his name on the tombstone and the neglected and why I - I just don't know but that always appealed to her and she always insisted on that part being read and the lads liked there part where they were rev
e
ling in the warehouse, you know, where they had all the dancing and that kind of thing on. It was funny how different ones in the family chose different sections of the - of Christmas Carol and then after that the younger ones had to go to bed and we alwa
ys shouted up the chimney of course what we wanted but don't know as we ever got it.
\par And - we hung our stockings up and then the following morning of course we were up by about five o'clock, scurrying downstairs to see what we'd got in our stockings 'cos th
ere was a rail across the fireplace and they were hung on there you see. And usually it was - a sixpenny toy of some kind or other and an apple and an orange. And so Christmas morning was, as I say, they were very simple things that we got in our stocking
 
and of course practically alike because mother never liked giving one - one of us - Emily - diff - more than me because she was two years older anything like that, and they were nearly all similar things and - but always if the finances of the family were
 
fairly good they would wrap a threepennybit up in a little bit of silver paper and that was a great joy to us because we never had any spending money - at the most we got a ha'penny - a halfpenny on Saturday - that was about the limit of our pocket money 
i
n those days you see. So that when we - we squealed with delight when we found a threepenny bit at the bottom of the toe of the stocking and we were very - we were never - sort of resentful about knowing that other children had got much more than us - som
e
how or other, I don't know whether it was just quiescence or not, but I don't ever remember sort of feeling jealous about other children in the street who might show us much more expensive toys or anything of that kind. And Christmas morning was generally
 
spent with us going up around to other children in the street showing them what we had got and they showed us what they had got and - but it was always - I will say that, it was a day when the family were united because they all came home to tea - they ca
me - we had Christmas Dinner of course with this pork you see, and then everybody - wherever they went - the older ones - they did all return home to tea on Christmas Day. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
So that those were two days - Christmas Eve and Christmas Day when the whole of the f
amily were more or less united and father was kept of course in a very good temper by having this bottle of whisky and - there was kind of peace at home as you might say for that - that those two days, you see, and that threepenny bit we reserved until Ne
w
 Years Day when father took us down on the fairground you see and we used to - we used to walk down to the fairground from Rankin Street feeling like little Rothschilds with this threepennybit screwed up in our first you see because we'd been warned not t
o
 put it in our pocket because of pickpockets and we used to plan a penny in the pea saloon - we liked peas you see - we spent a penny in the pea saloon, a penny in a showground - now what did the third penny go on - I'm not sure if it wasn't - if father d
idn't win a coconut we bought a slice of coconut with it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
But it was so that we all had it planned, you see, what we did with this threepennybit, so - that was how our Christmas more or less linked itself with the New Years Day, you see. But it - New Years 
Day was not considered anything like as important in the family as Christmas, you see, it was Christmas Eve and Christmas Day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. Might have a penny or a mouthorgan or something like that put i
n the stocking, but I mean we were never guided or - or encouraged really to be musical. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did anybody sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Sing? Well, father whistled a great deal and we could tell by the whistle what was going to happen you see. Mother used to say that he
 was more dangerous when he whistled - because he nearly always lost his job. He would start spouting poetry and whistling when he should have been doing his job you see, he nearly always lost his job through it and - no, that was one of the queer things 
t
hat - I - I used to sing, but I must admit I sang horribly out of tune 'cos I didn't know notes or anything and in the street, of course, there were a band of singers - we were always marching up and down you know singing some kind of song or hymns and I 
w
as never guided at all until when I was about eight - at school the - the organist in the - in the chapel was a lady - a lady teacher - and she came round to test our voices for going in the church choir you see and singularly enough I got into the church
 
choir, although I can't remember that I ever sort of knew what key I was in and - but I did develop into quite a good singer and I have gold medal that I won in my teens in - singing you see in Co-operative Choral Choir - and things - although I had no tr
a
ining until I joined the Socialist Club and that of course is another story - I won't enter into that, but - mother never sang - I never heard mother sing. Father whistled - yes, and probably one or two of the boys would sing when they were washing themse
l
ves or something like that but we were not a musical family. My sister, Kathy, joined the - Choral Union when she was in her teens and used to often sing snatches of the pieces that they were practicing you see, at this Choral Union, but - I don't - I wou
ldn't say that we were a musical family until I branched out later, you see, as a kind of a singer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did your parents ever play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. I played - well, shall I say - yes, probably they did but father was a big card player and the 
- the lads and he used to play a lot of - not whist - what would it be in those days - would be - it was a card game - you know doing this kind of thing. Wouldn't be - it wouldn't be bridge because - no, the draughts - yes, they always had a draught board
 
and the boys were very keen on draughts and dominoes - dominoes were often played but mother and I and Emily often played snakes and ladders in - you know the cold winter evenings when it was too dark to - do much else and of course I always wanted mother
 
to win because I never like winning myself and - I used to dodge horribly, you know how you got your counter on the top of a ladder and you had to go down to the bottom, you see, you probably don't know snakes and ladders, but it was a card game of snakes
 and a lot of ladders, and if you got on a snake - if you got on the bottom the ladder - the number - you went up to the top of it but if you got on a snakes head you went to the bottom you see. Well now, I always used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 maneuver}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  that when she should get h
ome, you know, the winning post was home, and - I used to look at her face you see - I don't know whether she knew that I was - I was dodging or not - but I deliberately did it because I used to love seeing her smile and it used to pain me as a little chi
ld, I was so sensitive, her sad face. That is my mother's - a painting of my mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
You said there were plenty of books going in and out of the house and you mentioned the Clarion newspaper - did you have any other newspapers that you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
I can remember the - did you ever know Alan Clarke - he had a paper in those days called Teddy Ashtons weekly - it was a very well known Lancashire paper containing all kinds of Lancashire sketches, he was a Bolton man - who eventually, of course, wen
t to live in Blackpool and I - his relative - might be one of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 his sons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 - did quite a lot on T.V. you know, when radio first came in. Well he had a paper called - it was the Northern Weekly really but it was christened Teddy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Ashton\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  Weekly and that always came into the house, you see, this Teddy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Ashton\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 Weekly and the Cotton Factory Times - they always took the Cotton Factory Times. Which contained all sorts of articles about mill work, you know, mill conditions and everything attached to the cotton indust
ry, well, it was of course a paper that was printed in Ashton-under-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Lyme}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 but went on for a long, long time - I mean I think it only went out just after - about 1930 - folded up about 1930 you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You mentioned the Sporting World that your father had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, well, he - he had one or two sporting papers too that used to come in, yes sporting papers - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You spoke about going to Bolton Library for your books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 That was in High Street - that was a branch library - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was the Co-op Library in existence then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, yes it was. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you used that at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Not until I was older because you see, we weren't members of the Co-operative Society and you were supposed to be a member of the society to used the library bu
t later on when Kathy got - taking more charge of the household she insisted, you see, that mother stopped this business of shopping with Kitty Kaye and transferred it to the Co-operative Society so then we were eligible to take books and we did - we did 
- I did go down there, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Somebody else said how much better the Co-op library was than the Bolton library.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, well - where was the Bolton Public Library? Was it where now on the town hall square? Yes, I don't - I don't remember that lib
rary very well you see because I always went to High Street library which was the branch library and then the Co-operative - yes, we had those two - those two libraries - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you remember a funeral in the family when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes. I
 do. Very, very - tragic. You see, this - about the boy you see, James that was the youngest boy. He had never been very strong - he was always ailing as a boy and - I can always remember the - oh, the tedious weeks and weeks when we had to have a bed dow
n
stairs in the living room - there was now here else you see and this bed would be in a corner like that you see and this brother was nearly always ill and it would last for quite a long time - weeks and weeks and weeks you see. Now, there was no health in
s
urance then you know, we'd only sixpenny doctors and - the doctor would come and we used to pay off - he would send a bill at the end of the time and we would pay off at sixpence a week. The collector came regularly every Friday night to pick up this sixp
ence - it was always put on the end of the dresser, you see, mother }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 religiously}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 would always insist that things like that had to be paid for - no missing them whatever happened. So that - now I can remember those dreary stretches you see of - of having to b
ring the bed downstairs you know and - this boy one day came home when he was - he was sixteen - I was about ten - ten - and he came home full of trouble and must have been in terrible pain and - mother immediately lit the bedroom fire and we put the lad 
i
n the bed that we - Emily and I - slept in you see - didn't matter about use, the boy had to have this bed you see where it was warm. And she hurriedly - she asked me to sit with him whilst she went for Doctor Beesley who was on Dean Road. I can always re
m
ember it because I thought I was cheering him up by singing and we had a rocking chair and I rocked myself back and forward singing and the poor lad was groaning terribly. And then when the doctor came of course I had to go downstairs and when the doctor 
h
ad gone mother says - he - he's very, very ill and he has to have - he'll have to go the infirmary and have an operation and I say - oh, why, what is it? And she said the doctor says it's twist of the bowels - that was appendicitis - that was it's special
 
name but they called it in those days twist of the bowels, you see. Now, she couldn't decide - the doctor told her to let him know that night that it was so serious. Now, when father came in - I don't know whether father was working at that time or just c
o
me home - just came in for his tea but it would be about six o'clock I know, there was a terrible row. Father said he was a Catholic - he didn't believe in surgery - and he said under no circumstances had the boy to go to a hospital. If he had to die he d
i
ed at home. Well, Kathy was absolutely furious about this and they had a terrible row, I can remember it to this day, poor mother was in the midst of it - not able to say, well I - I'm with Kathy or I'm with father. She was with Kathy but - whether she ha
d
n't the courage to stand up to father or not I don't know - but it was so that when she had to go to tell the doctor - the doctor that - he - my father wouldn't agree to the operation. Well, the following morning the boy was very much worse. I went off - 
s
he told me to go off to school and she was left alone in the house. She suddenly realized that the boy was practically dying and so she rushed out to the - to get the doctor and of course when she came back the boy was dead, you see. Well, there was more 
f
urious rows after that, you see, because my Kathy - this sister, said straight out to father - you killed the boy. You see she jumped to the conclusion that the boy - might - he might have died - he might have been too bad at that time - but she jumped to
 the conclusion that - if - if he had agreed to the boy undergoing this operation, because you see, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 peritonitis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 had set in, and so - ooh, it was a dread - it was a dreadful time because poor mother was worn out with grief about whether she'd made a mistake 
in not insisting on the boy being sent to the infirmary and Kathy - well, I don't think she ever afterwards spoke to father, unless she - she couldn't help it. It was a - a deadlock between them you see. The result was of course that I got a terrible shoc
k
 because I'd gone to school and I was coming home at dinnertime, coming down the - the top of the street was another little girl going up to the mill with the dinner and you know how children are, and she shouts across the road to me - Alice Foley - Alice
 
Foley, your Jim's dead. Well, the shock - I can - I stood frozen - almost frozen to the ground you see - didn't know - didn't speak - just took to me heels and ran home. When I got to the door Kathy had been sent for from the mill and she was outside weep
ing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 uncontrollably}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 and - well, it was an awful household you see and consequently I have never forgotten what death can mean you see. And the worst feature of it was the after - the after feature was terrible because when I went back to school - mother insi
sted on me going back - she said you can't do anything - and I went back to school in the afternoon and of course I was crying bitterly and the nuns came to ask what was the matter. They were very kind but this stood out. They said had he been to church -
 
to mass the previous Sunday? And I had to say no. And they just shook their heads and they said oh, well, I'm afraid that he's either gone to hell or he's in purgatory. And that finished me with the Catholics. I never after had any faith you see. And it w
a
s terrible and I began to be ill - the pain of it all and - oh, it was dreadful - and I must have been ill for probably six months and I can remember the doctor said he couldn't understand what was wrong with me and I used to get suddenly attacks of viole
nt pains and the family didn't understand what it was but I suppose it was this inward grief, you see, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 psychologist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 now would know what it was but they didn't, you see, but - that part made a - a great - a terrible impression on me you see and of course i
t helped to shake my faith in - in father you see. I had been able to appreciate his good points but after that of course I - I began to doubt very, very much you see, whether he was as good as I - I had kind of painted him you see. But - I mean after all
 
- I realized afterwards that perhaps it had gone too far - perhaps the boy - you see hadn't the strength to fight against it - this twist of the bowels - on the other hand of course they might have saved him but - we always look back on it as a - as a ter
rible grief, because it was the first experience we'd had of death and to children it's - it's very deep - very deep. And you only realise what death means when it comes inside your own family. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you remember anything about the actual funeral?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Yes, I can remember the actual funeral. Father insisted of course on a grave being bought on the Catholic ground - on their number three ground which was the cheapest you see. And he was buried of course by the Catholic priest and - I can remember it
 - it was all in Latin you see, it was in Latin. And mother - mother couldn't understand a word of it of course, we, Emily and I, who had listened so much to services in Latin at the church on Sunday could follow - follow quite a lot of it you see but - w
e
 were too - too sort of dumbfounded with grief to - to really think much about you see - much about the service - although years after I did of course have a good chat with one of the Catholic Priests in Bolton because I was then helping to bury an old la
d
y who had taken in tow, and - they were gabbling away in this Latin you see and I said to the Priest - isn't it about time - I said - you got permission from the Pope or whoever's permission you ought to have to say these funeral services in English so th
a
t people can follow you. And he agreed, he said, yes it was high time that - and so a few years after they did because now they do give the funeral service in English you see. But that stands out to me and the - the money that had to be spent on black. Yo
u
 see, we were so poor and yet it - we should have been picked out in the street if we hadn't all have been dressed in black you see and I can remember taking us to a cheap shop on Dean Road to have us black frocks made or bought you see for this special o
c
casion you see, first time in my life I'd ever had a new frock and it had to be the occasion of a funeral you see and I - I can remember all that very vividly and very clearly and I can remember my eldest sister getting a dress made by her friend who - wh
o
 was a milliner and a dressmaker on Dean Road and she insisted on having a velvet - a black velvet band let into the skirt and this friend was shocked and she said - Oh Katie - they called her Katie - now we called her Cissie in the home until later we ch
anged it to Kathy - and she said - oh, but Katie, we never put velvet on funeral attire. Kathy says well I'm having it and she always - and I can always remember this black dress with this velvet let in because later on I had to wear all her }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 hand-me-downs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  y
ou see and I loved it - I loved this black with black velvet being let into the skirt, you see. And - and I used - I used to have to shove my feet into her shoes and she was very small and I had big feet and - you know I almost ruined my feet in childhood
 
by having to - you know - they were nice shoes - well, they were small you see and it attracted me small feet and so everything that Kathy had eventually came down to me you see so her shoes did and I used to crunch my feet into them - they were probably 
t
wo sizes too small. Anyway that - that's arising out of the tragedy of death. Anything else about the funeral because you know they always had a feed hadn't they? Yes, it was the practice. And I remember the - the relatives - we hadn't many relatives but 
what few came to the funeral. I remember they came to the house you see and had a tea and it rather shocked me you see to hear people laughing because I - I felt it was so tragic an event that I couldn't understand people }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 laughing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and chatting at a funeral you see. And I can remember that part of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You would have other relatives apart from your own family circle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, but we - we didn't visit them very much. We had an uncle - mother's brother who lived at Farnworth - and I remember a cousin or t
wo that I remember being taken to as a little girl up Halliwell Road, but we were never - kind of hospitable family you see, we never had - many friends or relatives visiting us. Just occasionally - just occasionally. Father had a brother who lived in Sco
t
land and I think we only saw him once or twice because he used to come - he was - he must have been in a show business - and he used to come with the fair on Bolton Market - so at Christmas time and New Year he generally popped up and - a queer oddity - w
e were always glad when he went back because he used to do juggling tricks and all that kind of thing and used to perform on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 sidestep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  outside the house and get a crowd round which was rather embarrassing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you remember having any outings with your parents at all - at Bank Holiday time or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, I don't remember any Bank Holidays. I do remember we had one holiday a year. What was a day at New Brighton - that was only holiday we ever had. As children. And it was very cheap you
 see, used to go on a day trip. It was two and nine at that time for a ticket return to New Brighton and we all used to get up very early in the morning about six o'clock and mother used to cut up all the sandwiches you see, we had to take all the food wi
t
h us, and - I remember - I could remember it was always boiled ham, you know, and either home made flour cakes or homemade bread and then her currant cakes. And father of course would be fuming and cursing all over the place because the lads were getting 
i
n his way. He didn't used to help much but - supposed to be superintending everybody and this was one of the things I do remember which always embarrassed me - in the early days when I was quite small - they didn't used to pay for me, you see, children co
u
ld go half price, and children under a certain age were free, and so for quite a long time they used to push me in between father and mother when they were going through the booking office, you know these stiles, and I used to have to crouch down and be c
o
vered by them you see until we got in the compartment and then you see, I was always warned that if the inspector came along or anybody to look at the tickets I'd to dart under the seat and they would cover me up you see with their knees which was very em
b
arrassing to me and - I was very glad when later on I sprouted up into a rather tall girl - they couldn't do it any longer. But anyway we used to go along to New Brighton and we used to think it was wonderful. I was always sick crossing the Mersey. The id
e
a that it was part of the sea I was sick you see and - but we used to have a - a very, very good time with - used to get a pennyworth of shrimps you know and you had a pin to pick them out - I - I never - I never liked them but the others used to have the
m
 and we used to - you know, dig sand pies and collect shells on the sea shore and we had pints and pints of hot tea - hot sweet tea - jugs - they used to sell - send you for jugs of tea you see, and then we came home in the evening very, very tired but ve
r
y happy that we'd had this day. But I never got another holiday to go away and stay 'til I was sixteen so that was that. But - not many outings - no. Occasionally mother would come to a field day with us - the Sunday school you see had field days and we u
s
ed to take our own cups you know tied - knotted in a handkerchief you see, swinging these cups along and the field days were usually held somewhere now which is Great Lever. We called it Green Lane and Georges Lane - somewhere about where Green Lane is no
w
 and - we used to go there and mother would accompany us but never father and - mother used to quite enjoy sitting about you see and having coffee and buns and watching us play games. She never - she never joined in anything and - then once - oh well, whe
n
 I was a child we - the people next door to use - that lived next door to us were members of the gospel hall, this was a little mission that was in Mare Street which is now leads down to Bolton Park you see, and nearly all the children in the street used 
to go to this - this gospel hall because every so often they had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 tea party}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 - a free tea party, so we pestered mother so much that she would only agree on condition that we didn't let on to father, you see, that we were going to a gospel hall. And so we st
arted to go to this gospel hall and to learn their little hymns and prayers which were quite different from the Catholics and they used to give us a little ticket like that for all our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
at tendencies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 . And then when you'd made about twenty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 attendance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you wer
e entitled to go to a free tea party, you see. We did that for quite a bit until I think father somehow or other discovered what was happening and so the whole thing had to be stopped immediately you see. But I don't remember many outings because they had
 
no - they hadn't much money, you see, and the only outing we ever got was just to be taken what we called down - down town you know or - looking at the shops in the market hall and perhaps having a - a glass of ice cream, you see, sitting at a stall, you 
see, perhaps a penny - a penny cornet or something like that, but I don't remember ever being taken anywhere, you know, either to concerts or - anything that was - that might have been elevating, you see. No, I don't remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You told me that sometimes you went into town Saturday nights for shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, in town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did you normally spend your Saturdays when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I don't really think it was very much different than an ordinary day apart from going to school. Us
ually - we did part - little bits of errands and things a bit of cleaning up on Saturday morning while mother was out and - we were given our - you know, - our little jobs of cleaning up so that Saturday morning whilst mother was out mainly doing the shop
p
ing we would do the tidying up you see, cleaning the kitchen - we had - it was a whitewashed place, it was always to me a very dark disagreeable kitchen and we used to have to take the dishes and pots off these shelves and wash them and put them back you 
s
ee, and we'd always a dark rather miserable slop stone, you know, the stone slop stone which we used to try to stone, you know, with a rubbing stone in order to make it look a little bit cleaner and do the doorsteps - polish the door latch, you see, we ha
d
 a - we had a brass latch, which I was very proud of and we used to do all little jobs like that. Now in the afternoon we were more or less left to our own devices. And we either played in the streets some games or other or else we went to Queen's park - 
that was a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 favorite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  place for us to go to. And we had another play ground - where - it was of course the ruins of the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 old}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 Chamber Hall owned by some big Bolton family and they had had this hall knocked down - it's now where the new Pipes Lane - well wha
t was a new Pipes Lane infant's school was built and there is a housing estate there which of course was considered very modern in those days and we used to play amongst the rubble because it was a very, very good playground because there was a lot of san
d
 - it must have been a sandy foundation - there was a tremendous amount of sand to play amongst and there was a lot of different stones that we used to break up - we used to have pepper you know, and mustard and salt out these stones, we would smash them 
u
p you know and - make them very fine then we'd set out a little stall and with a sixpenny pair of scales what somebody would bring along we used to play shop you see, with these different commodities that were found amongst this rubble and then of course 
a
fter they started building there - our main recreation ground was of course going to the park and swinging - we were passionately fond of swinging and roly-polying you know down the - down the green. And then on a Friday night - if we - this was after whe
n
 we got a bit bigger and could do our own bathing - Friday night when we were children was always the bath night as I told you. But when we got a little older and we could do our own washing we used to go off to a spare ground off - on Dean Road which is 
n
ow of course built on, but it was the auctioneer ground for Balleys the pot people, you see, and he was a character and he - they used to have - put all the crockery all in a great huge circle on this open ground and they had those flares, you know, the -
 
the gas - gas flares all round you see and of course on dark nights it was very attractive so every Friday night we always trotted up there because there was always a lot of fun going on and we, the kids, used to be running round the edge of the crowd you
 see, there was always a lot of elderly people coming and he always used to tell - tell such funny stories, you know, that he used to have the crowd in roars of laughter and of course he sold anything from little chamber pots to nearly - }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Venetian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  vases, you
 know, his range of pottery was tremendous and he had an art of holding it up you know, so you could see the light through the china you know, and he would tell you all sorts of fantastic stories - he was a real character. Well, we used to go there - that
 
was one of our regular haunts - was going to Baileys pot - we used to call it Baileys pot stall, you see. Things like that we passed our time with. We were - a small community pretty closely knit you see and we used to go about in groups - not spending an
y
 money because we never had any to spend but - we used to have a ha'penny and of course there was a little - little toffee shop on Dean Road that we liked going to but was down steps, it probably had been a little old cottage at one time and we used to sp
e
nd an awful lot of time gazing in at the window deciding what the ha'penny had to be spent on - it was a very, very serious affair and then of course when we'd decided we all trouped in the shop, you see, and she was a very religious woman and she went to
 
Noble Street Methodist and - but she was very near with her - what we call near with her ways, you know, and the - we always wished she'd leave the extra toffee on but she used to pull it off you see, if it just - and then she would - before we left the s
h
op she would give us a tract you see - anyway - but we always felt that in spite of her piety she was a little bit sharp on her ways. Yes, it was a community - it was a kind of close knit community and we had to make our own - our own amusements by having
 
little - pin shows in the back yard, you know, and little magic lantern things, you know, and pay a button or a pin to come in you know, that kind of thing - yes. Oh yes, that was where we got our - more of our relaxation and amusement from rather than be
ing taken out anywhere.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You played together with the neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What about other members of your own family - was the age range too wide?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, the - at first when I was very small I can remember they boys congregat
ing in groups - particularly playing football and we - the younger elements - had to be on guard for the bobby coming because, you see, you were liable to be fined for playing football in a street in those days, you know. And so we were placed at differen
t corners to watch out for the bobby and we used to have to give the call you see if we saw a bobby approaching and then of course the lads all skittered in all directions you see. And Sunday they used to play }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 pitch and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  toss at the corner of the back street, you see, groups of them - tossing a penny or - into the - into the - circle, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 against}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 that was supposed to be our job - we - they called it nicksing - nicksing for the police you see. And I remember, they were often were fined and - but I do remember 
once - on one occasion they had to go to court - my brothers were in it - and they were fined five shillings each and you know the whole neighbourhood clubbed to pay the fines and they - they went and took it all down in ha'pennys. I can remember that. So
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 they - the boys did club together until they got older and of course then the war - the war came in and of course they groups were broken up you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters - was there one that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
The one that died. I was particularly close to him because he was the nearest you see, he was sixteen. But the other two were more or less remote - remote from us you see, the - they - as again - as I said before we were never a very loquacio
us group you see, we were nearly always either reading or the boys would be discussing football - football matches you see, with father, but - I never - I can't really say I ever got close to them. Possibly closer to them when they both left to go in the 
Army because then we began corresponding with them, you see, we had to write letters, so I was nearer I think to them then than I had been when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were you free to play with any children that you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did your parents discourage you from playing with some children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, no, there was no discouragement. No. It was a kind of open house, if you wanted to play with these children next door or if you wanted to play with somebody higher up or - it - it didn't matter - they
 just - all that they chastised us about was if we played ball against somebody's gable end - there was an elderly lady lived in one of these houses - she was a bit nanky - and of course when we played ball she used to say that we shook the pots in her cu
pboard you see. She would come out and complain to mother and we would be told, you see, that we had to stop playing ball there, you see, so then we used to have to seek another gable end where they didn't complain you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you play games on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Not to the same extent as we did during the week. Sunday was rather regarded as a - a different day, you see, although - I - I - for a short time we were made to go to Sunday school - Emily and I went to Sunday - they had a Sunday school then at 
the Catholics - they don't have now. And we were told that we had to go off to Sunday school. Well, I found it was a child rather boring because it was just chapters of the Bible, you know, and this kind of thing and - but later on we gave over going - I'
m
 not sure whether the Sunday school was not discontinued. But anyway we - we ceased to go but we were a bit bored on Sunday afternoons and that was why we nearly always decided that we would go to the park. We nearly always went in a small group, either o
t
her children joined us or we went with Kathy and as a rule, sometimes they had a band in, but not often on a Sunday - mostly on Wednesday evenings, but we did often go to the park to listen to the band you see. But Sunday - in the main we - we rather cons
i
dered it a dull boring day, you see, it wasn't as interesting as the other evenings because you see we all played the - the old fashioned games in the street you know, ring-a-ring-a-roses and here comes the robbers. We'd a lot of street games in those - a
 
lot - and we were very, very happy especially the girls doing these singing games, you see, they were singing games and of course when it got a bit too dark to go in - before we had go in - we had a time that we had to be in you see, and that was strictly
 enforced.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was this while you were still at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh yes, no still at school - we were at school then. And I was of course the champion fairy tale teller so after the game - when it got too dark to continue the games we used to crowd on an - t
here was an empty house - nearly always empty - plenty empty houses in those days - and we used to crowd on a doorstep and gather round in a circle and of course I would start telling them fairy tales because I knew so many and the other children didn't k
n
ow them and we used to stay there until we'd hear the doors opening and somebody would shout - Mary, you know, Alice come in, you see, and then we - disbanded and of course went inside. But - on the whole we were happy group of children, you see, fitted i
n very well in those days because you hadn't the traffic you know, you weren't always being interfered with - the streets were very quiet and we could play our street games, you see - different street games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have special clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, yes, they - they were better than the things I went to school in - yes. Probably a more decent coat, you see - but still a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 hand-me-downs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  not new. Probably my sister - the elder sister, you see - and mother would, or she would shorten it - alter t
he sleeves and that kind of thing, but it would be much better than how I went to school because often I went to school in mother's old cape, you know, the - the woman used to wear those beaded black capes, you see, and I must have looked like little Moll
y Rooney - with this little black cape on you see and - anything really - anything patched and darned and that but on Sunday - yes, we were - we were dressed a little better, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were you allowed to play in these better clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh no. Oh no
, no. No, if you used them for going to church you see, you had to take them off when you got home if you were going to go out, but if you were going to the park, anywhere like that you were allowed to - you weren't - you weren't being rough and you could
 keep the sort of coat on - the coat and dress. Oh yes, they were better on a Sunday but you only wore them that one day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You belonged to the Sunday school for a while?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were there any Sunday School outings apart from the field days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, no. That of course was I think one of the - one of the things that the Catholic churches at that period were lacking in. It was all religion, you see, and the other the human side of appealing to children, you see, apart from the one outing - the fi
eld day - they didn't - there didn't seem to be anything - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did they have any other social activities at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, of course, the - the church that we went to - had an - what was called an assembly hall and - and of course it was rather a - 
a very good building - the top floor had a stage and it was used for plays and dancing - oh no, the dancing was down at the - on the bottom floor, because I remember it was a beautiful black floor - later on it was turned into a boys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  school and of course all got pot }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 marks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 and spoiled really. But it was a very big building that was built presumably for social purposes and I remember one or two plays that I happened to be in as a little girl being played there you see, in the top - top floor. And I can remem
ber bazaars - the - they ran quite a lot of bazaars you see. Things of that kind to get - make money - they were money making affairs you see. And then late on they did start - dances in the - in the - on the bottom floor but not very long after and befor
e
 I left school - the education authorities came and said that this assembly hall would have to be turned into a school or - they would have to build a new one. You see, the school was overcrowded. The girls school was separate from the boys and it - the s
c
hool that most of my - schooling was at was really very, very poor. We were all in one building you see - one class - standard three would be here, standard four, standard five and so on, you see, all - so the we all impinged on one another - you could he
ar what was going on in each others classes, you see. And I think the authorities must have come along and seen the state of the building and how old fashioned it was with no equipment - we had no equipment really.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11536143  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 Not r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 eally. And they then insisted on this
 assembly hall being turned into the boys school and the boys school being extended for the girls. So instead of this one building that we were all in downstairs they built an outside staircase and we had then more classrooms above you see which was bette
r
. But the biggest share of my education was in this long, terribly bad - bad building you see. So that with using that assembly hall we lost a great deal of the social activities. They went, you see, there was no more plays could be produced there and the
 dancing went you see. Only in - in Sunday - at Sunday evenings - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 strangely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 enough, they started to open the bottom floor again as a kind of social - club later on for younger people you see on a Sunday evening. But there was no - no other social activities that I can remember apart from money making affairs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you belong to the social club at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, there was no social club. You just went when there was some }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 event on
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 . No, they had no organized social club - none at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did they have a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, I never remember temperance being - being discussed or talked about. Don't think the Catholics ever - ever were a temperance body you know. They had people who were heavy drinkers you know. The Irish - especially the Irish part o
f the congregation and - they used to have an awful lot of raffles, you know, tables - tables - and I can remember to this day the amount of whisky and wine and rum and that - bottles - that were always exhibited as prizes so they mustn't - I don't rememb
er any temperance at all - any temperance instruction - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 That was quite different from the Church of England at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was grace said at meal times ever in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. No. It was never said in the home. 
As I say we - we hadn't many niceties you see. Never said in the - in the home and I never remember it being said at any tea parties. It was never part and parcel of the kind of Catholic set up. Now, it was in the Church of England and the Methodist wasn'
t it? But never in - I never remember it - not in the Catholics. Assembly - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. No. I only remember Emily and I had to until we were quite big - to say our evening prayers before we went to bed. We knelt down
 at our either mothers knee or fathers knee, whoever was there and said these simple prayers but I never remember the family joining in at all - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 These were Catholic prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I presume they were although I - I can't remember any of them
 now but they were only simple little things about bless father bless mother you see, thank God for a happy day or something like that. But I - I wouldn't say that they were Catholic prayers - I should rather think they were just bits and pieces that were
 strung together more or less ourselves you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 I wondered if it would be make any difference your father and mother being of different religions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, that was perhaps why there was no kind of - as you say - family prayer. Because you see
, father being a Catholic - I don't know what arrangement they had made but I do know that mother had said when she agreed to marry him that if there were any children in the marriage they would be brought up Catholics and that was why she always insisted
 
- she used to say to us - now I'm having no bother - your father's a Catholic - you've been christened there and you must go there, you see. And so I should think it was that that mother not being deeply religious herself in the - in the sense of going to
 places of religion and father being a Catholic they had never more or less discussed any kind of family prayers or anything of that kind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You say your father was a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes. Rebellious one of course - not a conformist at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you know why he was a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I should think it grew out of his rebelliousness about Ireland, you see, and about things that were going on in the industrial world and - he was a socialist without really knowing it, you see, but if - if he voted at a
ll he voted liberal - largely because at that time there were no socialists being put up you see, or Labour people - not when I - I was quite tiny so that his vote always went to the Liberals, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was your mother interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 She
 wasn't interested in politics - no. She - she knew right from wrong and she knew what - what things needed attention, you see, she was - she was alert enough on that but of course her life was so taken up with - fending for the children and darning and m
e
nding and cooking and cleaning that she'd very, very little time to - become orientated as we say to politics at all, you see. But she would have been I - I think, very definitely if she'd had a vote - she would have voted Labour. Her sympathies were in t
h
at direction, you see. And of course Kathy had a big influence on her by telling her about the lectures and the discussions that went on at the Labour church, you see, she used to - she used to tell her things that were going on and mother had a profound 
f
aith that we were always right. She - she used to think that - well if they say so and they say that this ought to be done and that ought to be done - you see, Kathy used to say one of the things that ought to be done was the lengthening of the school lea
v
ing age - children ought to be allowed to stay at school long, you see. And mother used to say, yes, yes, that's right, but you know, after all you want their wages. You see, mother knew the economic difficulty you see. So I - I should say had women had t
he vote she would probably have voted Liberal or Labour, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you know whether she would vote in the first election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh no, there was no votes you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 1918 was the first one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh well, but she died - she died before then - yes. 
Yes. Wait a minute - no, she didn't. Oh no, no. Oh yes, of course - it's coming back to me now - 'course she did - she voted all the time because I used to take her and - you see, I - I had the difficulty in telling her who - who she must vote for because
 
she couldn't read, you see, and there would be three or four names on the ballot paper. So I used to say, now mother, can you remember that it's the third down - the third name down? And she would say, yes. Now you know his name, it's so-and-so. And nearl
y
 always when she went into the booth she'd forgotten and she would call out in a loud voice when she got it - Alice, who did say I'd vote for? So the policeman used to come and I used to whisper to him and I used to say - it's the third on the list. And s
o he used to - point a pencil - she could make a cross you see - point to the third name, but oh yes - yes, she used to - yes, she voted all the time - I used to insist on her voting. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you ever feel that there was any pressure brought to bear o
n your parents or on any member of the family to vote for a particular party by employers or the landlord or anybody like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, I can't remember any pressure because the landlord who owned the house in which we lived - we never saw him - he had a
n agent, you see, who picked up the rents, you see, so there was nothing at all ever came from there. Now, there might have been occasions when the priest in - in the service would rather lean towards suggesting that you might vote - they never told you s
t
raight out that you must - but - there were several people that they might favour - particularly if they were Catholics, you see, were in the - in the voting list. They - you were expected, you see, expected to vote for them although there was no pressure
 
- I don't remember any pressure being - being brought to bear on them about - father who would be voting then you see - any pressure being brought to bear on him to do that. There, could have been and probably was quite a - quite a lot of it going on but 
I didn't experience it - not inside our household - no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Apart from your father's activities in the Irish home rule affairs was he active as a member of the political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Not - not - no, he wasn't active at all. As I say he was only active in 
the home rule controversy - and - to what extent - as I say - it was a largely secret, you see, his activities were largely secret but for - he wasn't a man who joined - who joined anything, really. No. He was a - to some extent - an isolationist. But he 
would discuss, of course, discuss and argue intensely about things but he never joined that I remember any organization.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did your mother have any interests at all outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Not until she became much older. Not until she became much older 
because she was really weighed down, you see, and - and wasn't of course given a lot of encouragement., I think by any of us, to take an active part but after father's death and she began to take - she was of course a great one for helping other people an
d
 - of course in those days you see there was a lot of communal help. I mean if any of the neighbours were having babies or anything like that everybody shared in doing the work, you see. Mother would take the washing and she would go and help to clean the
 house, you see. She was always very good at taking a share of whatever was happening in the little community, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
But, of course later on when she was more free and we were able to move into a better house and that kind of thing, we did get her intere
sted in - one or two groups of people, particularly women - who, you know, had little outings - little picnics amongst themselves and that kind of thing attached to a - when we moved into Fern Street we were next door to a little Wesleyan chapel and there
 
was a group of women, you see, and mother joined them and was able to get a little bit of pleasure out of these outings, although she herself was conscious that she'd missed so much in her early life that she wasn't an easy mixer - wasn't - but still she 
did - she did try anyway to - to get interested in - in other groups.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 This question says when did your father get home from work in the evenings - that would be rather a difficult one to answer wouldn't it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When did your father? Well, if - if he 
was working his day would finish about half past five or six. He generally got in about six o'clock you see, but of course he was so seldom working that - that hardly - hardly fit - fitted him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 He
 was - he was in most evenings and that was always a big trouble to us because - we were happier when he was out of the house, you see, because then the - the boys were freer to do what they wanted and we were freer but as the years went on he seemed to g
e
t more and more - isolated, you know, and just wanting to sit - sit by the fireside, either reading or - always drinking and - he used to recite an awful lot and - I can remember the agony of having to be Desdemona. You see, he knew all the tragedies of S
h
akespeare and he would - he would enact them, you see, half drunk he would enact them. And he used to go stalking round the house, you know, he had a - he was a majestic man and - stalking round the house, you know, giving us Hamlet's - soliloquies and al
l
 these long speeches and if he took - Othello he would fling me suddenly into an - either an armchair or on the old horse - horsehair sofa and smother me with a - with a cushion, you know. I can remember to this day the stuffy old cushion that he used to 
put over my mouth. And then just as suddenly he would fall back in his chair and he would say - the pity of it Iago, the pity of it. And it was his own soliloquy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
It was the pity of it you see, that he could do that kind of thing so magnificently, and yet you see, and consequently everybody went out and left me with him - that was the - the bitterest part. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 See, the lads were so fed up with this, you see, that they cleared off out to their own particular - mates homes or wherever they went. Mother used to sne
ak out to go and sit with one of the neighbours and Kathy would be at some meeting or other because by that time she'd joined the trade union, well, she joined - she had to join the trade union the first day she went to work. Father was an ardent trade un
ionist and made us join the trade union, you see. And she was always out at trade union meetings because she was the first woman to ever get on a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 card room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  committee - they'd always been men 'til she invaded them, you see, so she was always out of the way a
nd I was left with father and consequently I always had to be some character in - in these plays you see, either Ophelia or Desdemona or somebody else and - and I would be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 persuading}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  him the whole of the time to go to bed - I knew he wouldn't go out - and 
I used to sit on his knee and try to persuade him ardently - well, come to bed dad - come to bed, dad. All to get him out of the place so that when the others came home they'd have a little bit of peace you see. But - I was a kind of little }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 heroic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  martyr. 
I look back on it now and realize you see. But - that - that was largely how - how the evenings were spent. If they were nice evenings and I could of course escape out into the street to play with the other children, well, we did that, you see, and left h
im in more or less alone, you see, then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did he ever take part in any sport himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, I don't - he wasn't a sporting man - no. No, I don't ever remember him either joining a bowling club or anything of that kind. The only thing I - I do know 
him was he was a good card player and of course at dominoes and draughts, you see, but I don't remember him having any hobby at all - or any other outside interest apart from this period when he was in the home rule movement, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Apart from his actual betting on the horses did he ever go to the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Occasionally when he was in fund. If he'd won any money he would probably go perhaps to Liverpool or somewhere near where there was a racecourse - Manchester or Liverpool you see, but I don't r
eally think he was interested so much in watching the horses as he was in the hope of winning something, you see, and there is this about him that if he did win everybody in the street knew about it and everybody more or less had to share in it. He was ve
r
y generous when he won, but not very generous to his family - he would just occasionally buy the boys - one of the boys - a suit, you know, a decent suit out of his winnings but I don't remember anything ever coming much into the house, you see, and - but
 everybody outside had to have drinks with him, you see. But I don't - I don't think really he was interested in watching - watching the game - as he was in the - this hope that he was - he was going to be lucky, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You mentioned saving for burial and such like - I gather that your father and mother belonged to a club for this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Yes, they - they had pennies and tuppences you know - a penny a week on the children and probably, I don't know, it was the custom of course to have you
r relatives insured, you know, but I - I don't think they - I never remember them saying or hearing anything about if any relative died they'd come into anything so I can only think that it was just the - the home - the home where it - where they were ins
ured you see. People in the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was there any savings scheme for sickness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
None at all - no. No, you had to depend, as I say, on either the sixpenny doctor or the - the other doctor that you paid off at so much a week and - no, I don't remember
 - I don't even remember them having any saving clubs at school. You, know, like they have - they do have now - I don't remember. Of course it was a - a - we were a terribly poor family and you see, one of the things about - our poverty was that at that -
 
I think - I think it probably still is in being in the Catholics - you had to contribute - every family had to contribute what they called Peter's pence. You'd to pay a certain sum each week. Well now, mother wouldn't pay. I - I can remember the collector
 coming on a Saturday afternoon and arguing with her and trying to persuade her and I can remember now hearing her say she says - Peter's pence?, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 Takes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  me all me time }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 t\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
keep kids in food and, you know, never mind about Peter's pence. And we were in the blac
k books through that, and I felt I suffered at school a great deal because, see we were one of the families who'd opted out of Peter's pence, you see, and it - I think it did - it did have an affect on my schooling. Whereas if we'd have been one of the fa
milies who'd contributed they would have taken more interest, you see in both Emily and I and - but I don't remember that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11536143  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
there was any margin - ever any margin for saving up. I don't really. In fact they were once or twice in the hands of the money lenders
. I - I can remember that because - I - I more or less let the cat out of the bag one morning by - you see, father - I don't know whether they were father's debts or what - that they were trying to clear, but he persuaded mother to sign a form saying that
 
they wanted a loan and they would repay it back, you know, at so much a week, that kind of thing, and I noticed that every morning everything was all spruced and cleaned and mother did special things about the house, you see, then that a man came and - of
 
course, unconsciously I mentioned something about this to Kathy - when Kathy was in the house - and of course she knew then what was happening so there was a furious - furious row about that, you see, she strongly objected to - borrowing money from money 
l
enders and having to pay back at exorbitant rates of interest and I know she lent mother money - pretty often out of her savings to - settle this thing - this debt or whatever it was, you see. So there was no margin for saving up clubs at all - no. Not in
 our family anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Apart from the church organizations that you belonged to were there any youth organisations that you could belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I don't know that I knew of any. Because, you see, our activities, as I say, were in the streets and 
we had every year a court and alley concert. There was a choir - a town's choir who called themselves the court and ally concert society and they used to go round to the poorer streets giving concerts in the summer and that was an event that we always loo
k
ed forward to because they used to bring a piano on a truck and - pushed by boys you see - and - it created quite a commotion you see, this piano coming in the street on a truck and being unloaded against a gable end, you see, then the conductor would sta
n
d on a borrowed chair and the choir would sing away, you see, and - we kids thought it was wonderful. Everybody came and stood - the older people came and stood at their doors, you see, there was nowhere to sit and - until the concert finished, you see, a
n
d then of course, we hurrahed them and cheered them and - followed the - the little truck that was taking the piano away, you know - great glee. And it was that kind of thing that we spent our time on, we - I - I don't remember any clubs. I might have bee
n you see, if I'd been attached to either Church of England or the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Wesleyans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 but we weren't you see - we were in a sense isolated there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have any hobbies like collecting anything or keeping pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, I don't - I don't remember - I was - I
 used to play an awful lot at being teacher of a class and I used - I had a lot of books, old books, story books and things, and I used to paste - names on of the - the scholars that I knew - in - in school you see. And I used to set this school out on th
e
 stairs, you see, the stairs and every evening I was teaching these and of course whacking those who I didn't particularly like at school. And I used to do an awful lot of that and of course talk to myself a tremendous amount - used to talk to myself trem
e
ndous and occasionally we went to the park to go to the museum - there was a museum - Chadwicks museum was there then - and we used to do that kind of thing, but - not a lot of jollity - not like you would - you would expect from a boys or girls club, you
 see, I - I don't remember anything of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you go for walks at all apart from going with your father for his drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No, no, I didn't know the country until I was - probably fourteen. Our walks were mainly looking at shop windows, you see, w
andering up and down Dean Road or Derby Street, you see, or going into town looking at shops. It was only - that father did of course introduce me to the country by the Sunday morning walks but we hadn't - you see, there wasn't an age of coaches, we'd onl
y
 the horse trams and then the electric trams came, you see, but they only ran a short distance up Dean Road, you see, you couldn't get very far only by walking and walking was never sort of considered by us as a kind of pursuit, you know, if you know what
 I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You wouldn't have such a thing as a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
I got one later on - but I had to buy it myself. I remember spending twenty - five shillings on it I - that was when I was working - I saved up sixpence a week until I got this twenty-five shi
llings and then I bought this secondhand bicycle and then began of course the outings. I joined a club, the Clarions Cycle Club and those were glorious days because for the first time I came to know the moorlands and the beautiful country and - until I ce
a
sed cycling they were great days and that was how I really became to know more about the countryside - it was just kind of mystery to us as children, you see. We could only - we walked to Barrowbridge we thought we'd gone to world's end, you see, it used 
to seem so far away, you see, and in the heart of the country and it was only by bicycle - getting a bicycle that I learned - that - how lovely the country was, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you ever go on the lake at Barrowbridge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, they had a great big -
 they had great big clumsy wooden boats, you know, penny around - penny round the lake. I never enjoyed it because I never was fond of boats being near the water but we did go on and of course they'd a lot of roundabouts there as well - swings you know, a
n
d different things and we used to like going to Barrowbridge because of that. And then the cottages - used to brew tea - jugs of tea, you see, so that was - those were kind of gala days when we had a penny or tuppence for tram fares you know, bus fares wh
en the buses started running - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would that be at weekends or holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, mainly - mainly weekends. They were kind of special occasions really. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you ever take part in any sport yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, again I was rather wooden
 as sports because you see we never had any at school - we'd no - we'd only a very - confined playground and we were never taught anything like baseball or tennis or any of that and we had - I can only remember later on when I - probably nine - they intro
duced - physical }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 instructor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 - a young man - we'd never had a man teacher - we'd always been taught by the nuns you see, and they were very gentle and didn't encourage sports you see, didn't encourage you rushing around you know - you could play demure games
 in the - in the yard but not - not sporty and I remember this young man, we had to - he insisted on having the lessons outside. Well the schoolyard - it was used by both infants and the older girls so to our surprise they took us into a spare ground that
 
lay on one side of the church and there was a big stone monument - with steps up it and this was the memorial to a - a bygone dead priest you see and I was terribly shocked to see this young man mount these steps and use it as a platform, you see, to give
 
his talks. And of course he - he tried to - well, there were graves all about - little bits of lumpy bits of ground - it was very awkward if we stood on these little lumps and 'course he showed us these exercises you see and - I was - as a child I was awf
u
lly shocked to think - again you see I had curious ideas about the dead and - I - I'd thought about this dead priest you see lying under this monument and I thought it was awful bad behaviour to be doing physical jerks in this little cemetery. Of course i
t
 isn't there now - it's probably been built over but - that was how I felt about it. We were never encouraged you see to - have sports and - I tried to learn tennis later on and when I joined this - we joined a club at Tottington - we had a camp there - t
h
e cycle club I mean - mainly cyclists - and we spent hours and hours panting forth and getting all hot and bothered about learning tennis but it - I used to get an awful lot of colds because I perspired so strenuously that immediately afterwards I seemed 
t
o go cold and then I got bad colds so I had to give that up. Swimming - yes. I - the - they did - they did once institute - a swimming group at the school but - I - I developed something, I think it was a bad ear, I know my ear was very bad for a long tim
e
 and I was withdrawn from the group there, but I took it up at High Street baths and of course became a fairly - a fairly good swimmer. But - I think those were about the only sports my - my - the one I loved best was walking. I learned to enjoy walking v
ery, very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When you were a member of the cycling club was that as you were getting into adult life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 I was sixteen when I joined - yes, sixteen - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When you were a child did you ever go to a theatre or a cinema?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 We went to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 pantomime}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 . My sister - the eldest sister again - was responsible for taking us to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 pantomime}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
. which we used - we used to go in the gods of course, it was the old theatre and it was sixpence to go up in the gods and of course there was no backs to the se
ats - it was just a gallery. You were all crowded in you see and I can remember they used to sell hot pot cakes and oranges you know, lads with trays you know, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  they stepped down these steps these hot - these cakes and pies used to bob up and
 was all sorts of funny things went on before the curtain went up. But we always - we loved that - we loved going to the panto. That was a treat that my sister saw - saw that we had later on, you see. Now, the first time that I remember that I ever saw an
 
opera was when I'd started to work and I used to get a shilling in the pound pocket money, you see, and - which was what - a penny in the shilling - a penny in the shilling of pocket money. Well, I would probably be earning perhaps about fourteen shilling
s - something like that - so I was allowed to keep a penny in a shilling fourteenpence out of the wage I turned up so I began to save some of this and I remember going to Gilbert and Sullivan and I didn't know who }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Gilbert}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and Sullivan was but I remember goi
ng down to a matinee at Bolton theatre and queuing up - I would be fourteen - and queueing up in this long dark alleyway and then climbing all these steps, you see, and sitting down and - what - what annoyed me was that you'd all - you'd go early because 
y
ou paid early door price, you see, you got - you paid an extra tuppence to go in early doors - and - you'd go and pay this extra tuppence and get - sit down - and then right on the last minute a lot of people would come crowding in and there would be an u
sher who would come down - shove up there, shove up there, shove up, and we had to shove up and make way for people who'd come in at the last minute and hadn't paid this tuppence and I used to be very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 incensed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  about this injustice, you see, and you nearly a
lways got fleas on you because you were so near to everybody else, you know, everybody's elbows were poking into you and you had fleas on you but I was absolutely enthralled with this opera - it was the Yeoman of the Guard - and I couldn't take my eyes of
f
 it and - oh, the lilting tunes and the dresses, you see, it was just a new world to me. I raced home and - they were all having tea - or were getting round the table and I announced that I didn't want any tea - only a drink of tea. I was running back - I
 
was going to the night - the night performance - the evening performance. They all thought I'd gone potty and - but anyway I rushed back and I queued up again for this evening performance and it was that funny one - what is it that they - the - they - it'
s
 a Japanesey thing you know - Mikado. And oh, I thought it was wonderful - I never really, you know, had experienced anything like it - I was in a new world entirely. Well, of course, whenever the op - they came to Bolton I was there, you see, I never mis
s
ed any of them. And then - then from that I graduate to opera - grand opera. My sister was interested in opera because she'd then joined the choral society and so Rudy Manners used to come, you know, Rudy Manners and the old - what's that big company they
 have now in London - not the Covent Garden - the other - they used to come an awful lot. Oh, I used to be there every night. I used to spend all me money - spare money that I had on - on - on the operas you see. And that of course - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Sadler\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  Wells, yes, th
ey used to come to Bolton quite a lot in those days. And, again I used to just go in the gods and then as we - got in when I got in this cycling club, you see, we got interested in the Manchester theatre because Miss Horniman had opened, you know, the Pri
n
ces Theatre, Manchester and she was showing a lot of Galsworthy's plays you see and of course a group of us on a Saturday afternoon then used to - we used to save up and then we used to go to Manchester - it was only a shilling the bus - the fares in thos
e
 days - and we'd either go up in the gods or stand up - you see, standing room only and we saw most of Shaw's plays produced there. Well, that again, Shaw and Galsworthy and these early playwrights - it was just wonderful and of course that made me a conv
i
nced socialist you see - especially Shaw's play you see. And that again was - a - a great source of happiness. Well, it probably was the only relief that I got from the - monotonous job of working in a factory you see. But none of that came in early - in 
early childhood, you see, that all came more or less after I'd started working you see from fourteen to about sixteen or seventeen. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
And I came in touch with the Halle Orchestra through that - started to be a member of the Halle Orchestra and used to book th
e seasons concerts, you know, and - oh that was - it was wonderful, you know, under the different conductors, you know, Rich - Richter and oh, there was a lot of wonderful conductors and so I got introduced to very fine music through that, you see.}{
