\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Can you tell me how old you were when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh well, compulsory five, you see. You couldn't go before because they had no - nursery classes or any of that kind and I remember Emily taking me, you see, I was five - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You didn't have any tuition before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
None. Apart from - probably - I would probably be trying to read I should think because I was interested in trying to make out letterings you know in shop windows and that kind of thing. Probably I knew
 a bit of reading but very little of course. No, I hadn't had any tuition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What were the school hours when you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, nine to twelve and then, I think it was half past one to about four for the infants, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And it was the Catholic school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 A day school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 It was mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Mixed - yes. But we were in separate buildings - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How far away was the school - how long did it take you to get there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well it was very near where we had lived when w
e were in Milk Street, you see, it was - it was that neighbourhood, you see, and so we had to go from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Rankin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 Street up Noble Street onto Derby Street and then cross the road to where the school was near Pilkington Street. Pilkington Street and - and near w
here we had originally lived, you see. The school was in Pilkington Street and Fletcher Street sort of - it was - part in Pilkington Street, part in Fletcher Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 About how long did it take you to get there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, of course, if you ran which 
- which we usually did it wouldn't take more than probably ten minutes or quarter - quarter of an hour. If you walked and loitered looking at things of course it could take you a good twenty minutes, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, at first wh
en my sister was at the school we went together, you see. Emily, yes, yes. We went together because there weren't many Catholics who lived in the Street. Most of the other children went of course to the board school you know on Dean Road, you see, their w
ay diverted from ours - we had to go up to Derby Street whereas they went Elean Road, you see, went to the board - the board - what was board school in those - the state school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Apart from the school being a dingy building what did you think about going to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I always liked it. I can give you my first impressions of going at five because - it was a big - a gallery. Again there were no forms - no seats - it was just a high gallery like that and these steps were far too high for our littl
e baby legs - I can remember so - you know - having to scramble. There was one teacher who was only a pupil teacher - probably sixteen, a girl sixteen or seventeen - in charge and it was a huge class and - I can remember feeling very strange and very lone
l
y. Sit on this - rather high up from where the teacher was down there and there were all little tots besides myself and we were all very quiet and very strange and the only thing I can remember being taught was the coloured ball frame. They had one of the
s
e old fashioned coloured ball frames and in order to teach us to count she shot the yellow ball and the red ball, the blue ball, you see, and of course I was fascinated - I always was fascinated with colours and that's the one thing that I remember most v
i
vidly about the first day at school and - then Emily called for me, you see, at the end of the school day - to pick me up - I had to wait for her coming out of the bigger school and she would bring me home. The only thing I can remember is the chanting, y
ou see, twice one or two, twice two are four, twice three are six - we all had to learn that way - chanting, you see. Now when - after I'd been in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 gallery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  - in the infants gallery for twelve months we were moved then into the infants school proper and a
gain that was a long room with three or four classes in it you see, not separated in any way. And - this was a rather strange thing. Now this infants school was mixed - it was little boys and little girls, you see, we weren't separated - the sexes weren't
 separated in the infants. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
But one of the things that - that struck me as being odd was - occasionally we had a young curate came who, presumably, were in training to be priests, you see, and I remember distinctly when I was in this infant group one young m
an coming and he always looked like a farmer. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
He was always red faced and very jolly and he used to come to test us on our - catechism, you see. And then after he'd tested us, on - we had to be very, very quiet and very good when he was there and after he'
d tested on this catechism he would then say - now, all come out and kick the teacher. And she was only a young girl about - as I say - about sixteen or seventeen - and there would be a mad rush from the benches - there were benches then you see, not this
 
gallery thing, and particularly the boys and they would come and that teacher had a hell of a time. And I used to sit cowering wondering what on earth was going to happen next because I hated rows - I'd been brought up with so many rows at home that I was
 
terrified of - people shouting and these lads used to kick this - kick her shins terribly - and she used to suffer it with a kind of sickly smile and there would be just a few of us who would never get up - never get up out of our places and - and then af
t
er about ten minutes of this hurly-burly, he would say, clap his hands, yes, yes, that's enough, that's enough. And he would just go out laughing like a great big schoolboy and leave the teacher then to restore the class to order and I used to feel terrib
l
y sorry for this poor girl you see. And I - I couldn't see why it was done and up to this day can I unless it was a sadistic trait that was in him. And I remember her once coming round and she said you were one of the little girls that don't come out and 
kick me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
And I thought, isn't it awful - to think that that has stayed with - stayed with me all this time and that was the only thing that I didn't like about that school - I was glad when I was old enough to move into the - you know, the more adult - adul
t part because there we were under}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11536143  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 the nuns. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
They were very gentle you see and we had none of that - that kind - but, oh, it used to be - it used to be awful - all these lads yelling and - and pulling at her skirt and - oh, it was dreadful - and I couldn't
, in my childish mind, you know, understand why, you see, why it was done, you see. So I don't really say I enjoyed the infant part of the education but when I got into the bigger school, yes, I - I - I felt more at home, you see, and although the - the t
h
ings that - oh we were taught were pretty much the three R's you see, we never got much beyond the three R's. And religion was of course very, very strongly emphasised you see, very, very strongly emphasised. But perhaps that was - perhaps that was a good
 thing really in it's way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did the nuns emphasise any other things as being important - things like manners or tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Tidiness - yes, because I can remember very much the teacher telling us that we had to come with clean hands and we had to h
ave our clogs polished you see. And occasionally unbeknownst to us she would make an examination. And what a to-do there was - spitting on our hands - and we used to spit on our clogs then polish them on the back of our - you know - we had - wore thick st
o
ckings - we'd polish. We just managed to scrape through - I - I never got - I never got either punished or a note given to me to tell me mother to send me but some of it was more luck than good management, you see, but she did stress very strongly coming 
w
ith clean hands and trying to keep ourselves clean you see and - and she was very particular about us coming in clean clogs, you see. What was the other thing that you mentioned? Manners. Well, she - they were very, very - quiet nuns and of course perhaps
 
they expected their manners to be imitated - I don't remember them telling us very much about we ought to be mannerly. They did of course reach. We ought to love one another, you know, and not - not fall out with each other and not be unkind and not to co
py and things like that. But - I don't think that they ever gave us any set lessons, you know, in kind of being mannerly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You were of course always a punctual attender?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was punctuality important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, yes, it was - it was co
nsidered important in school. I remember that - there used to be a few late-comers come panting, you know, up on the last minute and of course occasionally the nun - the teacher would take them on - on one side you see and speak to them about it. But on t
he whole it was - it was emphasised punctuality.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Ways of speaking - did they concern themselves with the way you spoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. That was one of the things they did not attend to. If you spoke badly, which a great many of us did, you see, dropped our 
h's, we never knew why we had to sound the h's - there wasn't much notice taken of it. No. No, they didn't - they didn't bother about that kind of thing which another - another school probably would, you see. They were more really concerned with trying to
 
keep us quiet and getting the - the curriculum, you see, the lessons in the curriculum done and that seemed about the total - total output. I don't remember any very illuminating - things - I mean that when I - later when I began to study - literature, I 
r
ealised what glorious opportunities there had been for giving us some good English lessons but we hardly ever had it. Grammar - yes, a bit of grammar at the beginning but then I skipped standard three - they jumped me from standard two into standard four 
a
nd possibly I missed quite a lot of grammar through that you see, through that jump. We had a lot of composition, you know, dictation - writing from dictation and that kind of thing but they never really stirred your imagination as they - they might - I t
h
ink they might have done, you see. But you were always being questioned on religion - why you had - in fact the priest used to come in nearly every Monday morning and ask - and this was when they had a Sunday school - because of course you were expected t
o
 go to Mass because that was a mortal sin you see, if you missed Mass and - but when they had the Sunday school, he once came in the priest, unexpectedly, and went round the class asking us all individually why we hadn't been to Sunday school. Well, it wa
s
 amazing all the excuses - there'd been very few gone to Sunday school - and when it came to me I was stumped for an excuse and for once in a while I told the truth - and said it was my fault that I didn't go. And he said well, for telling the truth I sha
l
l excuse you the punishment. I always remember that. And it was only because I was stumped - there - there'd been so many before me - made all sorts of excuses about their mother being ill or somebody else or something else that when it got to me I just d
i
dn't know what to say and so I just blurted out, well, Father, it was - I - I could have gone - it was my own fault, you see, so I got let off because I'd been honest for once. But the emphasis was rather on that - on goodness and gentleness, you see, and
 
- on the whole I can't say that - that the discipline wasn't good. I can't remember - we - of course we did get caned and we had one teacher - a - a nun who was called Sister Sebastian, I always remember her, and she had a face full of sorrow, lined with 
a
 - sorrow that used to fascinate me and often instead of thinking about what we were doing I would be gazing at her trying to understand why she had all these lines, you see, on her face. She had a dreadful temper and she used to say to us when we were na
ughty and troublesome, she used to get her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 fist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  clenched like that and she used to say come out you so-and-so, I'll an - I'll 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 annihilate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you. That was it - I'll }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 annihilate}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you - oh, she'd a furious passion. And she'd a bunch of ironmongery hanging from her 
- from her dress, you know, keys and scissors and button hooks, all sorts of things, ooh, and you used to get such a clout on your knuckles with it. It - it told you know. But almost in a few minutes the passion would die down and she'd just have this fac
e
 like a - a dying Christ almost. She used to fascinate me. And she was - she was a terrible - disciplinarian - you'd not hardly to move you know, or - or whisper at all but she had you out you see. And the boys - oh, they did used to - don't - didn't half
 used to get their knuckles - crashed. With this bunch of ironmongery.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were there any other sorts of punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 I - I didn't see a lot of physical punishment. No, they used to rely more on - sending - sending you up to the - headmistress, you s
ee, the head nun, and she more or less would have a talk with you - very quiet talk, and - say that they would - if your conduct didn't improve they would report you to your parents and things like that you see. No, I didn't see a lot of - of physical pun
i
shment - even from other teachers - not when we were in the big room because otherwise we would have seen it you see because we - our eyes were always straying to other classes - what other classes were doing, you see, rather than attending to what we wer
e
 doing ourselves. And I know they used to let the boys - up to that standard - learn drawing but the girls had to take sewing and I rather resented that because I always had a longing to draw, you see, and I never got any tuition in it and I used to have 
t
o do this sewing, which I did and which - the - the teacher used to say was very neat but it was done against the grain - I would have preferred - I would preferred the drawing lesson, you see, than having to do the sewing. But I was pretty submissive - I
 was a passive child really, and - but I - I enjoyed school on the whole - I enjoyed school and was rather sorry when I had to leave.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I accepted them fully, you see, I'd no resentment at all against any 
of them. And rather liked the gentleness you see, and of course the piety because I was very - pious little Catholic at that time because I - I used to have an altar at home on the bedroom - cornice and - used to spend what little money I had on candles a
n
d - flowers and things like that and I had a statue on and - it was a very, very - in my childish way - a very devoted little Catholic you see, so I accepted them fully, you see, I didn't question - didn't question their ability to teach or whether they w
e
re going the right way or the wrong way about it, you see, I just sort of accepted it. The only thing I didn't like was, of course, the - awful pictures that we had on the wall you know of Christ with the dagger through his heart, you know, and blood drop
ping it - I - I used to be fascinated with these terrible pictures but wondered why on earth they were in a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 school, you see, because there was nothing pleasant about them to look at you see. I don't suppose they're there now - but they were really - you know - all to do with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 crucifixion}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 and that kind of thing and it used to depress me terribly, you see, I wanted to see a smiling Christ not - not this agonizing figure, you see, that was - seemed to be everywhere - everywhere about the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, I'm afraid they didn't. Mind you we rarely ever had homework until I got into the last standard. And then when I was about twelve we got a new - headmistress - a new nun and she seemed to 
have come from a much better school and she then - made the lessons very, very interesting - she was a very good drawer and I can remember she used to take our copy books and draw something - it might be an animal, it might be an object - and then she wou
l
d ask us to write on the opposite side of the page what we thought about this object, you see. And I was very interested in that, you see, and - occasionally she would give us homework to do - and - when I got home I used to show it to my eldest sister yo
u
 see and of course she used to say little things about either this little animal or whatever the object was and of course I think the headmistress gave me praise really for having had the advice of an older sister, you see, and she used to say that my ess
ays on these things were very - very good and very interesting. And she did - she did bring a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 liveliness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 about teaching that we hadn't had previously and I remember she introduced the Mill on the Floss as a book we should read, you see, of George Elliott's,
 and quite a number of very interesting things. It seemed to me as though in the earlier stages they were so afraid of giving us anything to read that wasn't partly religious you see, that we never seemed to get into a wider field at all and she did and i
t was a pity really that I hadn't - I hadn't opened out to her when I was leaving school because when I went to ask for my school leaving papers, you see, we all - always had to get our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
attendances}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you know - she said, I'm very disappointed that you are lea
ving school. And I just said, yes I'm sorry too, you see. But nothing no more and possibly if I'd had the courage to have opened out and said to her, well, are there any means by which I could be helped, you know, to stay on at school because there were n
o scholarships, it might have made a difference but she didn't open out and I didn't you see and so I just left, see, just like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 A lot of them did but on the other hand the
y had a sprinkling of girls from much better homes. And - they were very well dressed you see and they were teachers favourites - teachers pets, you see, and I used to feel that somewhat because - the singular thing was that I never got a prize and - they
 
often had books to give out as prizes and - I used to notice that the prizes went to the well dressed girls, you see, and then they would apologise and say they'd forgotten me and so they would give me an old dog-eared, you know, book and - and I would be
 
so disgusted I wouldn't take it home and I used to give it to one of the other children on the way home, you see, I used to be so sort of disgusted to think that they'd measured what I could do by this dog-eared book when they'd given these beautiful new 
books to other girls who were nowhere near as accomplished but of course, as I say, probably paid generously to Peter's pence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, there were gangs. Yes. Yes, because these better girls ganged tog
ether you see. They scarcely ever played with us and one incident that stands out very clearly is that, as I told you before I used to go to school looking like Joseph's coat of many colours, but my sister always saw to it that I had a big white pinafore 
c
overing it all. Well one day we were in the playground and I must have been feeling very happy and there were a few of us pirouetting round you see, dancing - like ballet dancers - and this pinafore was lifted up, you see, floating round like that and all
 at once I became conscious of some girls shouting one, two, three and when I turned round I realized they were counting the different colours in me frock you see - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 patches}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  here, sleeves different colour, you see, and I just dropped - I can remember just dr
opping this pinafore and slinking away feeling very hurt and bewildered you see, that they could do that because it was rather cruel to me, you see, and - but they did - they were always in a gang these - these very well dressed girls and - I could only t
h
ink - some of their parents of course were business people with businesses you see and consequently they had a fairly high standard of living and they - they could always take part in everything, you see, there were collections for any charity or anything
 they could always - pay up you see, and then they were always being chosen either for May Queens or carrying banners, you know, in the Whitsuntide }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 procession}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and I never could - they shut - they asked me but of course it was always too much money to dress 
up you see, and so I never got to - string a banner, you see, as they said - I was always in the - and there were other groups you see - groups that were poor like - like me and we probably ganged up together you see. And - it was kind of an economic - gr
o
uping rather than a - a - a grouping of people with the same interests, you see, it was rather on an economic basis I should think our - our ganging up as it were. And yet, you see, the - the odd thing was that on one occasion they had a - a vote - a ball
o
t vote for the most popular girl in the school and this - girl was explained by the nuns had - well, they were - they'd been collecting and we'd been paying a penny a week or something like that - for some fund in - that the Bishop of Salford had - introd
u
ced. It was the building of a new church somewhere and so the - this new teacher that had come - this headmistress, you see, said - oh we shall do it the democratic way - every child, every girl in the school will have a vote and you must nominate who you
 
want to be the - popular girl in the school and then you vote. Well to my great surprise I was moved as the most popular girl in the school - I wasn't not by any means - not popular and - I won it. There was about ten nominated but I got the highest numbe
r
 of votes which staggered me completely because it was something I'd never expected and I don't even think that the nuns were too pleased about that - they would rather have had a very pious Catholic, you see, and - but anyway I went to Salford to some hi
g
h Mass. I can remember going and I can remember kneeling at the Bishops feet and kissing his ring and he thanked me for what the school had done although I hadn't contributed very much I must confess, but you see, that was the strange thing, that the scho
o
l must have been - had a big proportion of poor children who would nominated me and voted for me than the - the richer girls you see. They were in the list of course - they were nominated but you see they weren't - and I can only think that I was popular 
t
hrough the fact that I - I was a good story teller you see, and when we had any odd moment I used to be telling them stories, you see and possibly it was that that brought the popularity. But strange all the same. I often wonder about it. It was the only 
- the only prize that I ever got - if you can call it a prize.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes. Yes, very many regrets. Yes, I should have loved to have been a teacher - loved to have been a teacher and you see, when I'd got
 into the mill - and I must have been probably sixteen I - I - well of course after I started - after I left school I went to night school, you see, they had a night school and it was in this same assembly hall that they later had to turn - and this - per
s
on who was in charge of the class was the same person who had the organ - who was the organist, you see, she wasn't a nun, she was the organist for the church and she was the teacher. And she was interested in me and she said it was a shame that they let 
y
ou leave the school, I'll lend you a book on grammar. Well, you see, I had nobody to help me - it was just a book on grammar and nobody seemed willing to help me with it - you see, I read some of it and tried to master some of it and then years after - pr
o
bably when I was about sixteen or seventeen somebody came from the church and said they'd now built - the Catholics had now built a secondary school and would I like to go and have tuition there. But you see, I - I'd broken - I'd broken my student days an
d
 - I felt that I should have to, you know, it would be too hard for me to catch up and then we were still poor and - I - I really felt that I could hardly ask the family to let me leave the mill and go to school for the length of time I would have liked t
o
 have gone to this secondary school, you see, to - to have caught up. And so it was turned down but - I guess I have many regrets about - about not having had an adequate education. That's why I'm so very, very interested in education for other people. Ve
ry interested. 'Cos I think it's such a training ground you know. Training ground not only for jobs but for character and personality.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes. Yes, I did. Because - of course, I mean to say, histo
ry had been more or less a closed book to me, you see. And so I got very, very interested in history. Geography, not so much but literature - yes, and we used to have poetry - poetry sessions and of course, well, I was O.K. with that because I'd had done 
s
uch - I had heard such a lot of it at home, you see. Yes, there were certain subjects that I was very interested in - would have loved to have gone further with them you see. And that was why later on I came to regret that I hadn't taken my sister's advic
e and left that school and gone to one where they had - scholarships because I did feel I had the capacity to - win a scholarship you see, but it - the - the chance had gone by you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  classes did you attend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 ? Well
, really when I first went it was the - it was more or less English you see - grammar and writing essays and then they added onto it shorthand and I was interested in shorthand so I began to take the commercial courses, you see, then I got a free scholars
hip from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 to go to the central school which was in Great Moore Street - you know, it was the kind of central - higher grade they called it - higher grade school. Well, there it was rather funny because - they sent - they give - they sent me 
a form to fill in, you see, with the subjects I would like to take and they sent a syllabus and strangely enough - 'course I suppose I was always an oddity - I put down economics - economics - what was the other? Something else. Forget what the other subj
e
ct was but - it was akin to economics. And I got a letter asking me to go down to the education office that the Chairman of the Education Committee wished to have an interview with me and so I - I went down there and - I remember he was - the Chairman of 
t
hat - the Education Committee was a Mr Horrocks. He had a - a train of tripe shops in Bolton, you see, and the Education Officer was with him, Mr Longworth, and they both looked at me rather queerly and they said we're - questioning the subjects that you 
w
ant to take with this kind of free scholarship that I'd got and he said what does a girl like you want he said with economics. And for a minute or two I was nonplussed and then I said, well, I know a lot about economics - I've read part of Marx's Das Kapi
t
al. Worst thing I could have said. Father had a copy of Marx's Das Kapital in - on our selves you see, and I'd delved into it from time to time - I didn't understand it. And there was something else and they queried this and - he said - oh, logic and eloc
u
tion. And they queried this and so when I said that I knew so - well, if you'd seen their faces and they must have thought this is a budding revolutionist we'd better chop her wings off so they said, no, now going to put you in the millinery class - the w
orst thing they could have put me down for - and it - sort of be a good girl and good night that's it. So I went quite dutifully the following Monday night to this class in - millinery and I always remember it - was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 women\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  institute you know. And there
 was a very nice lady taking it and I remember her giving us all a piece of velvet and we had to learn to him it without the stitches coming through, and I was bored stiff 'cos I wasn't interested in hats at all - or clothes and - anyway I stuck it, I tho
u
gh well I - I'd better they said I have to - have to accept it so I'd better and so I went to the elocution and logic class and I didn't understand a word of the logic - he was drawing diagrams on the board you know, proposition one, two, three and I didn
'
t follow it or understand it but I liked the elocution. The elocutionist was a lady and so she was teaching us how to project our voice and she gave us a poem, Mary, call the cattle home across the sands at Dee, to learn. Oh I was thrilled with this. I mu
s
t have said that poem hundreds of times at home - I'm sure they must have gotten absolutely sick to death of Mary, call the cattle home but I was trying to get it perfect for this person, oh, I thought it was wonderful. Anyway it so happened that this log
i
c and elocution class had to be changed to the same night as the millinery class - something went wrong - I don't know what it was - but we had to change it. Oh, this was a glorious opportunity. So I wrote a very nice letter to the Director of Education p
o
inting out that I had attended the millinery class but now it was clashing with the one literature - why, elocution and logic and as I was very happy in that class I hoped they would leave me where I was, yours truly. I never heard a word. So after that I
 
did join the commercial course at the higher grade - all sorts of things - shorthand typing, banking, commercial subjects you see and that enabled me of course later on to get the office job you see, although I wasn't sort of working for it - I was just -
 it was just because it was an interest and it was something to do at night you see. And that was the end of me learn - taking economics - they weren't for letting me have economics. Eeh it's funny isn't it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have any part time job at all to earn a little money while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No. I - I'm afraid that we were a family that didn't - didn't put much - emphasise on earning money. We did a lot of voluntary jobs but we did it in such a way we never thought we were doing it really
. For example, mother always insisted that we did errands for people - elderly people or sick people, you see, and I used to run errands day in day out for people you see and scarcely even dreamed that I should ever have anything for it, you see, occasion
a
lly you got a penny or something like that but in the sense of earning money - no. There were boys who went round with the newspapers, you see, and they would probably receive something but - that never came into sort of our discussions at all and we - I 
u
sed to do quite a lot of baby sitting, you see, if people who had numerous babies and wanted to go out either shopping or visiting then mother would send us to sit with the younger children, you see, and so that I never really got - got any money. I can o
nly remember one old lady at the bottom of the street who used to send me for an awful lot of - of errands and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 she would say - I'll bay thee a gold watch at Christmas - and I really believed her you see, that at Christmas there would be a gold wa
tch you see, and it never came and - but it never brought any - any sort of regrets or anything - it was just a promise that had been broken, you see, I just looked at it as a promise that had been broken - but it was that kind of thing that we filled in 
our spare time with - it was - we never - I never had a - an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 instinct}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 for earning money really - not really - no. Never bothered me very much about it if I'd just enough to live on that was - that was enough you see, so I didn't do any part time jobs for money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Your first job was in the fancy goods shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, that was after leaving school 3/8 yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did you get it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, there was an advertisement in the Evening News. And also I happened to know that the girl who previously had worke
d there who was now of course an adult had and was a member of the church that we attended, you see, she was a Catholic, and I knew that she had worked at this particular shop, you see, so that when my sister saw the advert in the Evening News she said, w
hy not put in for it, you see, so I wrote and was interviewed and given the job you see. But of course it only lasted one month. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
'Course the funny part about that was that the man - the owner of the shop - used to - dodge in and out you see and strangely en
ough, in the afternoons he would just come in - just look probably at a poster or some of the invoice and then he would dash off and then the lady who kept the shop used to tell me to run after him and follow him and find out where he was going. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I wa
s anything but a detective and I used to loss him in the crowd - you see he was only a little chap and I never - I never succeeded in finding out where he went - probably he went to a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 men
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  club I should think by his - his speech and attitude. But when I c
ame back I used to get scolded terribly because I'd failed, you see, and - I think that was really what ended the job - not so much about my being too quiet and inoffensive but rather that I was a failure in being a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 sleuth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  hound you see, so I always remember that little funny bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 During the short time that you were there what hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, we started at eight in the morning and most evenings it was eight in the evening before the shop closed, you see, longer even on a Friday night or
 Saturday night. They were long hours for shops in those days. Yes. I should say from eight to eight o'clock or nine at night, you see. Eight o'clock usually but - longer on Friday and Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have a half day at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Wednesday afternoo
n - yes. Yes, Wednesday afternoon - which was not much good to me because I didn't know any other shop girls you see and consequently it was not - it was an afternoon that I sort of didn't go anywhere, you see, just sort of lounged about more or less at h
ome, you see. It wasn't a day of - that I would have called recreation - you see, not for me, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 You said that your first wage was four and eleven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 That was in the mill. This - this wage was four shillings. Four shillings per week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you feel that that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I thought it was a poor one but you had to make a beginning you see so that the four shillings was accepted without any protest, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you give the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Oh yes, yes, all of it - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would she put this into the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, it went into the family pool - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you get any of it back as pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, we - we - we used to get - supposed to get a penny in the shilling so probably I would ge
t threepence or fourpence, you see, out of it - yes, That was a standard - a penny in a shilling in those days for most working class homes. Was a kind of a standard that most people accepted without question, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did the employer treat you on the whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
You mean in the shop? Oh well, I couldn't really complain - the - there was a lady of course in charge. This was not the - the proprietors wife - a - a lady in charge of you - she was very nice and very quiet and - seemed to know - she w
as very efficient and she gave me what orders there were to be given in the morning, dusting and emptying boxes and - you know, keeping check on stock coming in and going out and - re-ticketing prices on goods that kind of thing - she was very efficient a
n
d very nice - I had no - no call to - to query anything about her. The lady - the manageress, she was very dictatorial and - I never - I hardly ever spoke to her and she hardly ever spoke to me apart from just being angry and saying I was stupid when I ca
m
e back and said that I had not succeeded in finding out where Mr so-and-so had gone, you see, and she thought I was stupid really. But we didn't have much conversation so I can't say that there was any sort of cruelty or anything of that kind - oh no. It 
w
as just, I think, that they decided I was a failure almost from the first week and it was just a case of putting up with it until the months was over you see, I - I - you felt that - there was no encouragement I mean to say, now if you want to be a succes
s for - there was no training - if you want to be a successful shop assistant you must try to do this that and the other you see. They didn't. And one of the things that seemed to annoy or perhaps not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143 anger them}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  is the right word - puzzle them was that I us
ed to take cocoa - we had to take our own afternoon tea because the hours were so long you see, you went back about two o'clock and you had an hour for lunch and then you see it was from two 'til eight or later, so they instructed me to take some tea and 
y
ou used to brew it down in a cellar base - in a basement of the shop. But I used to take cocoa and I think they thought I was odd - odd in that - drinking cocoa at teatime you see. Why I just - I just don't know why it was cocoa but mother put it up you s
ee and that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did you feel about the work yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
Well, it was hum-drum - I felt that I - I was doing a lot of - dirty work that I hadn't anticipated, you see, because I'd always thought that shop assistants were always dressed up, 
you see, and very clean but they gave me an awful lot of clean - in fact I really felt that the month had been spent more in cleaning the shop out than in learning anything because they'd a tremendous amount of stock - boxes and boxes and boxes stacked up
 
you see which were covered with the dust of - oh, it must have been a long, long time since they were ever dusted and I had to climb this ladder you see and clean all these boxes and I was always more or less covered with dust, you see, and then they used
 to ask me to scrub the floor behind the counter - behind the counter it was bare boards. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The counter that the customer saw of course was quite nice }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 linoleum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  you see. But I had to scrub this floor and I do remember her saying I was a good scrubber and I sup
pose that was why the lady when she wrote said she's a good girl and a clean girl, you see, but will never make a shop assistant - I was clean because I'd been taught to clean at home, you see, scrub and do. But that wasn't being a shop assistant, you see
,
 and that in a sense rather disappointed me but I was quite prepared to stay on if it led to training you see but there didn't seem to be any training in the offing it was just you were a kind of errand girl and clean - cleaning up you see. I was never al
lowed to serve anybody or - tell then the price of things you see, I was just sort of in the background.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And after your months trial you tried to find a job in suitable places and failed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And eventually your mother told you try at the mill didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 To get the job in the mill did you go to the mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh yes, you had - no they, of course in those - at that particular period the mills we not busy, you see, either. Trade was very, very bad that was why I got so d
ownhearted going round day after day, you see, because mother insisted that I went every day you see, somewhere and the result was that when I went to the mill there was quite a lot of girls the same age - all school leavers you see all more or less being
 interviewed together and - what I rather resented in my childish mind was the way they - they eyed you over almost like an animal, you see, and I wasn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 loquacious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  at all - I just could answer yes and no and often I fell by the way because some of the girl
s you see were very sharp very quick and they were chosen you see for jobs and I began to think I was a failure - was a - beginning to think I was a failure and then this - manager, whoever he was, was inter - interviewing us said, you can - you can start
 
here and you, you see, and he picked a few of us out. And - but we didn't know what we were starting at or anything - we only knew the wage which was five shillings per week - it was given to me as five shillings per week and we had to - start, I think it
 
was about the week following, and - I can just remember being examined by a doctor - they had a doctor who came to the mill to examine you for cleanliness and - you were only in a few minutes. He just looked at your hair to see if your hair was clean and 
a
sked if you'd had any serious illnesses and just looked you up and down sort of thing and asked you a few questions and you were passed, you see, you were - you'd passed the doctor. So then you were taken into the mill and - well, I had several jobs befor
e
 I got into the weaving shed - they tried - whether it was a came of trying you or whether it was that adults were away sick or something of that kind but I did get several jobs. Well, the first - the first job that I had was - it was in a weaving mill th
a
t it was knotting - they put all the school leavers more or less together in one room and they were long table in this room and you knotted quilts - it was what was called a quilt mill - that was bedspreads they wove bedspreads you see, and these bedsprea
d
s in those days had fringes, you know, short fringes, and you had to knot these fringes - take each alternate bunch of ends as it were and knot them and you used to put - have a - put a little ticket in to say that you had knotted that - that quilt and yo
u
 were paid piecework and they were frightfully badly paid. In fact I never knew what a bordall was 'til I went to this mill and a bordall was a half a farthing and some of the quilts were - you were just paid a half a farthing - some was a farthing - a bo
r
dall and then a farthing and then you might get a half - threefarthings and a ha'penny but never a penny. Ha'penny was the highest rate you were paid, you see, according to the size of the bedspread - for a double bed you would get a ha'penny - for a sing
l
e bed you would get half you see, and a farthing and so on, and then all this was totaled up at the weekend and then you got your wage. Well it was a frightful wage - I could - some girls could make five shillings but I never could. Presumably because I h
a
d a very tender skin and in those days the quilts were - we - what we called very low picked, you may not know what that means, but that means that there were so few picks put in the weaving of the cloth that there were tiny little holes left you see, so 
t
o fill these holes up so that they would become more sellable in the shops they used to stick these quilts in a bath of size and the size - the sizing of them filled most of these little holes up so that you - you - you didn't detect them you see. But it 
a
lso made the fringe very, very stiff, you see, because it was a kind of starch and - the friction, you see, of constantly knotting these used to fray the skin off your fingers and - the - the most cruel part was that if you got a drop of blood on the frin
g
e you didn't get paid - you were fined for faulty material you see. And this made me very, very bitter. And so after some weeks I asked my mother could I leave - that I both detested the job and hated really having to go because they were very unkind to u
s
. They had a woman who was in charge, a rather short tempered angry woman and often I saw her deliberately, when you'd put your ticket your little ticket in this quilt she would do that like that and the ticket would fly out and you never got that registe
r
ed as being part of your earnings you see. And I resented it very, very much, you see. So I asked my mother could I leave. And she said yes, if I could find another job. So from there I went to another mill and I was happier there and as I say I did one o
r
 two - this was a mill that had both spinning and weaving - the two separate, you see, functions. So they put me in the spinning part for a beginning and I had a - a little job there which I quite liked and - I was in a - a small room with about probably 
e
ight or nine other women and I got - I seemed to get on very well with them and I worked pretty hard and as - I was always punctual and they liked me and I rather liked them but then after a time there the manager came and asked would I transfer to the we
a
ving side and I had no objections - I didn't know what the new job was going to be or anything about it and that was a fixed wage as I say of five shillings you see. So I went across from this spinning side to the weaving side and for sometime I used to s
i
t on the floor in the warehouse merely nicking blankets that had to be - they were weaving blankets and they head a little threat, you see, the whole length of the blanket was woven in the loom and then to separate it they put a threat in it and went on w
e
aving, you see, and all the sheets and blankets went on a roller. Well, my job was to have a pair of scissors and every time the blankets came over the roller you had to nick this little bit so that other people tore it across later on you see. Well, it w
a
s very, very monotonous but there was nothing to it and - I - I wasn't unhappy there It was monotonous and you often got very sleepy, you see, doing nothing but these coming over and just doing this, you see. But anyway that seemed to fade out the - the m
i
ll became slacker as it were and so they asked me then to transfer into the weaving shed. And there I was - rather terrified - the noise was dreadful because these other previous jobs had been rather quiet ones, you see, not much machinery. And I had to g
o
 round more or less collecting what they call bobbin heads and these were little bobbins that - the - the - weft was wound on and which the weaver put into the shuttle and when the yarn had woven off these - these things dropped more or less on the floor.
 The - the weaver should have picked them up and put them into a utensil but I suppose they were so busy they never bothered. So these little - they were little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 pearls}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  like that - little bobbin heads - they were needed by the winders in the winding room to 
rewind the weft on them and when they got short they hadn't - a great supply of them, I had to go round the shed picking these little bobbin heads up - putting them in a basket and carrying them back, you see. Well, I - I can't say that I liked that reall
y
 because it was work that entailed going all over the shed in between the machines and I was terrified of these flying shuttles and there was very little protection of machinery in those days - they have to be protected now by the factory act - but in tho
s
e days it - most of it was unfenced and I used to see some shocking accidents. The weavers would have their - their aprons torn off them you see caught in some wheel or something and sometimes they had head - head injuries and arm injuries and I - I reall
y
 was scared - I was a scared child and - I used to have to grope under the looms you see to find these little bobbin heads because they - they used to roll. And then I realised that - that when I got my wages I'd only got four and eleven and I couldn't un
d
erstand why a penny had been deducted and I asked several of the - of my mates but they didn't seem to know anything about it. I asked the manager - the man who was over us - the overseer and he said he knew nothing about it and he said if you're dissatis
f
ied you'd better go to the office. And so I found my way in fear and trembling to the office and timidly asked why - why I was supposed to get five shillings a week and I was only getting four and eleven and I was growled at and informed that the penny wa
s
 deducted by the British Empire Cotton Growing Association - that they were growing cotton to compete with the Egyptian cotton etcetera and all the mills had to contribute something towards this Empire Cotton Association which I resented very, very much. 
I
 had to accept it because the reply was you see, if you don't like it you know what to do - get out - you see, that was always the thing that was held over your head. So I never got any satisfaction there and - then later on they asked me to go into the w
i
nding room and - which I liked better than being in the weaving shed because, of course, it was quieter - there wasn't as much noise - but we were in a basement, it was a very depressing room, there was no direct light - we had artificial light on all day
, but - the work was better than going round this terrible weaving shed and I stayed there for quite a number of years - 'til -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you only spend a very short time in these previous?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes, a very short time really - yes. And the majority of my w
orking life in the mill was between the weaving shed - I went back into the weaving shed, you see, after I'd learned this winding, I - I was in the winding for quite a long time and then went into the weaving shed more or less to learn to weave with a - a
n elderly person, you see. And then I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 About how old would you be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I came out at twenty-one, you see. I went in at thirteen and came out at twenty-one. And probably would be doing these odd jobs for about - 'til I was about sixteen I 
should thing and then I - I got the settled job you see, winding and then from winding to the weaving you see. Yes. But there were a lot of things that - were very, very unpleasant in the mill in those days - I don't say it is now because of course some o
f
 the modern mills are very, very up to date, you see. But we had no canteen of any kind - you just had to go in the morning at six - six - you'd start at six o'clock and then the engine stopped at eight o'clock - you hurried home, if you could get home - 
y
ou nearly had to run all the way because you'd only half an hour, and this mill that I was at was about quarter of an hours distance from home, so that you'd to run all the way. Mother would just have the tea out and the bread and butter, whatever you wer
e
 having - you didn't have very - very much more than bread and butter and jam or marmalade - and then you'd to rush back again because you'd to be in at half past eight for the engine starting again, and if you did happen to be late you had to go through 
w
hat we called a watch house - there was a - a very angry old man in - and you were fined - you were what we called bated, you see, if you came late - they bated you, they'd take - they took a penny - or more out of your wage for the minute or two you were
 late, you see, which again I - I very much resented.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were you on piece work at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Yes, when I was in the winding room I was on piece work and when I was in the weaving shed - first we had just a small wage as a little tenter, you see, te
nting with a woman, but when you came to weave you were on piece work. So what I resented was that you were losing money by being late yourself you see, and then in addition the - the - they fined you, you see, which again was something that I resented ve
r
y much. And then there was no red cross - there was no first aid at all and if you got injured or if anybody was sick it depended on the other people who were working round about to take the person home - they'd no ambulances or anything - and - often - I
 
was supposed to be quite good natured - if anybody got hurt or they were sick, then I would volunteer to go home with them, you see, to take them home. So that I used to take the sick person home and then go back to the mill and I'd lost my wage - my earn
i
ng capacity, you see. And they never gave you anything - they never compensated you in any way, you see for these little jobs that you did - the little human jobs, and I used to be very disgus - disgusted with the - arrangements for washing. We had no hot
 
water, only cold water and the sinks were filthy. They were always full of tea leaves and old wet newspapers, you see, a lot of them stayed in the mill both for breakfast and dinner and they brought jugs of tea with all the leaves - tea leaves at the bott
o
m, well then it was just poured into the sink and they were really filthy. I hated having to go even for a drink of cold water because they were so filthy and the toilets were inadequate and in a very dark part of the mill and you avoided as much as possi
b
le going to the toilets, you see. There were no facilities and much of it was dirty work because you had to clean your own machinery, Saturday morning you see the engine stopped at eleven o'clock and - or half past eleven in that - in some cases, and you 
h
ad to do all the dirty oily cleaning on your hands and knees under the looms and you'd nowhere then - no hot water to wash your hands you see, and we used to have to go to the mill lodge - mills were then run by steam you see - and the water was dirty but
 
steamy, and you used to kneel down by the mill lodge and clean yourself before you went home on a Saturday. And as I say again I - I resented that kind of thing, you see. We had - when we were on piece - when we were on day wage we were given a little che
c
k with your number on - we were known by numbers not by names - and when you were enter the mill you used to put this little check on a board to say that you'd arrived and then at night you took it off to say - more or less say you were departing - and dr
o
pped it in another box you see. But of course, when you were on piece work that didn't apply, see. But - there were a lot of things - they - they were a harsh uncouth crowd, the people who were more or less over you and - hardly knew how to talk - how to 
s
peak to you and again - that always irritated me you see. But - I liked - I liked the work people - I liked the people that I worked with and always - always did because although they many of them were rough and uncouth they were very, very kind and they 
h
ad a - a very strong sense of humour you see. 'Course it probably was a good job that - it enabled them to stick to the job, you see. But I was one of the rebels - very quickly, and - of course that was probably why I got the trade union job later on you 
s
ee, because when there was anything wrong they used to come to me and say what did I think about it and if things got so very bad about bad yarns and - things like that, well, we - we used to form a kind of small deputation you see. And - I can remember t
h
e very first deputation I went on - we'd been bothering about whatever it was for weeks and weeks to have it put right and nothing ever happened so then in desperation we decided that we would go up to the management. Well, of course, in those early days 
I
 hadn't learned the art of negotiating and of course afterwards I could see what ought to have been done but we went in a body, you see, and the office was at the end of a very, very long - the managers office was at the end of a very long passage - and I
 
can remember us tramping down this passage like an army, you know, our clogs sounding and we got to this door and we knocked very timidly and a great voice shouted, come in, you know. Well, could hardly all get in we were - were so many of us, you see, an
d
 he turned round, you know, and he said, shut that door. Shut that door, and then, you know, what did we want. Well, the abuse we got was terrible - he wouldn't even listen and - he just absolutely brow beat us and I - I was supposed to be the spokeswoman
 
and I was stammering - you know - about these things and he just turned round to me - I can - I can always remember it - and he said, next thing, he said, you'll - you'll be asking me to provide sofas for you sit down on, and he bad us all get back to our
 work under the pain of being dismissed you see. Well, we all fell out of this room in disorder, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 you see}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
, and went back. But we christened him old sofa - he never got any name - any name after that, out sofa - he were out sofa. And we never had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 any respect}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  
for him - he lost all the respect - and - he reigned for years with this kind of bullying - bullying attitude because the - the trade was so bad you daren't say anything, you see, you just had to put up with it. And it was that that got me going to the tr
a
de union, you see. The men were very well organized - the men weavers because they were an old association you see and trade unionism seems to come naturally to men and they - they always used to say to you, you don't want put up with it - get down to off
i
ce, you know, that sort of thing. So then we shifted our tactics from - bearding the manager in his den and going down to the office - they called it club then - go down t'club - going down to the club and reporting these things that were wrong and lettin
g the trade union secretary deal with them, you see, to see if he could negotiate between us and the management, you see. And of course, under that system we fared much better because we were not brow beaten the same, you see, as we had been previously.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When did you actually join the trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh, well, I had to join almost the first week I went in the mill. Father was a strong trade unionist, you see, and he insisted on any - any of the lads or the - Emily and I when we went in the mill had t
o join straight away. So the - the - it was a little collector that used to come round and it was funny that later on I found that this little collector had worked in the mill and they had called him hell-for-leather, or something, he had a nick - they al
l had nick - nick-names. And it was because he was a weaver and he used to go pushing through the shed, you know, through the broad }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 alleys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  and that with all this cloth on his shoulder - in those days they'd to carry all the woven cloth, you see - and he'd h
ave great huge packs of - of a - of sheetings or quilts on his shoulder - get out of road - get out of road, you know, he was so keen on earning money you see. And so he started coming to our house collecting and - sometimes mother would say, Alice is not
 very satisfied, there's a lot of things going wrong at the mill. Tell her to go down club - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 tell her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 go down club - you see, that attitude. And it - they were - a form - all the collectors that they had in the trade union at that time were former cotton op
eratives, they got the jobs by virtue of being cotton workers, you see. So that - I got very familiar with going down t'club, as we say, you see, and reporting things and - getting the women, of course, to join the trade union and that wasn't easy in thos
e
 days, you see. There were quite a lot of the - the operatives did join but we always had a bunch of - non-members, you know, who would - who would say, oh, unions no good to me, you see, sort of thing but that was how I got interested and I was only - I 
w
ould only be thirteen when I joined you see, because I had to join almost immediately - and remained, of course, and am still a member of the weavers association. I still pay my trade union money, you see. There was always a strong loyalty in our family t
o
 the trade union, you see, Kathy was on the committee of the cardroom association and she was very, very keen, you see, on women trying to get better conditions and better wages for the women in the cardroom so that we were all - always I think rather str
ong on the trade union side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was there any sort of feeling between the people who belonged to the trade union and those who didn't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes. Sometimes they did. For instance, if we managed to get a little bit of a wage increase, you see, or if we man
aged to get - better - a few better facilities we would then go round and use it as a kind of argument, you see, and say well, now look you're benefiting by what the trade unions and don't you think you ought to join. Quite a lot of them did. They would s
a
y, oh yes, yes, I agree they've done something for us. But there was - there was always a hard headedness, you know, about Lancashire people - they must see something for their money. They never like paying money and not seeing anything tangible and it wa
s
 only at - at points like that - and there were not many of them until the - the first world war, because things were very static - very static, you see. And - but some of them would join and round about me in - where I worked we were very solid but - you
 
see, you couldn't go all over the mill, you hadn't the time, you see, or the facilities either, because, you see, if they saw you prowling round any - any - where else you - you were severely ticked off, you see, for not being in your own alley - you had 
t
o be, you see, in your own alley attending to your own looms or machines. So - and some of them, of course, were - reluctant to join because - it was only fourpence, it was fourpence a week then - and they were rather reluctant because of course fourpence
 
was fourpence in those days, you see, and often they would only join on the promise of bad trade benefit. You see, we had a bad trade benefit, so that when you were - you were stopped, out of work, they would pay - we used to get about six shillings a wee
k
, you see. And we cheerfully came on strike, you see, for - for six shillings a week - in those days, yes. If we felt that it was justified, you see, and it might not have been our place that was out on strike - it might have been somewhere else - but - s
omehow or other there was a loyalty - a basic loyalty - and we came out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was there any distinction felt between the trained craftspeople and the untrained?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes - I should say there was - there was a bit of aloofness. Yes, there was a bit of a - 
for instance, the overlookers in the weaving shed were considered the aristocrats, you see, and - they had a - a fairly good wage as compared, of course, to the weavers although there was in those days what we called a driving system which again the - the
 
trade unions had to fight years and years to get rid of - whereby the overlooker had a basic wage. But then on top of it he got a percentage of the weavers earnings - so it always made him that he was always bullying the weavers, you see, to keep their ea
r
nings up because his bonus depended on it you see. And they used to have a slate system which would - was very - very much resented - and he used to put slates up on the walls giving the earnings of all the weavers in the shed and, of course, the bottom p
e
ople were always told about the top notchers, you see. Mary so-and-so, well, she made so-and-so and if Mary so-and-so could do it you could do it, you see, irrespective of what sort of work you had in or your capabilities, you see. And we resented that ve
r
y much, you see, because some of them, of course, hadn't - well, they weren't - they weren't educated, you see, and they used to go in the mill before the engine started, doing jobs - we called it knob-sticking - and working during the dinner hour which w
as again you see breaking the rules and the regulations - but it gave them the chance of earning better money, you see. And it was those kinds of things that we resented about the slate system. And that was done }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 away }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 with afterwards and the overlookers more
 or less put on a kind of standing wage, you see. But they were always considered the aristocrats, you see, of the industry - foremen and that kind of thing and consequently there was a feeling that - we were two classes as it were. The people down below 
and - the people - people at the top, as it were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 How did your wage alter during the time you were there between the ages of thirteen and twenty-one, you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes. Well, when I went in of course, as I said, I was getting four and eleven - five s
hillings with a penny deducted - and by the time I left I was averaging eighteen shillings a week, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Were you then a skilled weaver?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Averaging eighteen or twenty. Occasionally I got a pound but it - it had to be some good work, you know, 
something that wove pretty well. Yes, I should say it was average because I was a hard worker - I mean, I was conscientious, you see, and always at the back of my mind was not the ability to make profits for the employer or anything of that kind - rather 
t
he home conditions, you see, always had at the back of my mind that sad face of my mother and I always wanted to earn as much as I could in order to bring something into the home to give us a little - a little more - you know, a little more culture, and -
 and more - a few luxuries, you see, we hadn't many, but - that was what I worked for really. So that I should say it was pretty average - pretty average.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Did you have any training period for any of the jobs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No. Oh - no, you were put with someb
ody else and the first jobs that I had well it was only an hour - probably an hour or so because they were simple jobs, you see, and then you were left on your own. But of course when it became more skilled like the winding and the warping - the - that wa
s
 more skilled you see and you had to be more careful about it, well, there you would be put with another woman - to learn. But it wouldn't be more than a day or two, you see, at the most. And then you were given a set of what we call ends in the winding o
r
 warping room or you were placed with a woman in the weaving shed. But in the weaving shed it was much longer because it was more skilled - more highly skilled you see. And they only moved you to do - to go on a loom yourself providing the missus - we cal
l
 them missus that we're under - said she was fit to be moved. She had to say whether the girl under her - the little tender - was fit to be - and then she wasn't altogether left on her own because if they gave her loom somebody else was supposed to kind o
f
 keep an eye on her. But you hadn't any training as they have today, you see, the girls in the weave - now - go in a special room and they're trained away from the shed altogether, you see, but there was nothing of that you know. You'd no - no set trainin
g.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 Would you say that anybody who described themselves as a mistress - as duffing mistress or such - was inevitably a skilled worker?}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The doffing mistress? Oh I should say that she'd worked there quite a while and was - was very capable of doing 
the job herself but I wouldn't say that she'd ever been trained in - human relationships or anything of that kind. They never knew how to speak to you, scarcely ever, you see all that was in the background - it wasn't considered part of the - of the job. 
I
t was only the mechanical process that really mattered - not the way you encouraged them or handled them or anything of that kind, you see. It was a - a - it was a - oh, I used to think brutal rather because the human element scarcely ever came in - scarc
e
ly ever came in. And nowadays of course they do train the - the doffing mistress or the - the - they call them supervisors in the sheds now - to know how to talk to the operative you see and not to - expect too much or - try to encourage them to do the th
ings that you think is best for that particular job - but there was no - nothing of that, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
No welfare and no - no welfare officers or anything that were really trained, you see, it was just the operative that worked there and either got - got on wit
h the foreman - there was a lot of favouritism of course - certain people pushing their own relatives in and that kind of thing which of course is inevitable, but that was how it came about we - we - there was really no training. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 I asked that question because of this business of classifying people into skilled semi-skilled and unskilled workers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
I'm a little doubtful as to just which jobs would come into which categories at that time. The term semi-skilled was really hardly in use was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
No, not really. No, it wasn't. That only came later you see. Because there was such a lot of odd labouring jobs that were - you - you couldn't say they were skilled - they were odd labouring jobs. You know, for instance, if - if there were a s
lack period and they had - hadn't any orders for certain types you were asked to sweep the floors and the sheds and things like that, you see. Any odd job that came available you were more or less expected to do it, you see, without any resentment at all 
-
 merely to keep you in a job so you'd have a wage you see. But there was no grading really, the two jobs of course in the factories at that time were spinners - spinners were the aristocrats, you see, in the spinning side, because they employed the little
 
piecer and the side piecer who worked with them, you understand that. So they were the aristocrats and of course they wouldn't - they would have women - girls - in the - in the spinning room more or less doffing and doing odd jobs like that but they never
 
would allow them to become a spinner, you see, they could never rise to the top job. And it was - it was like that in the shed - weaving was classed as more highly skilled than - any other job in the weaving side, you see. Warping was - was supposed to be
 
more highly skilled than winding, you see. But that - there wasn't a great deal of - of kind of rigid class - by job - qualifications or anything - you more or less were expected - and yet on of the biggest grievances that I met later on, as a trade union
 
official, was the narrowness in which they kept - kept you, you know. You were - if you were a weaver you were a weaver for life, you see. If you were a winder you were a winder for life and so on through all the jobs. You were never encouraged or expecte
d
 to do anything else only that one particular job. Consequently you developed a closed mind on anything else and you were simply not interested in all the other processes, you see. Well, then later oh, you see, when automatic machinery became - introduced
 
into the mills you'd got to get people to change their minds on these kind of things, you see, and oh, it was - it was dreadful. In fact there is still a lot of opposition, even yet I understand, in the mills towards - modern machinery, you see, like the 
-
 water loom - where - where the yarns go through water - the shuttleless looms and things like that, you see, because they've been brought up in such a - in their early days I mean - in such a rigid narrow circle that mobility doesn't mean anything. It di
d
n't in those days of course we are becoming more mobile now. But that was one of the things that you felt frustrated with - that there was no offer of promotion - you could only see yourself, and most of the people that used to come in the office would sa
y
 to me, Miss Foley, I'm now nearly sixty and I'm doing the job - the same job that I went into the mill at fourteen. You see, there was no - no sort of higher reaches that they could - so consequently we nearly always lost to our trade union movement the 
m
ost intelligent people. I used to look round my committee and used to think, yes, that's a bright girl but I shall lose her soon. And inevitably when there were other opportunities they went, you see, and we were left with the rather hard core of - well, 
w
hy bother - you see, why bother about anything, you see. It's yielding us a wage and that's all that matters, you see. No, there were no avenues of promotion - especially for women. The men, now they - the lads who came in, they could - they could with a 
g
reat deal of struggle of course, get into the hut to be an overlooker apprenticed - they had an apprenticeship and there were certain jobs in the mills like the mechanics and that who had apprenticeships. Well, they could hope - the bright boys - for some
thing better but not the girls - no, there was nothing for the girls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was it when you were twenty-one that you went into the office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, how that came about was - I don't suppose ever I would have got out of the mill but for the fact that it w
as Lloyd George's insurance act, you know. And in 1914 - well, it was brought in - talked about in 1912 - then it became bill in 1913 and became operative early 1914 and it was agreed, you see, in the interests of democracy at that time that the trade uni
o
ns could become approved societies - approved societies where the trade union could administer the national insurance health act, you see. And consequently they had to have sick visitors to go round - looking at the sick people - mainly because they thoug
h of malingering, you see, and paying out the sick - the sickness benefits, the maternity benefits and disablement benefits etcetera. Well, they had to have two each - each association with so many members had to have two women sick visitors - we were a }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 women\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 organization largely in those days, you see, the men - there were a few men weavers but not a great lot because slowly as they died out or the war came and they - they enlisted there was very, very few men left, you see. So the soc - the association -
 weavers association advertised for two sick visitors - women sick visitors of course. Now, again, I wasn't applying - I just felt I hadn't the education, I hadn't the personality and it was only this little collector - the trade union collector that came
 in and he says - hey, what about one of these jobs 3/8 - he says - that's going for a sick visitor. So he says, are you not going to apply? And I said oh no, I don't think I would get it, I said, I don't really know anything. But I was going then to the 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 night schools}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 learning shorthand and typing, you see, commercial subject. And he says, take a tip from me, put in for it. So with that I did. But if he hadn't have spoken I shouldn't have applied, I was - you know, I - I mean I always have been never pushing
 - never pushing. And I applied and to my great surprise they sent for me for an interview and then I got a letter to say I'd been appointed - I wasn't really of age, you had to be twenty-one but I wasn't twenty-one I was twenty and so then I asked the se
c
retary afterwards when he'd written to say I was - I'd been appointed and he wished me well, I said, do you know I put the wrong age on I said I was twenty-one but I wasn't. And he said, oh that doesn't matter, he said, its only a few months and - you - b
e
fore you - you start working you'll have turned twenty-one, you see. So with - that was, how I got it. Well, it was - it was a delight to leave the mill, oh yes, didn't I feel glad and - but one of the things that hurt me was that it was only the woman I 
w
orked with wished me well. And they were - they were thrilled to bits with it and they thought - they said some very nice things to me but the manager and the people who you would have expected - they never said one word. I just went in and handed me noti
c
e in and they just took it like a scrap of paper, never said, well, we're sorry to lose you, sort of thing or any - perhaps - perhaps some of them were glad to get rid of me - and when I came out for the last time through that watch house I could have wep
t
 to think that I'd worked for them seven years, you see, and there was not one word of goodbye hope you're - hope you're happy in your new job or any - not a word and that was the atmosphere, you see, that atmosphere that there was. But anyway I settled d
o
wn and I was very happy. I used to - I had to get a bicycle and ran - well, it was - oh, I'd started to learn riding a bicycle and they'd asked me had I a bicycle and I said yes, so I had to go round because it was a very, very big district and it was Wes
t
 Horton and Horwich and Astley and Farnworth and Walkden and all - oh all over the place. And - but I was free, you see, I was free. And we used to have to take the money out and carry a great big bag of money - you couldn't do it today, you'd get cashed 
you see - and take the forms with you and - get them to fill them in and when they started to be ill and what - what it was all about. And then you used to have to visit those that you felt were dodging a bit, you see, because the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13978893 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  women - they had t
he tendency of course to want to stay at home and do some of the housework. Well, it was prohibited you see, was doing house chores whilst, you were sick you were supposed to be sick you see. So that part of it I didn't like - I didn't like the rather - t
h
e atmosphere of doing a bit of spying but it had to be done. And then you see, the war broke out and the assistant secretary was called up for service so the secretary, Mr Speke, suggested that - if I would learn more about calculations - arithmetic and c
a
lculating the sorts he would like to transfer me from that side - the insurance side - to the office. I probably would be about sixteen or seventeen then and - oh no, I was twenty-one of course, I'd - he was - I'd turned twenty-one then, but I had - I was
 
still going as - at twenty-one to the night schools doing - doing different things. So with that I tackled arithmetic and I went to have some private lessons in decimals and calculations and things and then moved over to the office side and of course did 
t
he office work - did the typewriting and the shorthand, the letters and - that was different than being outside - I missed the outside because I missed meeting people, you see, meeting people in their homes because I got into a lot of miner's homes - coal
 
and cotton have always been very, very close you see and the mines, of course, were then in existence then in West Horton and Astley, all round there. Consequently I got very, very friendly with the miners and their wives and - you see. So I missed that p
a
rt of it because I was indoors then more or less all the time. They'd a male committee which did not like women and didn't encourage women and I was a long, long time before I ever got any outside facilities you see, talking to the women. Then we got more
 
into the technique of shop meetings, you see, the employers were not anxious that you - the trade union people should be on the premises and - so we used to take schools pretty near the mill or pubs and meet the operatives there you see. So then I got mor
e outlet in being able to talk - talk to them and help them from my past experience in the mill, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 About when would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I should think a lot of that would be during the war period - from about 1914 to about 1924 or five. Well, 
the man came back, of course, after the war, the man, the assistant secretary, you see, came back about - probably 1919, I think, and so then I didn't get out again as much as I had been doing during the war because he - he started, you see, to take on th
e outside work so again I was more or less in the office just doing the - office routine work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 That meant that there were sort of two assistants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 There were three - yes, there were two of us then - he was the assistant secretary and I was just de
signated the clerk at that time - yes. And then - later on, of course, he - he decided that there wasn't much opportunity for him there because Mr Speke was relatively young - young you see and he couldn't see any sign of promotion so he went over to the 
e
mployers side - he got an offer from the employers association and to our - we were rather shocked because in those days you looked upon it as a desertion you see, but anyway he went over to the - to the employers. Well then they decided to advertise for 
a
 - an assistant secretary and to my chagrin they limited it to males - only men members must apply. And we'd not a great many - we'd probably about two hundred men out of about - oh well, at that time we must have had eighteen thousand members - and I was
 
very, very annoyed and often wished that at that point I had left the trade union and offered me services to something else you see because I felt very hurt to think that I'd done such a lot of work for them and then just because you were a woman you hadn
'
t to have your chance. Anyway, I suppose my loyalty kept me there and - they didn't appoint anybody. The applicant - applicants were so poor, from the men, they failed in the examination. So we went on without an assistant secretary for quite a while and 
t
hen they decided to advertise again and this time they dropped the word male out. So I put in again and went to sit for the examination - there were just two women with about might men putting in - and - Mr Speke afterwards told me that I'd come out with 
t
op marks and that I was thirty or forty marks in advance of the highest man, but they wouldn't appoint me. Again the - an - animosity towards women, you see. So I had to wait until Mr Speke himself decided to retire. Oh, they did make me as a kind of - co
n
solation prize - they said oh well we'll raise Miss Foley's salary and we'll call her the woman officer. So instead of being the clerk I was designated the woman officer and more or less took on the work of the assistant secretaryship then, had more scope
. But - I didn't get to be the Secretary until Mr Speke resigned and then of course I was called the secretary. But it was a long - it was a long uphill struggle, you see, and - much of it I enjoyed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 So that being a welfare officer would have appealed to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
It would have appealed to me on the - on the side of the operatives. I don't know of course how I should have got on altogether with the - managerial side, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13568115\charrsid11536143 
