I think, after the school leaving age was raised and - they said it - the youngsters were more or less getting bored with it. You know, they didn't like the idea of going back to school again and it was - it was - eventually they wound up. But that was an
 
enlightened firm and - they had - they had - the welfare - the welfare arrangements were, compared to the other places, were very, very good indeed. And they knew how to treat people and they got a better class - a better type of operative through it. I u
s
ed to be amazed how well dressed the - girls were and the women and how nicely they spoke as compared to some of the other mills, you see, because there was this kind of element of culture there, you see, and - of course their - they - they're not Tootal 
B
roadhurst Lees now - they're in a big merger you know and - but they still continue I think with the - with the welfare facilities, you see, they always have spent a good proportion of the profits on welfare and they also have a very, very good pension sc
h
eme you see and they - also allow the operatives to join in the other profit sharing scheme you see and at the end of every year, if there are profits, the - they have a share, they have a proportion of it - they share it out you see. So they were - they 
