\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Not - oh, no. No, shift work only came in - there was overtime work during the war but it was for war purposes - aero
plane cloths and things like that, you know, in the first world war now I'm talking about. So that we had to agree to overtime although the cotton industry's always been opposed fundamentally to overtime. And - but we had to agree to it because of the urg
e
ncy of war orders, you see, and but there were no shift working like this - double shift - six to two, two 'til ten and now of course we're on - there is a three shift system, you see. But we fought very strongly, did the trade unions, against a shift sys
t
em, you see. We had a lot of struggle with Tootal Broadhurst because they went on a - this Tootal Broadhurst Lees which was the good firm - the went on it in opposition to the trade union and for a number of years we had to communication with them - only 
b
y the operatives coming down to the office to have a - to ask for advice because they didn't approve of the system, you see, and Mr Speke would not negotiate. So the mem - there was a strong membership but we could only do it through advising them you see
.
 This was after the war, yes. And between 1930 and probably 1935 there was, of course, a lot of trouble and disputes about the shift system coming in, you see. Then of course after the - with the second world war it - it just became almost inevitable. The
 competition you see and that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 The mill hours would be pretty much the same would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, when I first started in the mill it was fifty-four hour week, you see, fifty-four. Well, then - we never got any reductions - tremendous l
ong time - 'til 19 - 1918 - at the end of the first world war. And then it - it was reduced to forty-eight, you see. That stayed a long time and then it was reduced to forty-five in order to get Saturday morning for the women, I fought very, very hard for
 
that because the women always used to want Saturday morning off for shopping and cleaning, you see. So we got forty-five. Then it got to forty-three, this is out of my time now, forty-three they have and they've now forty and forty-one-and - a - half. But
 that was a long, long time to wait from 19 - from when - when it was fifty-four hours to come down to forty-eight, you see. But that the ward did - did enable us to do that, you see, to enforce - a shortening of the working day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would you say that your full time work changed your attitude to life?
