how wonderful to think that they'd got all that in that uneducated age, you know, really. It - it really was a marvelous - marvelous little Sunday school. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15297942\charrsid11536143 
And if it was fine on the Sundays when it was in summer they used to tell us to bring some bread and b
utter with us - sandwiches - and instead of coming home afterwards we used to go on the buses out into the country and I knew quite a lot of Rivington - Rivington Pike that I would never have seen but for those little rambles that we used to take - they w
ere - oh, it was an interesting place - very interesting. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 And we'd a little chap who was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15297942\charrsid11536143 genius}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  for music and he was a joiner at Dobsons and Barlows and he used to come and give us lessons on music and honestly the people that he trained to sing - he trai
ned me - I hadn't really no voice but he used to say oh yes, you have, you've a - you've a good voice, and he used to come down and you - we had - we had no sense of notes - we only knew we were going up and going down you see, but my word he trained quit
e
 a lot of good singers and he - he had a choir - he started a choir. And this choir - we used to go to the - temperance hall - we'd a temperance hall then in - in St George's Road where they started the films - the early films were there and we used to go
 
about all over Lancashire singing at Socialist meetings, you know, Victor Grayson, Kier Hardy and all the old stalwarts It was a - it was a - a really good period, that, in my life, very good period. And it - so that I - I really in a sense drifted away f
r
om mother - those - that period - but came back - after - in the second world war because one of the brothers never came back from the first war - he was killed out in France and the second - Tom went out and he was fond of horses and he went in the vetin
a
ry corps and he was away years after the war because they went to Palestine - he crossed the desert with - what was it - General - General - I forget - a famous general - and he used to write the most marvelous letters about crossing the desert and he was
 
fascinated with the stars and the moon and he used to say you want to come out here, Alice, in the desert and then you'll see the moon and the stars and - well, he came back and died - didn't live very long after he came back from Palestine, but - prophes
i
ed this would happen - the war between Israel and the Arabs. He said he liked the Jews very, very much - he thought they were an exceptionally nice race of people but he had no - no - no truck at all with the Arabs - they were sneaky. He said they used to
 
hide everything in the sand but they always knew where they'd hidden it, you know, and they were always stealing and pinching but anyway he - he came back and came back very religious. He had lost his religion before he went but he came back because he'd 
b
een interested in the Padre that was with the troop you see and I think if he'd lived he would have drifted back to the Catholic religion. And we used to have a lot of arguments about socialism and he used to say, yes Alice, I was a Socialist but it doesn
'
t answer everything, it doesn't answer everything. And - but anyway he died so mother was left alone then so that brought us closer - closer together and all the years that I was at the office I devoted most of my - I had very little leisure, but I devote
d
 most of my leisure to try to make up to her for what she had missed, you see, and I used to take her on holidays and take her away for weekends and all sorts of things to bring you know, some - some compensation into her life, you see. So I think she was
 very happy at the end of her life you see. Very happy.
