go down writing poll cards and canvassing and - all - always supported candidates that were put up in the interests of the party. And also when we were cyclists we belonged to the Clarion Club and we used to go on our bicycles anywhere where there were op
e
n air meetings to swell the throng, you know what I mean, and we used to deliver literature and - do all sorts of odd jobs even when they had meetings in the - in the - temperance hall - or the Grand Theatre in Bolton we used to act as ushers, and you kno
w, giving pamphlets out and all that kind of thing. Yes, we were - we were very embroiled in it - in the early days I mean. I started the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15297942\charrsid11536143 women\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  Labour group in Bolton you see, that was during the first world war. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15297942\charrsid11536143 We got a number of women together and of c
ourse there was a lot of grievances from soldiers wives you know about not receiving their pen - their payments at the right time and all that kind of thing so we - we had a mass meeting in a spinners hall - I remember it very vividly - and quite a lot of
 the women joined and we started a - a Women's Labour group which went on for years which I think in fact it's still in being but I don't go now but - we were really very active and we did a lot of voluntary work - yes.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
