\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Is this what you mean or was this something else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, the Socialist club is - is still in number nineteen Wood Street, you know. That was - I suppose really out of that and the demise of the Labour church was born the Sunday schoo
l, but I should imagine that the Socialist club had a lot to do with it because it more or less financed it you see. They were they group that could make money because they had a bar and all this - the drink brought - brought the money in. The Labour chur
c
h didn't - didn't agree you see - they were more - more a temperance group than - and they didn't believe in clubs at all because they thought it lowered the intellectual tone and they didn't of course believe in drinking you see, so they had to close dow
n because they hadn't a bar and they - they were short }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15297942\charrsid11536143 of funds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 but the socialist club prospered because it had this bar upstairs, you see, and they - they financed the socialist Sunday school. Paid the rent of the room you see and that kind of thing. And t
hey were the ones who had the choir - we practiced in the socialist club, you see, they lent us a room for practicing - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What sort of religious element was there in the Labour Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, it was a very strong ethical - ethical influence. T
hey didn't talk so much about God as they talked about man and - their hymns and that were all centred round more or less the wonder of the universe - they believed very strongly in evolution you see, Charles Darwin's evolution and we had any amount of ta
l
ks and lectures on that and - illustrated films, you see, and things of that kind. But they - they didn't - they didn't press - the idea of God so much as they did the fellowship of man - that was the - the main theme that they - they talked about. We had
 
ten socialist commandments and all of them were positive as against the Biblical negativeness, thou shalt not, thou shalt not - you see. They - they were - a very good set and we always opened with reciting the ten commandments you see - the socialist ten
 
commandments I mean and they were all positive you see - love your father and your mother, you see, for what they were doing for you, you see, and it - every one of them began with you know, do or believe or something positive - not thou shalt not, you se
e
, of the - of the Biblical ten commandments. And there were some very, very good brains no doubt amongst the people that came - very tolerant. There was no - no felling of - people might be superior in the sense that they had money and a big house and the
y
'd had education but fundamentally you were all human beings, you see, and if given your chance to bring out the potentials then we would have a better race of men and women, you see, with the emphasis on the potentialities, not on a rather crushing side 
of the logical beliefs you see - believe this because it's tradition - believe that, you see, because it's tradition. No, there was none of that. There was a very open fellowship - very open.
