think I did. Not - not very close personal friends. That's been one, of course, of the things that I've regretted and largely I blamed that on our early childhood. Never being able to invite anybody in the house because we were always afraid father would 
b
e drunk, you see, and Kathy - was the one who - brought - introduced us to very nice people and she always had to run the risk and she used to say to mother - I'm going to bring so-and-so and so to tea this afternoon and think on father and the lads keep 
i
n the back kitchen - they don't come in - don't come in this room, you see. Mother would be very worried about it all because she never knew when there would be an outburst you see, and - mother of course was always nervous and apprehensive - she used to 
say to me, it's now but long curtain talk. See, when they were talking about politics and - and a lot about culture and that you see, now but long curtain talk. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 
And - but she was the one who had that capacity to make friends like that and I couldn't - even 
when I was - when I was older and was supposed to have a rather - well, a better post than in the mill - I never was a great conversationalist and - I remember meeting Ghandi - I liked him very much - you know, the - as - he came over in - what time would
 
it be - it was - oh, I was only - probably about twenty-three - and he came to the office - the - the - Indians had put on the tariff for cotton goods you see, and of course it was - it was hurting the Lancashire cotton industry and Ghandi was coming over
 
to this country for some special purposes and he was staying with a family near Egerton - the Barlows - I think it was the Barlows - who owned Barlow and Jones - and he was staying at their big house up there and so the cotton people persuaded Ghandi to c
ome down to our office and see some of the Lancashire textile people - the trade union side, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
And he came and he brought his little spinning wheel with him and he was spinning all the time he was talking, you see, and I always remember it - I wasn't
 supposed to be there but I was in and out you know and - on - on one occasion when I had to go in for something I heard him say they'd all been lamenting you see about how it was hurting the Lancashire cotton people and how the wages were down to an aver
a
ge of twenty-five shillings a week and this, that and the other and he listened quite calmly and then he says, yes, yes, I understand - but do you realize that my people are working for nine pound a month. You see. And, then in the evening they invited hi
m
 to a - a dinner at the Swan Hotel at which I was invited. And I remember the - they were all tucking in to roast duckling and goodness knows what and poor Ghandi had just dry bread and water and they thought it was just - rubbish you see, and Mr Speke wo
uld say to me, you know, he's a hypocrite. I said, oh no, oh no, no, he isn't hypocrite. I said, he's a saint and you can't appreciate it. And he was really, he was - Ghandi was a saint, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
