i
ons from the W.E.A. and reminding him that he'd had early associations with us, you see, and he wrote a very, very nice letter back. We asked him whilst he was in England - he was in England at the time - could he come and speak for us, you see, in the Bo
l
ton branch, but anyway he said he was - he was far too busy - he was tied up, you know, with all the - leading people. But, I never really in a sense made - made many friends - Mr Speke had a - had a technique that he never agreed with inviting people who
 
were on his committee close to the work to his home. He said it was dangerous - there was always such a lot of catty gossip going on. And so he never did and I never did - I suppose I followed in his footsteps and I never closely associated myself with th
e
 committee. And it perhaps was a mistake - probably was because I know quite a lot of people who used to say, yes, she's all right but she's very stand-offish. Oh, she's a snob. The Labour party once said, we could - we'd like you to stand as a candidate,
 
you know, but you - you're a bit of a snob. Well I never was a snob - never. But I - I had this aloofness that had grown up with me and I never really got very close to people. Only just to - to a few people will I ever open out, you see, because we'd nev
e
r been accustomed to it in the home - it - it was a mistake but it grew up with us and I'm still - the same - rather aloof - rather aloof out - more outside people I think. And even, as I say, getting in touch with a wider circle of trade unionists and th
a
t kind of thing - to some extent I wasn't always in tune with them because one of the things that I always said was I would never force any of my members or even persuade them to do something that I didn't want to do myself or couldn't do myself, you see.
 
And when we got the shift systems coming in the employers secretary of course used to abuse me quite a lot about it and used to say it's your business to tell them what they've got to do, you see that kind of - I said, no, no, I said, I - I can't do that.
 I said, I'll put both sides to them very, very fairly, I'll tell them for and against and I said then they must make -
