w
ays be a lot of things about the town council which was a good thing because now I feel that local government its always more or less forgotten - its pushed in the background. And then the Socialists were always there. There was always a - a Socialist spe
a
ker and it would go on 'til very dark, you see, the evenings would grow dark and that went on for a long, long time. And then, you see, one of the councilors suddenly moved that the Town Hall steps would look very much nicer if they had lawns at the side.
 
It was a good idea yet it was a bad one because it broke up the open forum and we never had it again. And they - the - they laid the lawns and the flowers but it put a stop to - these speakers on the steps and people standing round because in those days t
h
ey had no mikes you see just speak and you'd to be rather near so that you heard everything. And I always remember I heard the first - time I ever heard about the prison system in this country from a man who'd been jailed for something he'd either done an
d
 he gave a very, very vivid description of the prisons you see and the routine that went on in them and there was always strange people coming along, you know, with their strange experiences you see. Well, that went you see. Well now its rather interestin
g
 to see that with the precinct they are going to start something again aren't they on the Town Hall step, yes. And I thought they might well say there's nothing new under the sun. There isn't really. But somehow or other - the classes seemed to get more t
o
gether didn't they. They seemed to me anyway, to get more together in those days than they do now and - I hope something comes out of the precinct along that line if only to compare it - compare it with the old days, you see. 'Course there weren't as many
 
newspapers - people didn't read the same and of course there was no radio or television so that open air gatherings were one source of gathering information, you see, which of course we don't need now because of the telly and the - the radio, that kind of
