\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would you say that all classes of society were represented amongst the throng at these meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I wouldn't say they all were because, of course, the - the better educated and the - the - the aristocratic side would - would think i
t a bit low to go standing on the Town Hall square listening to an orator, you see. No, I don't think they would be there at all. Because I - I can remember when we used to go round with the Clarion we used to have meetings - at some - usually at Rivingto
n
 - we had it on the Rivington Green, you see, and whilst people came out from the cottages and people who were rambling and that came we used to see the disdain written on the faces of some of the people to think that we were desecrating the village air, 
y
ou know, with talking like Socialism and the outcasts and all the rest of it so that I shouldn't think that it did represent the aristocratic circle - they - they would never dream of doing anything so vulgar, you see, as standing at street corners - eith
e
r shouting or - or giving out literature, you see. No, I don't think they did really. But, they were a help to people who were seeking information, you see, on topics of local government and things because you see you used to get all sorts of people compl
a
ining about the state of the streets - the rents of houses being too high and all sorts of things that otherwise you wouldn't have got to know, you see, they came out in those - if they had a grievance, you see, they - they up and told the speaker about i
t
, and then he would say - he might - he might have been a councilor himself - there used to be quite a number of councilors speak - and he would say oh well, the next council meeting I'll raise that point, you see. Whether he did and there was anything de
v
eloped from it of course I wouldn't know, but it was an opportunity. No, I think the classes were separate. Even thought today they're separate aren't they to some extent. But not - not so much - not so much divided as they were then - sharply divided I m
ean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Was there any social mobility at all in those days?
