Movements, you mean? Not a lot. You see, when you moved into a house, our neighbourhood, in my circle I mean, you stayed there until you died really, you very rarely moved. Well, now of cou
rse there's much more mobility you see. You'd never dream of - well, I don't think we should ever have dreamed of moving from the town until it came that they were building council houses and then you see we applied for one and got one on the outskirts of
 
the town and it was the first time we'd ever had any fresh air or a garden, you see. And - I know I can remember as a child my three ambitions were to - one, to have a bicycle, two to have a piano and three to have a garden and I was twenty-one before I g
o
t any of them. But - you see, you didn't move around - you stayed in this - in the same circle really and - now you see they're really having to demolish the slums almost against the wishes of quite a lot of the tenants you see, because of course it break
s
 - it breaks the community to some extent. My mother, when we moved to - from Fern Street up to this corporation house - council house - she looked forlornly out of the window and I thought it was wonderful because there was a lark singing and I'd never h
eard a lark sing and it was trilling away in the sky and she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 gazing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 out and she turned to me and she says - what's bought me up here fore, there's now but cocks and hens? You see, the difference, you see, the kind of separation of the generations. Back 
street and the front street and gossiping and shops - that was her world and we'd moved her from it, you see, and - she never really settled down - never really. She - she made the best of it for my sake, you see, but never really settled down. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 And she - I
 used to take her to the park a lot - we had a park very near us - and I used to leave her sitting in the park on summer days whilst I went to the office and she would tell me afterwards that she'd get sit chatting with people on the - she could chat to s
trangers, you see - there was no inhibition there about talking to strangers - and she - they would tell me afterwards that - said - eeh, your mother does think you're wonderful. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
She said, we were grumbling about this, that and the other and we were saying 
this ought to be done and that ought - and she says - I'll tell our Alice and they'll send a letter up paper. She had - she had great ideas how you could put things right by sending a letter to the paper - the Evening News. But - there's a lot more mobili
t
y and of course I think it's a good thing really it's a good thing. But we suffered from it, you see, we suffered from the lack of mobility because you were tied to the job, you see. You were tied more or less to the one shop who you went to and you were 
t
ied to the one school and - you - you didn't change schools and you - you - you didn't change much at all, you see, you grew up in that traditional fashion, you see, and it wasn't until you get much older and then you can compare that you begin to see tha
t there is something - a good deal to be said for mobility.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
You described your community as a close knit one and people helping one another when they were ill and so on - did people come to help your mother on any occasion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, they were alway
s friendly but they were always rather afraid of father and they would bob in - put their head round the door and have a good look and if he was in they'd decamp. But if - if she wanted sort of any - anything doing they were always ready and willing to co
m
e you see. She did most of the going and the doing, but there was a responsiveness that if there was a need there and you told them about it they would help. She was - very hesitant about ever asking anybody and I never heard her, in the whole of my life,
 ever ask for a penny piece off anybody. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 
You see, a number of them they would go down to the guardians if they were pretty des - destitute, you see, they would go down to the guardian and plead poverty and perhaps get a little bit of help, but she never would. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
She thought it was rather degrading and she would rather fight her own way you see. But it was a helpful community in that sense, that you all stood by one another and if anybody got prosecuted for anything well it all went round the neighbourhood and 
if you could help by having a little collection towards a fine or anything like that it was done you see. But there was a community sense that you don't have now, you don't have nowadays. Because people are - well, they're more prosperous and, whilst they
 invite you in - into the house - there's not the same homely community, you see, that there was. Not the same 'Course people rely more now on the social services, you see, don't they for everything and so that's - that's gone by the board really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Do you know much about what went on in the other social classes in Bolton about that period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Well, I think there was a - in the better class - in think there was a genuine liberal feeling that things were wrong - that there was too big a gap, you know, b
etween them and the fairly cultural standard living and ours, you see, in the backstreets and that kind of thing because I - there was - there were quite a lot of charities and they were always supported by the people who - the better class people, you se
e
, and whilst I used to be - feel a bit cynical bout it - because of my experiences in the mill and that kind of thing - I think at the roots there was some genuine feeling for it, you see, and when I joined Bank Street Chapel, which was later on - they we
r
e nearly all fairly - fairly well off quite a lot of - of aristocrats of Bolton. They nearly always had the mayor - the mayors nearly all came from Bank Street for quite a period - Liberal Mayors you see, and - there was a feeling that, I suppose in their
 
way they felt things were unevenly distributed, you see, and I know they had some very, very good classes. There was one man who took the men and he had a class of probably about thirty men and - didn't show any sort of feeling that he was superior to the
s
e other chaps that were coming to the class - the Sunday school class, you see, so that - I've grown a little bit more charitable towards them - my mind used to be on, yes, they go and live on the outskirts of the town and they had nice houses and nice ga
rdens and they don't care two hoots about us living in these backstreets, you see, they're indifferent to us. But perhaps that was a little bit harsh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 criticism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  because a lot of them were mill owners and that was what made me a bit critical about them you se
e, they were making huge profits out of the cotton industry and not distributing it as fairly as they could have done by either shortening hours or providing facilities, so I was inclined to be very critical of quite a lot of these people, you see, who ca
me to talk to us. You know, about what we ought to do, you know, in the name of religion and that kind of thing. This was at Bank Street, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 When was it that you started going to Bank Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well - it must have been after the - after the Sund
ay school closed - the Socialist Sunday school closed down. It must have been, probably the 1930's because by then you see I'd become a bit cultural, you see, as I told you' I'd started going to operas and good music and became a subscriber to the Halle C
o
ncerts in Manchester and of course began to think I knew a little bit you see. Well, the thing that attracted me to Bank Street was that the - there was an announcement in the Evening News that the minister at that time I think it was Mr Flower, was going
 to give a series of articles on Dante's inferno and that might have been a reaction from my early days because after they said that this brother of ours might have gone to hell I'd no use for hell at all. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 As a child I was always terrified of it and the - t
hey threw it at you in those days, you see, very forcibly and al - always you see I had a strange ideal that - the - the body was - the soul would - we were always being told - told about the soul and I had the childish idea that the soul was a kind of wh
i
te and I imagined it a shoulder of lamb, wasn't it funny, in your inside and this was all white and when you did anything wrong you got great big black marks on it and that was sin, you see, and hell I - I was so horrified that I could hardly contemplate 
it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
It was so utterly cruel - because you see they taught us that even unbaptised babies went to hell and I was so near being not baptised that I thought about all these went to hell I was so near being not baptised that I thought about all these things you
 see and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 purgatory}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
 I pictured as it was a kind of lake - a kind - serene lake where the souls swam about in this - lake and waited until it was their day and time to enter paradise you see. And when I - I'd heard of Dante, but only heard, I'd never read 
anything about him - and when I heard that these lectures were being given I thought - eeh, I'll go to this chapel. So I stalked to this chapel, and in those days it was always packed, I had to go in the gallery I remember because it was packed. And it - 
t
hey were marvelous lectures on Dante and the different circles he went into, you see, and - that started me interested in Bank Street, because later on he began to talk and give series of lectures on Thomas Hardy's Jude the Obscure and the things that I h
a
d read so I kept on going for quite a while - not as a member just as - just going Sunday evenings and then somebody asked me to join the choir. Somebody who'd been in a choir that I'd previously been in and so I was more or less roped into this choir and
 
I've been at Bank Street ever since. And - but that was how - how I got going. Well, there was a lot, as I say, of very rich people going then - very rich. And - I did feel a grievance against them you see. They were always very nice, very polite but they
 
at that time had two congregations - the morning congregation was the toffs and the evening congregation were the - also rans. And it was - there was a sharp division there you see. But gradually, of course, quite a lot of these wealthy people either died
 
or left Bolton, you see, as they retired they went to the - Devon and lovely places and the middle class more or less came in and the - unfortunately, more of the working class left, you see, it wasn't their cup of tea and - it's now, I would say, more or
 
less a middle class - a middle class organisation - or at leas they think they are, they think they are, you see. They've been lifted up from probably very poor surroundings and - they've got better jobs, their children have been better educated and that 
k
ind of thing. They - they were very shocked, you see, when somebody asked me to give some parts of my life story, at the Women's League you see, and when I started off with this business of Shaw Street and Milk Street they were - they were rather horrifie
d
 to think that you talked about those things - you shouldn't talk about them there, you see. And that - those are sordid parts of life but it's better not to refer to, you see, that was their attitude, you see. So I only got up to being about twelve years
 
of age and - I - I didn't sort of go on with it. Several people have said, oh you ought to have done, it was very interesting. But you could tell, you could sense their kind of reaction - reaction to it, you see, that - well, you didn't - you didn't do qu
i
te that kind of thing, you see, you hid those things, you never told people you'd worked in a mill -it was a bit, you know, you presented that you'd gone to Bolton higher grade school even if you hadn't you see, but - you shut your eyes on those other par
ts of it you see, rather vulgar.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Would you say there were two or three classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 
Oh there were three. Yes. Definitely three. The aristocrats we never came in touch with. The real moneyed people were hardly - I don't think we ever - they ever touc
hed our life. The middle class just occasionally by as I say, the court and alley concerts, that kind of thing. They were more middle class people you see, who ran that kind of thing. It was a kind of charity but it was bringing light and culture into the
 
dark places, you see, so they devoted them - selves to that kind of thing - that was the kind of middle group that we had. And then our own group which was of course very consolidated by its poverty. Poverty and its lack of opportunity, you see. We hung t
ogether, really, for kind of safety - kind of safety valve, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11012655 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 What sort of people would the middle class be constituted of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14835199 AF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Well, I should say that some of them were town councilors, you see, who'd got on the council. Others were - members
 of various committees. The Guild of help was very prominent you see in those days and - organizations like that, they - they had a clog fund at Queen Street Mission, you see, for providing clogs for poor children and all that kind of thing. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 Benevolent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  - t
hey were kind of a benevolent group, you see, some - many of them shopkeepers of course, who'd got shops in town and - were making a fairly comfortable living, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 
One or two might have been bankers, you see, who - who were in banks, you see and - they}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11536143  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4265682\charrsid11536143 
thought, well, we have to do some kind of - we ought - we ought, in view our religion, to be some kind of - we ought - we ought, in view of our religion, to be charitable, you see, and do this - do this kind of thing, and they did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143 Now we children used t
o enjoy - the court and alley concert but, you see, when I got older and could discriminate I felt rather ashamed that we lived in housing where they had to come and give us the court and alley concert, you see, it - it impinged later on. You accept this 
a
s children and it's - oh it's lovely - it's part of your life you know, and we used to go pushing this - this truck with the piano on, you know, we had the time of our life. But later on I - I began to wonder why - why the court and alley concerts coming 
i
n this neighbourhood, you see, oh, we must be very poor, you see, to have a court and alley concert. Then the - the Victoria Hall started its penny concerts and we all drifted there. A marvelous concerts you know - a penny and then it went up to tuppence 
a
nd finally it was about sixpence 'til they - they died out but they were marvelous concerts. So we always used to go there on Saturday night, you know, it was champion going in there for a penny or tuppence. And we used to crowd, of course, into the tempe
r
ance hall when the first movie pictures came, you know, and those dreadful things, you know, to be continued in our next - you know, always left the heroine hanging over a cliff, you see, and we had to wait a week to see whether the poor creature - 'cours
e either murdered or revived - saved, you see. That was the kind of thing, you see, that we had for our entertainments, you see, we didn't go places only just that kind of thing. Parading in the market hall - there the boys and girls led}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204880\charrsid11536143  down}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6489771\charrsid11536143  the centre ais
le as a parade, you see, and the girls marched up one side and the boys down the other, you know, making glad eyes at each other - things like that you see, where - where - were your amusements and outlets.
